{"title_page": "Stand-up comedy", "text_new": "{{redirect2|Stand-up|Stand Up Comedy|the U2 song|Stand Up Comedy (song)|other uses|Stand Up (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Ahmed Mamow Parkteatret (231834).jpg|thumb|Ahmed Mamow on the stage at Late Night Fredag on Parkteatret]]\n\n'''Stand-up comedy''' is a [[Comedy|comic]] style in which a [[comedian]] performs in front of a live audience, usually speaking directly to them. The performer is commonly known as a '''comic''', '''stand-up comic''', '''comedian''', '''comedienne''', '''stand-up comedian''', or simply a '''stand-up'''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Fisher, J ''Tommy Cooper: Always Leave Them Laughing'' {{ISBN|978-0-00-721511-9}}</ref> Comedians give the illusion that they are [[dialogue|dialoguing]], but in actuality, they are [[monologue|monologuing]] a grouping of humorous [[narrative|stories]], [[jokes]] and [[one-line joke|one-liners]], typically called a [[shtick]], routine, [[Performer|act]], or set.{{refn| <ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=https://www.thehistoryofstandup.com/episodes/s2-ep-06-meltdown\n | title=S2 Ep. 06: Meltdown\n | website=The History of Standup\n | publisher=The Podglomerate\n | host=[[Wayne Federman]]\n | others=[[Dana Gould]]\n | date=9 July 2019\n | time=21:40-21:54\n | access-date=27 August 2019\n | quote=A low ceiling and proximity to the stage is important because standup comedy is not a performance. It is a conversation in which the comedian does all of the talking.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andreamorris/2018/07/26/a-robot-stand-up-comedian-learns-the-nuts-and-bolts-of-comedy/\n |title=A Robot Stand-Up Comedian Learns The Nuts And Bolts Of Comedy\n |last=Morris\n |first=Andrea\n |date=26 July 2018\n |website=Forbes\n |publisher=Forbes Media LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=[A lot of] stand-up comedy\u2026as a general art form\u2026is pre-scripted}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/16 16]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Jerry Seinfeld explains: \u2018Comedy is a dialogue, not a monologue\u2014that\u2019s what makes an act click. The laughter becomes the audience\u2019s part, and the comedian responds\u2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Stewart Lee\n | date =3 July 2013\n | title =On Not Writing\n | medium =YouTube\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IrXVaytvJtQ\n | access-date =13 February 2019\n | format =Lecture\n | time =48:54-48:58\n |location=St Edmund Hall\n | publisher =University of Oxford\n | quote =On the whole, you have to give the illusion that it\u2019s a dialogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=190\n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/90 90]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=A comic's material about his life may have some connection to reality, but basically an act is just that, an ''act''\u2014it\u2019s a fictionalized account with a few actual facts thrown in to make the act believable and, perhaps, more relevant to people\u2019s lives.}}</ref>}} Some stand-up comedians use [[prop comedy|props]], [[comedy music|music]] or [[Magic (illusion)|magic tricks]]<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Martin\n |first=Steve\n |year=2007\n |title=Born Standing Up: A Comic's Life\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Scribner\n |pages=40\u201342\n |isbn=978-1-4165-5364-9\n |quote=I was demonstrating tricks eight to twelve hours a day\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bornstandingupco00mart\n }}</ref> to enhance their acts. Stand-up comedy is stated to be the \"freest form of comedy writing\" that is regarded as a fictionalized \"extension of\" the person performing.{{refn|<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Jerry Seinfeld\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=199\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=That\u2019s the goal\u2014to become yourself.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Mendrinos\n |first=James\n |year=2004\n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc.\n |page=12\n |isbn=1-59257-231-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://craftsmanship.net/the-art-of-the-joke/\n |title=The Art of the Joke\n |last= Munro\n |first=David\n |year=2018\n |website=CRAFTSMANSHIP Quarterly: The Architecture of Excellence\n |publisher=The Craftsmanship Initiative\n |access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/08/stand-up-comedians-and-their-alternate-on-stage-personas.html\n |title=Stand-Up Comedians and Their Alternate On-Stage Personas\n |last=Evans\n |first=Bradford\n |date=7 August 2012\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/90 90\u201391]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[A stand-up\u2019s] act [is a] fictionalized account with a few actual facts thrown in to make the act believable and, perhaps more relevant to people\u2019s lives...Every stand-up goes onstage as a character to some extent. Some may adopt a persona that\u2019s very similar to their own personality, but it\u2019s still a separate entity...even observational comics...use truth...as a foundation on which to build jokes by taking the truth to its farthest [sic] extreme.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/262\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/262 262]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=(loosely) autobiographical comedy is the dominant form of stand-up today.\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Gary Shandling\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=209\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I [Gary Shandling] think you can only be on stage what you are in real life.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Katzif\n | first        = Mike\n | date         = 16 November 2018\n | title        = Mo Amer: Working The Classroom Comedy Circuit\n | url          = https://www.npr.org/2018/11/16/668601188/mo-amer-working-the-classroom-comedy-circuit\n | work         = NPR\n | access-date  = 11 September 2019\n | quote        = [I]f you're not real\u2026people will sniff that out.}}</ref>}}\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Bridget Christie Parkteatret Crap \u00e5pp\u00e5 Park (181801).jpg|right|thumb|Bridget Christie at Parkteatret. The event is part of Crap Comedy festival 2017 and took place on 28. January 2017 in Oslo.]]\n[[File:Jinx Yeo at restaurant Kaisla.jpg|thumb|right|Jinx Yeo, a [[Singapore]]an stand-up comedian, performing in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]].]]\nSome of the main types of humor in stand-up comedy include [[observational comedy]], [[ribaldry|blue comedy]], [[black comedy|dark comedy]], [[clean comedy]], and [[cringe comedy]].\n[[Alternative comedy|Alternative stand-up comedy]] deviates from the traditional, mainstream comedy by breaking either joke structure, performing in an untraditional scene, or breaking an audience's expectations; this includes the use of [[shaggy dog story|shaggy dog stories]] and [[anti-humor|anti-jokes]].\n\nStand-up comedy is often performed in corporate events, [[comedy club]]s, [[bar]]s and [[pub]]s, [[nightclub]]s, [[Neo-Burlesque|neo-burlesques]], [[college]]s and [[theatre]]s (audiences will give applause breaks more often in theaters<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Louis C.K.\n | date =22 April 2011\n | title =Talking Funny\n | trans-title =\n | medium =Film\n | time =11:55-12:12}}</ref>).<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Chris Dipetta\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/68 68]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=The average club seats [250] people}}</ref> Outside live performance, stand-up is often distributed commercially via [[television]], [[DVD]], [[Compact disc|CD]] and the [[internet]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"signonsandiego.com\">[http://www.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20050624/news_1c24ferrell.html ''Fearless delivery sets Will Ferrell apart.''] ''The Denver Post'', 24 June 2005. Accessed on 29 March 2010.</ref>\n\nIt can take an amateur comedian about 10 years to perfect the technique needed to be a professional comedian;<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=George Wallace\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=240\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=How did you answer them? 'By being [[George Wallace (American comedian)|George Wallace]], and finding out who you are as a comedian. And that takes between seven and eleven years.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Jerry Seinfeld\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=200\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=How long did it take you to figure out your individual comedic essence? 'I'd [Jerry Seinfeld] say ten years.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Louis C.K., Charlie Rose\n | date =7 May 2014\n | title =Louis C.K.\n | medium =TV Show\n | language =English\n | url =https://charlierose.com/videos/19176\n | access-date =3 February 2019\n | format =Interview\n | time =3:59-4:03\n | publisher =HBO\n |quote=A stage presence comes pretty quickly [but] how to write jokes and how to generate material and know it\u2019s going to work; [concerning these, the] first ten years are building the [base] skills}}</ref> this is a constant process of learning through failure.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Bobby Lee (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =1:02:38-1:02:48\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =Bombing is a necessary event. It\u2019s the only way one gets better, but every time it happens, it\u2019s very painful.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = John Thomson (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =1:02:52-1:02:55\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =You\u2019ve got to die to get good.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2014/03/18/hannibal-buress-bombing-can-be-good/\n |title=Hannibal Buress: 'Bombing Can Be Good'\n |last=Seabaugh\n |first=Julie\n |others=Hannibal Buress\n |date=18 March 2014\n |website=The Village VOICE\n |publisher=VILLAGE VOICE, LLC\n |access-date=4 February 2019\n |quote= Yeah, bombing can be good\u2026you grow up and realize it\u2019s about continuing to work. It\u2019s about making progress.}}</ref>\n\nAs the name implies, \"stand-up\" comedians usually perform their material while standing, though this is not mandatory. Similar acts performed while seated can be referred to as \"sit-down comedy\".\n\n\"Comedians are more likely to exhibit psychotic[-like] traits\" than the average person; most comedians display \"magical thinking\" and are \"introverted[ly]\" \"[[Anhedonia|anhedoni[c]]]\".<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/02/the-dark-psychology-of-being-a-good-comedian/284104/\n |title=The Dark Psychology of Being a Good Comedian\n |last=Khazan\n |first=Olga\n |date=27 February 2014\n |website=The Atlantic\n |access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Stand-up comedy show==\n\n[[File:Tiffany Haddish at Incirlik.jpg|thumb|right|Tiffany Haddish, comedian, tells jokes to audience members during a performance October 21, 2013, at Incirlik Air Base, Turkey.]]\n\nIn stand-up comedy, the feedback of the audience is instant and crucial for the comedian's act, even from the moment they enter the venue.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Lee\n |first=Stewart\n |year=2010\n |title=How I Escaped My Certain Fate: The Life and Deaths of a Stand-up Comedian\n |location=London, UK\n |publisher=faber and faber Ltd\n |page=43\n |isbn=978-0-571-25481-1\n |quote=A show begins the moment the audience walk into a venue.}}</ref> Audiences expect a stand-up comedian to provide a constant stream of laughs, calculated at four to six laughs per minute,{{refn|<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Chris Rock (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =11:24-11:31\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =A lot of comedians just want laugh, laugh, laugh\u2026every, what is it, 15 seconds they say?}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/oct/04/learning-laughter-an-experts-guide-on-how-to-master-standup-comedy \n |title=Learning laughter: an expert's guide on how to master standup comedy\n |last=Nevins\n |first=Jake\n |date=4 October 2017\n |website=The Guardian\n |access-date=26 January 2019\n |quote= Comedy club audiences...expect upwards of four laughs per minute.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.realfirststeps.com/4164/jokes-minute-standup-comedy-material/\n |title=How Many Jokes Are In A Minute Of Stand-up Comedy Material?\n |last=Roye\n |first=Steve\n |website=Stand-up Comedy Tips\n |access-date=26 January 2019\n |quote=If a comedian wants to generate headliner laughter levels, they need to average 4-6+ laughs per minute.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/253\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/253 253\u2013254]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=As each comic\u2019s usage of material varies (some say they use as few as two jokes a minute, other comics say they need a laugh every fifteen seconds or the act goes \u2018in the toilet\u2019)}}</ref>}} and a performer is always under pressure to deliver, especially the first two minutes.{{refn|<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Frances-White\n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur\n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Stephen K Amos\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=209\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=The first two minutes is very important with a stand-up}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Pete Lee\n | year =2017\n | title =I Need You To Kill\n | medium =Motion picture\n | time =31:27-31:56\n | publisher =Comedy Dynamics\n | quote =I call the first two minutes, your flash. And that\u2019s where you\u2026go up there and\u2026hook them with whatever material it is, so that they know exactly what\u2019s funny about you and they trust you and they\u2019ll come along with you for everything.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2004/aug/16/edinburgh04.edinburghfestival3\n |title=How can he show his face?\n |last=MacInnes\n |first=Paul\n |date=15 August 2004\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |others=Karen Koren\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote= If you don't make them laugh in the first two minutes, you're fucked}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Neill\n |first=Geoffrey\n |date=22 December 2015\n |title=Hitting Your Funny Bone: Writing Stand-up Comedy, and Other Things That Make You Swear\n |location=San Bernardino, CA\n |page=Chapter 5\n |isbn=9781515180661\n |quote=If you have a strong first minute\u2026the minutes that follow will be great, too.}}</ref>}} The late [[Phyllis Diller]] holds the record for most laughs per minute, at twelve laughs per minute.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote from Phyllis Diller, 'who is listed in ''The Guinness Book of World Records'' as having gotten the most laughs per minute of any comic alive or dead'\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=181\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=I [Phyllis Diller] actually got twelve laughs in one minute from an audience\u2026Most comics do setup, payoff, setup, payoff, in other words six jokes per minute. In my case of twelve, ''one'' setup got ''twelve'' payoffs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last= Gorman\n| first= Steve\n| date= 20 August 2012\n| title= Pioneering comedian Phyllis Diller dies at age 95\n| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainment-us-diller/pioneering-comedian-phyllis-diller-dies-at-age-95-idUSBRE87J0PZ20120821\n| work= Reuters\n| access-date= 28 March 2020\n| quote= Diller prided herself on keeping her jokes tightly written and boasted that she held a world record for getting 12 laughs a minute.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last= King\n| first= Susan\n| date= 22 December 2006\n| title= Diller can still pack a punch line\n| url= https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-dec-22-et-diller22-story.html\n| work= Los Angeles Times\n| access-date= 28 March 2020\n| quote=[Phyllis Diller] still holds the Guinness Book of World Records for doling out 12 punch lines a minute.}}</ref>\n\n===Basic format===\n====Opener, feature, headliner====\nA show begins with an opening act, known as a host, ''[[wikt:Special:search/compere|comp\u00e8re]]'' (UK),<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/1664527.pdf\n |title=Stand-up as interaction: Performance and Audience in Comedy Venues\n |last=Rutter\n |first=Jason\n |year=1997\n |department=Department of Sociology\n |website=CORE\n |publisher=University of Saford: Institute for Social Research\n |pages=149\u2013150\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> [[master of ceremonies]] (MC/emcee), or simply \"opener\" who, for 10\u201312 minutes,<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.malonecomedy.com/blog/10-rules-to-mceeing-a-comedy-show\n |title=8 Rules to Emceeing a Comedy Show\n |last=Malone\n |first=Michael\n |website=Malone Comedy\n |publisher=Wav Records\n |access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> usually warms up the crowd, interacts with audience members, makes announcements, and then introduces the other performers;<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |pages=67\u201368\n |isbn=9781468004847}}</ref> this is followed by a \"middle\"/\"feature\" act that lasts 15\u201320 minutes but is expected to have \"30 minutes of solid material\"; the feature act is followed by the headliner, who performs for \"an hour.\"<ref name=MSU>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=195\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Ron White\n | year =2018\n | title = Ron White: If you Quit Listening, I\u2019ll Shut Up\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.netflix.com/title/80244900\n | access-date =15 April 2020\n | format =Motion Picture\n | time =39:21-39:41\n | quote =[T]raditionally in American comedy clubs, there\u2019s three acts: there\u2019s an opening act...a feature act\u2026and [then] a headliner}}</ref> An opener can also double as a feature for travelling headliners, with the opener performing a 25-minute set.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Martin\n |first=Steve\n |year=2007\n |title=Born Standing Up: A Comic's Life\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Scribner\n |pages=136, 139\n |isbn=978-1-4165-5364-9\n |quote=One week, I opened for a show...I was now capable of doing two different twenty-five-minute sets per evening\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bornstandingupco00mart}}</ref>\n\n====Showcase format====\nShowcase format has a host/MC with several other acts who perform for roughly equal lengths of time.<ref>{{cite book\n|year=2006\n|chapter=A Little Comedy From The Audience: Vic Henley\n|editor1-last=Shydner\n|editor1-first=Ritch\n|editor2-last=Schiff\n|editor2-first=Mark\n|title=I Killed: True Stories of the Road From America\u2019s Top Comics\n|url=http://www.standupstories.com\n|url-status=dead\n|others=[[Vic Henley]]\n|edition=First Paperback\n|location=New York\n|publisher=Three Rivers Press\n|page=222\n|isbn=978-0-307-38229-0\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501193623/http://www.standupstories.com:80/\n|archive-date=1 May 2012\n|access-date=15 April 2020\n|quote=[[The Comedy Store (London)|The Comedy Store in London]]\u2026[is] a showcase format, with a host and five comics doing sets, with\u2026[a] guest thrown in from time to time.}}</ref>\n\n===One-person show===\n{{Main|Solo performance}}\n\nThese one-hour, headlining performances focus on storytelling.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote by Mark Travis\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=213\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=A one-person show has a story line. While a stand-up comic focuses on getting an immediate reaction from the audience after every joke, a person doing a solo show takes the audience on a journey.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote by [[Christopher Titus]]\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=216\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=A one-person show is not just an hour of stand-up. It has to be dramatic ''and'' funny.}}</ref> One-person, stand-up comedy shows became popular in the 1990s, with no consensus for what separates stand-up acts from one-person shows.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/02/theater-review-birbiglias-thank-god-for-jokes.html\n |title=Mike Birbiglia\u2019s New One-Man Show: Stories About Jokes; Jokes About Stories\n |last=Fox\n |first=Jesse David\n |date=28 February 2017\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=28 March 2020\n |quote=Though there have been one-person shows for ages, the first\u00a0comedian\u00a0to do a one-person show in a big way was Lily Tomlin\u2026However, it wasn\u2019t until the \u201890s, correlating with the rise of storytelling, that the stand-up one-person show really blew up\u2026for the shows that consisted of thematically stringing funny stories together, it was always hard to decide what exactly made them one-man shows and not stand-up acts.}}</ref>\n\n===Open mic===\n{{Main|Open mic}}\n\nMany smaller venues hold open mic events, where anyone can take the stage and perform for the audience. This offers an opportunity for amateur performers to hone their craft and perhaps to break into the profession, or for established professionals to work on their material.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.pattonoswalt.com/index.cfm?page=spew&id=167\n |title=A Closed Letter to Myself About Thievery, Heckling and Rape Jokes\n |last=Oswalt\n |first=Patton\n |date=14 June 2014\n |website=Patton Oswalt\n |publisher=Patton Oswalt\n |access-date=3 February 2019\n |quote=Open mikes are where, as a comedian [like Daniel Tosh and his controversy], you\u2019re supposed to be allowed to fuck up.}}\n</ref> Industry scouts will sometimes go to watch open mics.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://saraschaefer.com/2012/03/advice-to-a-young-comedian-myself/\n |title=Advice to a Young Comedian (& Myself)\n |last=Schaefer\n |first=Sara\n |date=16 March 2012\n |website=Sara Schaefer\n |access-date=1 February 2019\n |quote=the next day, my friend who was also on the show [in a theatre above a porn shop across from the Port Authority], told me a scout from casting at Fox was in the audience and they wanted to meet with him.}}</ref> Breaking into the business requires \"10 minute[s]\" of \"A\" material. Roadhouses (remote clubs) start booking people for \"20 minutes of 'A' material\".<ref name=MSU /> \"A\" material means getting a big laugh at least \"75% of the time\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=197\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref>\n\n===Bringer shows===\n\"Bringer shows\" are open mics that require amateur performers to bring a specified number of paying guests to receive stage time. Some view this as exploitation, while others disagree.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/correspondents/2012/09/10/16114/what_do_bringer_shows_really_bring_to_the_circuit%3F\n |title=What do 'bringer' shows REALLY bring to the circuit?\n |last=Dunican\n |first=Angus\n |date=10 September 2012\n |website=Chortle\n |access-date=28 January 2019\n |quote=it gets tarred with the brush of new-act exploitation and lumped in with less scrupulous nights and the insidious blight of pay-to-play...[but] I, personally, have found it to be a very nice room.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/article/how-to-quit-your-job-get-into-comedy.html\n |title=I Want Out How to Leave the Boring Job You Don't Like and Start Your Comedy Career\n |last= Kelly-Clyne\n |first=Luke\n |date=20 September 2018\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=\n |quote= In order to get stage time at [bringer shows]\u2026you [have to] bring\u20265 to 15 friends, each of whom must show up and agree to buy at least two drinks\u2026Some people think bringers are a scam, and they kind of are. They\u2019re a cash grab for club owners}}</ref> The guests usually have to pay a cover charge and there is often a minimum number of drinks that must be ordered. These shows usually have a \"showcase\" format. Different comedy clubs have different requirements for their bringer shows. Gotham Comedy Club in New York City, for example, usually has ten-person bringers, while Broadway Comedy Club in New York City usually has six-person bringers.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.jimrichardson.com/stand-upcomedyworkshop.com/audition/bringerShows.html\n |title=Evil \"Bringer Shows\" & \"Pay-to-Play Shows\" Are even worse Than the already discredited Open Mic system\n |last=Richardson\n |first=Jim\n |date=11 December 2013\n |website=Jim Richardson's Organized Comedy\n |access-date=28 January 2019\n |quote=Some clubs require 10 bringers/show. If you show up with 9 people, you will not get on and your friends will not get their money back.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/24/arts/my-brief-weird-life-as-a-stand-up-comic.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=My Brief, Weird Life as a Stand-Up Comic\n |last=Strauss\n |first=Neil\n |date=24 January 1999\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |access-date=2 February 2019\n |quote=Clubs like Caroline's will ask for 15 people.}}</ref> In the '90s, the New York Comedy Club had pre-shows that were bringer shows; they also had audition scams with an \"accelerated pre-show program.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/24/arts/my-brief-weird-life-as-a-stand-up-comic.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=My Brief, Weird Life as a Stand-Up Comic\n |last=Strauss\n |first=Neil\n |date=24 January 1999\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |access-date=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Guest set===\nThis is an unpaid, five-to-ten-minute time slot (during the emcee's time slot of a professional show) that is essentially an audition to get booked for paid gigs.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=63\n |isbn=9781468004847}}</ref>\n\n==The comedian's set==\n===Stand-up joke===\nIn stand-up comedy, a \"canned\" [[joke]]<ref>{{cite book\n |editor=Salvatore Attardo\n |year=2014\n |title=Encyclopedia of Humor Studies\n |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AXtZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA417&dq=%22canned+joke%22#v=onepage&q=%22canned%20joke%22&f=false\n |publisher=SAGE Publications, Inc.\n |page=417\n |isbn=978-1-4129-9909-0\n |quote=A canned joke is a generally short narrative ending in a punchline\u2026[that] the speaker has memorized.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/1664527.pdf\n |title=Stand-up as interaction: Performance and Audience in Comedy Venues\n |last=Rutter\n |first=Jason\n |year=1997\n |department=Department of Sociology\n |website=CORE\n |publisher=University of Saford: Institute for Social Research\n |pages=188\u2013189\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> is made of a \"[[premise]]...[[Point of view (philosophy)|point of view]]\" and \"[[subversion|twist]]\" ending.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Mendrinos \n |first=James \n |year=2004 \n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc. \n |page=46 \n |isbn=1-59257-231-6\n |quote=[T]he Universal Joke Formula: Premise + Point of View + Twist = Joke}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |page=104\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=we can craft a joke just by creating and then defeating that specific expectation...introduction, validation, violation}}</ref> A joke contains the least amount of information necessary to be conveyed, understood, and laughed at;<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://archive.org/details/psychologyofhumo00martrich\n |title=The Psychology of Humor: An Integrative Approach\n |last=Martin\n |first=Rod A.\n |year=2007\n |orig-year=2006\n |department=Department of Psychology: University of Western Ontario\n |website=Internet Archive\n |publisher=Burlington, MA : Elsevier Academic Press\n |location=Ontario, Canada\n |page=2\n |type=Interactive Online Book\n |isbn=978-0123725646\n |access-date=18 February 2019\n |quote=a joke is a context-free and self-contained unit of humor that carries within itself all the information needed for it to be understood and enjoyed.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Neill\n |first=Geoffrey\n |date=22 December 2015\n |title=Hitting Your Funny Bone: Writing Stand-up Comedy, and Other Things That Make You Swear\n |location=San Bernardino, CA\n |page=Chapter 4\n |isbn=9781515180661\n |quote=A setup is the information a person needs to get the joke.}}</ref> the setup contains the information needed by the audience in order to understand the punchline.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=126\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0\n |quote=The setup is the essential information the audience needs in order to get the punchline}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=14\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5\n |quote=A joke\u2026must have all the information implicit in the setup, so\u2026the punchline\u2026makes sense.}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=https://www.letstalkaboutsets.com/048/\n | title=Episode 48 The Setup\n | website=Let\u2019s Talk About Sets\n | host=Jeff McBride, Harrison Tweed\n | others=Geoffrey Asmus\n | time=12:45-13:05\n | access-date=29 August 2019\n | quote=It\u2019s the first half of the joke\u2026It\u2019s the first part\u2026I\u2019ve seen it said that it\u2019s the part that gives all the information you need, so that people understand the joke, but I would take it a step a little bit to the side of that\u2026[the setup] is whatever is needed to make the joke work.}}</ref> Most of stand-up comedy's jokes are the [[Theories of humor#Incongruous juxtaposition theory|juxtaposition of two incongruous things]].{{refn|<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Mendrinos \n |first=James \n |year=2004 \n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy \n |others=Bret Watson \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc. \n |page=51 \n |isbn=1-59257-231-6 \n |quote=It seems like 99% of comedy comes from juxtaposing two things that don't seem to go together}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n |url=https://www.standupcomedyclinic.com/powerful-tool-joke-writing/ \n |title=The Most Powerful Tool for Your Joke Writing \n |last=Corley \n |first=Jerry \n |website=standupcomedyclinic \n |access-date=27 January 2019 \n |quote=You turn it into a juxtaposition of two ideas and create jokes.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://archive.org/details/psychologyofhumo00martrich\n |title=The Psychology of Humor: An Integrative Approach\n |last=Martin\n |first=Rod A.\n |year=2007\n |orig-year=2006\n |department=Department of Psychology: University of Western Ontario\n |website=Internet Archive\n |publisher=Burlington, MA : Elsevier Academic Press\n |location=Ontario, Canada\n |page=85\n |type=Interactive Online Book\n |isbn=978-0123725646\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/1664527.pdf\n |title=Stand-up as interaction: Performance and Audience in Comedy Venues\n |last=Rutter\n |first=Jason\n |year=1997\n |department=Department of Sociology\n |website=CORE\n |publisher=University of Saford: Institute for Social Research\n |page=17\n |access-date=8 March 2019\n |quote= Incongruity has been and remains the most influential approach to the study of humour even though superiority predates it by approximately two thousand years.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Luu\n| first        = Chi\n| date         = 12 June 2019\n| title        = The Dubious Art of the Dad Joke\n| url          = https://daily.jstor.org/the-dubious-art-of-the-dad-joke/\n| work         = JSTOR\n| publisher  = ITHAKA\n| access-date  = 15 June 2019\n|quote = At its core, humor seems to be all about incongruity.}}</ref>}} According to the founding editor of [[The Onion]], there are eleven types of jokes.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://bigthink.com/stephen-johnson/every-joke-falls-in-one-of-these-11-categories-according-to-the-founder-of-the-onion\n |title=Every Joke Falls in One of 11 Categories, Says Founding Editor of The Onion\n |last=Johnson\n |first=Stephen\n |date=24 March 2017\n |website=Big Think\n |publisher=The Big Think, Inc. \n |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref> Stand-up comedians will normally deliver their jokes in the form of a [[Joke#Telling jokes|typical joke structure]], using [[comic timing|comedic timing]] to deliver the setup and then the [[punch line]].<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=1 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> Stand-ups will normally frame their stories as having happened \"recently.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://mentalfloss.com/article/88012/11-wisecracking-secrets-stand-comedians\n |title=11 Wisecracking Secrets of Stand-Up Comedians\n |last= Raga\n |first=Suzanne\n |date=27 October 2016\n |website=Mental Floss\n |publisher=Minute Media\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=[C]omedians will often say that something happened to them recently when it really happened years ago\u2014or may have never happened at all.}}</ref> The comedian's delivery of a joke\u2014the pause, inflection, \"ener[gy],\" and look\u2014is \"everything\".<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =George Carlin, Charlie Rose\n | date =26 March 1996\n | title =George Carlin\n | medium =TV Show\n | language =English\n | url =https://charlierose.com/videos/19176\n | access-date =1 February 2019\n | format =Interview\n | time =7:29-7:37\n | publisher =HBO\n}}</ref> Comedians often include taglines (dependent punchlines that follow another punchline)<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=38\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=Taglines are...very short [jokes that are]...delivered right as the original laughter from the punchline is dying down.}}</ref> and toppers (independent afterthoughts that follow a punchline).<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Mendrinos \n |first=James \n |year=2004 \n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy \n |others=Bret Watson \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc. \n |page=93 \n |isbn=1-59257-231-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=61 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> \nSome sources may use tags, toppers, and afterthoughts as synonyms.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://nakedspeaker.com/2010/09/24/writing-for-stand-up-part-3-refining-jokes/\n |title=Writing for stand up part 3: Refining Jokes\n |author=Andrew\n |date=24 September 2010\n |website=thenakedspeaker: a public speaking blog\n |publisher=WordPress\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nA jokoid is a placeholder joke, which will eventually be superseded by a funnier joke.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |page=106\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=A jokoid fills the place on the page where a genuinely funny joke will eventually go}}</ref> Stock jokes are similar to jokoids (as placeholders) and are hack jokes that are for \"specific situations\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=36\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=Stock jokes are jokes that a comic has...that are pretty much hack jokes used for specific situations...they should only be used in certain situations until you can think of something better.}}</ref> A [[paraprosdokian]] is a popular method that is used by comedians, creating a surprising punchline that causes the listener to reinterpret the setup.<ref>{{cite book\n|last1=Leighton\n|first1=H. Vernon\n|year=2020\n|chapter=A Theory of Humor (Abridged) and the Comic Mechanisms of John Kennedy Toole\u2019s \u2018\u2019A Confederacy of Dunces\u2019\u2019\n|editor-last=Marsh\n|editor-first=Leslie\n|title=Theology and Geometry: Essays on John Kennedy Toole\u2019s A Confederacy of Dunces (Politics, Literature, & Film)\n|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Theology_and_Geometry/BjHNDwAAQBAJ?gbpv=0\n|location=United Kingdom\n|publisher=Lexington Books\n|publication-date= 29 January 2020\n|pages=2-4\n|isbn=978-1-4985-8547-7\n|access-date=27 March 2020\n|quote=it is useful to examine the famous paraprosdokian, \u2018I\u2019ve had a perfectly wonderful evening, but this wasn\u2019t it.\u2019\u2026Within the cognitive incongruity aspect of humor\u2026Comedians often rely on shared knowledge with the audience to provide the second interpretation toward which the joke will pivot\u2026As the paraprosdokian above illustrates, in some humor events, the brain begins tentatively to assign the event of one interpretation but then is forced in surprise to reassign the event to a second interpretation.}}</ref> Stand-ups will often use the [[rule of three (writing)|rule of three]].<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =[[Simon Amstell]], [[Eddie Izzard]]\n | year =2011\n | title =The Art of Stand-Up\n | medium =TV\n | language =English\n | location =United Kingdom\n | publisher =BBC: One\n | quote =Simon Amstell states, 'I transcribed a couple of the tapes just to figure out what he [Eddie Izzard] was doing cause it just seemed so (pause) It wasn\u2019t like setup-punch. I would sort of underline words\u2026is that the rule of three? I don\u2019t know what ''that'' is.' Eddie Izzard states, 'it should be\u2014establish, reaffirm, and then you kill it on the third...you can keep reaffirming before you twist.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Hannibal Buress, Marcus Raboy\n | date =2014\n | title =Live from Chicago \n | medium =Audio\n | publisher =COMEDY CENTRAL\n | quote =They have a parades department. New Orleans police department has a parades department. There\u2019s homicide, there\u2019s narcotics, and there\u2019s parades. There\u2019s other departments too, but you know, rule of three, for comedy.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/151 151]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |quote=[Three is the] cadence [that makes] it the most important number in comedy.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/151\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |pages=123\u2013124\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5}}</ref> Comedians will normally include [[stylistic device|stylistic]] and [[comedic device|comedic]] devices, such as [[Figure of speech#Tropes|tropes]], [[idioms]], [[stop consonant]]s, and [[List of forms of word play|wordplay]].<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/63 63]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/63\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/249\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/249 249]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Seinfeld adds, \u2018any k sound is good\u2014it\u2019s a very strong letter that impinges on people.'\n }}</ref>\n\nA comedian's ideas and jokes will fail nine times out of ten; this may require a comedian to write hundreds of jokes to achieve enough successful ones to fill a set.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |pages=12\u201313\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=For every ten jokes you tell, nine will be trash\u2026you\u2019ll need hundreds and hundreds of failed jokes to build a decent body of work.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Louis C.K., Charlie Rose\n | date =7 May 2014\n | title =Louis C.K.\n | medium =TV Show\n | language =English\n | url =https://charlierose.com/videos/19176\n | access-date =3 February 2019\n | format =Interview\n | time =2:20-2:38\n | publisher =HBO\n |quote=failure is the road to being a great comic\u2026failure is not succeeding in the moment}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/109 109]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |quote=For every ten jokes written, only one might be acceptable\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/109\n }}</ref>\n\n===The set===\nA traditional set is made of jokes (setup and punchline), bits (a joke or \"3 or 4 jokes\"), and chunks (multiple bits linked by a topic that may last \"10-15 minutes\").<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.goldcomedy.com/resources/put-together-five-minute-set/ \n |title=How to Write a 5-Minute Comedy Set \n |last=WAITHE \n |first=ELSA \n |website=Gold Comedy \n |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Craig Anton\n | date =28 January 2010\n | title =I Am Comic\n | medium =film\n | time =3:42-4:53\n | publisher =IFC Films\n | quote =a bit, 3 or 4 jokes in and around one central theme or idea\u2026[and then] 10-15 minutes, we call that a chunk}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Abby Stein\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/248\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/248 248]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=A \u2018bit,\u2019 Reiser explains, \u2018is a group of words used to incorporate a premise and all variations thereof\u2019\n }}</ref> Long bits must have the biggest laugh at their endings.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/magazine/100000001965963/jerry-seinfeld-how-to-write-a-joke-.html?action=click&contentCollection=magazine&module=lede&region=caption&pgtype=article\n |url-access=limited\n |title=Jerry Seinfeld: How to Write a Joke\n |last=Woodward\n |first=Jenny\n |date=20 December 2012\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=New York Times Company\n |format=video\n |access-date=1 February 2019\n |quote=If you have a long bit, the biggest laugh has to be at the end. It has to be. It can't be in the middle or the beginning.}}</ref> \nOnce a setup is established for a bit, the subsequent jokes should decrease in length.<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/245 245]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |quote=Since the setup has already been established, the second, third, and fourth jokes are short, shorter, shortest.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/245\n }}</ref>\nA segue is the link between jokes.<ref name=\"Dean 2000 187\">{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=187 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=111\u2013112 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0}}</ref> \nA callback is a reference to a previous joke.<ref name=\"Dean 2000 187\"/><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=112\u2013114, 118 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=53\n |isbn=9781468004847}}</ref> Bombing refers to when a comedian has failed to get an intended laugh.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=190 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> A stand-up comedian uses a [[persona]] or [[Character (arts)|character]] to deliver their jokes.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/91 91]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Every stand-up goes onstage as a character to some extent. Some may adopt a persona that\u2019s very similar to their own personality, but it\u2019s still a separate entity\u2014a person telling jokes as opposed to telling the truth, which no \u2018real\u2019 person does. Even observational comics, who base their material in reality, use the truth not as an end but as a foundation on which to build jokes by taking the truth to its farthest [sic] extreme.}}</ref> The quality of a comedian's material is more important than their persona,<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Budd Friedman\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=261\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=[W]hat\u2019s more important, material or delivery? I had to say it\u2019s the material.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Budd Friedman\n | date =28 January 2010\n | title =I Am Comic\n | medium =film\n | time =31:25-31:34\n | publisher =IFC Films\n | quote =when the material is good, you can overlook anything}}</ref> unless they are well known.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/science-news/8496960/Why-comedians-get-laughs-for-even-their-worst-jokes.html\n |title=Why comedians get laughs for even their worst jokes\n |last=Alleyne\n |first=Richard\n |date=6 May 2011\n |website=The Telegraph\n |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=We argue that using the name of someone who people consider funny generates an expectancy of humour when hearing a joke.}}</ref> Other sources say that personality trumps material.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Irvin Arthur\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=274\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I [Irvin Arthur] firmly believe that it\u2019s the persona first, and then the material.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Abby Stein\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/252\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/252 252]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[P]ersonality is far more important than material\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote from Johnny Carson, quoted from ''The Great Comedians'', by Larry Wilde (1972)\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=162\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=Your delivery can save you if the material isn\u2019t up to par.}}</ref> A good comedian will create a [[Humor in Freud|tendentious-like tension]] that the audience releases with laughter.{{refn|<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Oliver Double\n | year =2011\n | title =The Art of Stand-Up\n | medium =TV\n | language =English\n | location =United Kingdom\n | time =47:23-47:48\n | publisher =BBC: One\n | quote =The classic theorist would be Freud. Tendentious jokes\u2026a difficult or edgy subject is going to create a certain tension in the audience, and having created the tension, if your punchline is funny, the laugh is bigger.\n | editor=Alan Yentob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/24/arts/my-brief-weird-life-as-a-stand-up-comic.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=My Brief, Weird Life as a Stand-Up Comic\n |last=Strauss\n |first=Neil\n |date=24 January 1999\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |access-date=2 February 2019\n |quote=A good standup creates a tension in the room, which the audience wants to break with laughter. If you can do this, any punch line will work as a release valve.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |page=53\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=Every time you start a joke, you create some tension...If the joke works, then all that stored is released at the punchline in the form of laughter.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.humanityinaction.org/knowledgebase/174-when-the-truth-hurts-tell-a-joke-why-america-needs-its-comedians\n |title=When the Truth Hurts, Tell a Joke: Why America Needs Its Comedians\n |last1= Cohen\n |first1=Roger\n |last2= Richards\n |first2=Ryan\n |website=Humanity in Action\n |publisher=Humanity In Action Inc.\n |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>}} This is known as a \"relief/release\" laugh.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Sarah Silverman\n | date =30 May 2017\n | title =Sarah Silverman: A Speck of Dust\n | medium =film\n | time =17:26-17:34\n | quote =I would call that a relief laugh\u2026like release laugh.}}</ref> A comedian's stand-up persona/voice consists of the type of material they perform, the format of the material, the aggregate set, the comedian's rapport with the audience, and the comedian's \"own identity.\"<ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |pages=88\u201389\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=http://www.comedianscomedian.com/67-gary-delaney-live/\n | title=The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith: 67 \u2013 GARY DELANEY (LIVE)\n | website=The Comedian\u2019s Comedian\n | publisher=Stuart Goldsmith\n | host=Stuart Goldsmith\n | date=5 March 2014\n | time=5:00-5:38\n | access-date=3 February 2019\n | quote =You start off, and you want to be like your heroes\u2026you start out under the naive belief that you get to choose your style\u2026[but] your style of comedy chooses you\u2026it's a misnomer when people say you need to think about your persona\u2026its all bollocks about persona and timing. I didn\u2019t set out to be a one-liner comic, but I was shit at everything else.}}</ref>\n\n===Crowd work===\nWhen a set is consistently bombing, most comedians will perform \"crowd work\" by communicating with audience members to [[Face (sociological concept)|save face]]; much of crowd work is prewritten with added [[improvisation]].\n<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Rosenfield \n |first=Stephen \n |year=2018 \n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois \n |publisher=Chicago Review Press \n |pages=66\u201372 \n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref> Some comedians will use small talk that directs audience members to answer \"a question\" that the comedian \"[has] a topper\" for. Other comedians will become more intimate with their questions until they get multiple big laughs, before moving on.\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.comedianscomedian.com/125-dara-o-briain/\n |title=125 \u2013 DARA \u00d3 BRIAIN\n |last=Goldsmith\n |first=Stuart\n |website=The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith\n |access-date=29 January 2019\n |quote=don't stop [your crowd work with a single audience member] until you've got [approximately] 4 big laughs.}}</ref> The result of crowd work is often an [[in-joke|inside joke]].\n\n===Tight five===\nA \"tight five\" is a five-minute stand-up routine that is well-rehearsed and consists of a stand-up comedian\u2019s best material that reliably gets laughs.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/168 168]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=After deciding to become a stand-up\u2026[[Cathy Ladman]] worked to develop \u2018five decent minutes\u2019}}</ref>\nIt is often used for auditions or delivered when audience response is minimal.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.comedyofchicago.com/2013/12/a-tight-five.html\n |title=A Tight Five...\n |last=Maxwell\n |first=Dobie\n |date=December 2013\n |website=Comedy of Chicago\n |access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.goldcomedy.com/resources/put-together-five-minute-set/\n |title=How to Write a 5-Minute Comedy Set\n |last=Waithe\n |first=Elsa\n |date=2017-11-06\n |website=Gold Comedy\n |publisher=Gold Comedy\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=\u2018tight five\u2019 \u2014five minutes of solid go-to jokes that show who you are and reliably get laughs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.realfirststeps.com/599/5-minutes-standup-comedy-material/\n |title=Your First 5 Minutes Of Stand-up Comedy Material\n |last=Roye\n |first=Steve\n |date=26 February 2019\n |website=Real First Steps\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=A tight 5 minutes of stand-up comedy material generates an average 4-6+ collective audience laughs each performing minute.}}</ref> A tight five is the stepping stone to getting a paid spot.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=195\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0\n |quote=If you have an all 'A' [material] 5-minute set, you'll get paid nothing.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/169 169]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[[Fran Capo]] [states that]\u2026an audition is usually five minutes.}}</ref>\n\n===Memory techniques===\nComics memorize their jokes through the use of on-stage practice/blocking.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.jimrichardson.com/stand-upcomedyworkshop.com/audition/memorizingJokes.html\n |title=The physical brain prefers concrete over abstract activities: How to Easily Memorize Your Jokes\n |last=Richardson\n |first=Jim\n |date=29 December 2013\n |website=Jim Richardson's Organized Comedy\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref> Some comedians employ a [[mnemonic]] device called the [[method of loci]] (memory palace technique) to remember their jokes.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nickmorgan/2015/03/05/the-public-speaking-secrets-of-comedians/\n |title=The Public Speaking Secrets Of Comedians\n |last=Morgan\n |first=Nick\n |date=5 March 2015\n |website=Forbes\n |publisher=Forbes Media LLC. \n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=To avoid going blank on stage, use the Memory Palace.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Gary Delaney\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=124\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=I'm currently using memory palaces or I think the loci method}}</ref> Some write their jokes over and over, while others have a set list in front of them; for professionals, this may be on cue cards or a stage monitor.\n<ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Hannibal Buress\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=121\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=I will put a set list on the stage monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last=Rosenfield \n |first=Stephen \n |year=2018 \n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois \n |publisher=Chicago Review Press \n |pages=176\u2013178\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nThe term \"punching down\" is sometimes used to describe jokes that are made at the expense of disenfranchised groups or their members. It carries with it the assumption that comedy should be directed at the powerful rather than the afflicted.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.maskmagazine.com/the-joy-issue/life/stand-up-punch-down\n |url-access=subscription\n |title=a brief history of punch-down comedy\n |last=Cohen\n |first=Sascha\n |website=Mask\n |publisher=Maskmag\n |access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> Claiming one can \"smell the road\" on a comic is a [[pejorative]] phrase for a comedian who has compromised their own originality to get laughs while travelling.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Kris Tinkle, Pete Holmes, W. Kamau Bell\n | date =30 April 2014\n | title =I Am Road Comic\n | medium =Motion Picture\n | time =38:16-38:38\n | publisher =Comedy Dynamics}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Chad Daniels, Louis Lee\n | year =2017\n | title =I Need You To Kill\n | medium =Motion Picture\n | time =1:07:26-1:08:18\n | publisher =Comedy Dynamics}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/69 69]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=George Calfa, who feels that he\u2019s been forced to downplay the degree of real creativity in his act in order to pander to road crowds and bookers}}</ref> Comedian [[Seth Meyers]] coined the term \"clapter\": when an audience cheers or applauds for a joke that they agree with but that is not funny enough to get a laugh.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Sacks\n |first=Mike\n |year=2014\n |title=Poking a Dead Frog: Conversations with Today's Top Comedy Writers\n |location=NY, NY\n |publisher=Penguin Books\n |page=3\n |isbn=978-0-14-312378-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/30-Rock-Tina-Fey-Clarifies-Her-Remark-About-Daily-Show-9612.html\n |title=30 Rock's Tina Fey Clarifies Her Remark About The Daily Show\n |last=West\n |first=Kelly\n |year=2008\n |website=CINEMA BLEND\n |publisher=gateway blend: ENTERTIANMENT\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Heckler===\n{{Main|Heckler}}\n\nIn stand-up, a heckler is a person who interrupts a comedian's set. Comedians will often have a repertoire of [[insult|comebacks]] for hecklers.<ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |others=Jim Jefferies \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=230\u2013231 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0 \n |quote=I have a list of three or four [comebacks]...and the rest will be off the cuff}}</ref> Comedians will sometimes get into physical altercations with hecklers.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/theatreblog/2010/aug/24/heckling-comedy-goes-bad\n |title=When heckling goes bad\n |last=Kettle\n |first=James\n |date=24 August 2010\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |access-date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hack===\n{{Main|Hack (comedy)}}\nA hack is a pejorative term for a comedian with rushed, unoriginal, low-quality, or [[clich\u00e9]] material.{{refn|<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nathansmart.com/akhh.pdf\n |title=The Hack's Handbook: A Starter Kit\n |last=Kindler\n |first=Andy\n |year=2007\n |orig-year=1991\n |publisher=National Lampoon\n |location=Harvard University\n |language=English\n |access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/jmv7b4/how-not-to-be-a-stand-up-comedian\n |title=How Not to Be a Stand-Up Comedian\n |last=Koester\n |first=Megan\n |date=23 April 2013\n |website=Vice\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Schwenson\n |first=Dave\n |year=2005\n |title=COMEDY FAQS AND ANSWERS: HOW THE STAND-UP BIZ REALLY WORKS\n |location=New York, NY\n |publisher=ALLWORTH PRESS\n |page=68\n |isbn=1-58115-411-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |author=Stas Bekman: stas (at) stason.org\n |url=http://stason.org/TULARC/art/hack-stand-up-comedy/\n |title=The Complete Guide To Hack Stand-Up Comedy\n |publisher=Stason.org\n |accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.letstalkaboutsets.com/048/\n| title=Episode 48 The Setup\n| website=Let\u2019s Talk About Sets\n| host=Jeff McBride, Harrison Tweed\n| time=8:35-8:49\n| access-date=29 August 2019\n| quote=One definition of hack is that you [the stand-up comedian] are thinking about what the audience wants instead of what you think is funny\u2026as opposed to being the artist that comes up with something new.}}</ref>}} One proposed amelioration to hackneyed material is an essay by [[George Orwell]] called \"[[Politics and the English Language#Remedy of Six Rules|Politics and the English Language: The Six Rules]]\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=92\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5}}</ref>\n\n===Joke theft===\n{{Main|Joke theft}}\n\nWhen someone is accused of stealing a joke, the accused's defense is sometimes [[cryptomnesia]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2010/11/is-there-eve-a-justification-for-joke-stealing.html\n |title=Is There Ever a Justification for Joke Stealing?\n |last=Voss\n |first=Erik\n |date=4 November 2010\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=12 March 2019}}</ref> or [[parallel thinking]].<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Abby Stein\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/242\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/242 242]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[T]here are also cases of simple coincidence and, often in the case of observational material, parallel thinking.\n }}</ref>\n\n===Warm-up comedian===\n{{Main|Warm-up comedian}}\n\nA [[opening act|warm-up act]] (crowd warmer) performs at comedy clubs, before the filming of a television comedy in front of a studio audience, or the beginning of music concerts to prepare the crowd for the show or main act.\n\n==History of stand-up in Europe==\n\n====British Isles====\n[[File:Max Miller statue.JPG|right|thumb|160px|Bronze statue of Britain's [[Max Miller (comedian)|Max Miller]]]]\n\nEarly twentieth-century '''front-cloth comics''' started in [[Music Hall|music halls]], paving the way for stand-up comedy in Great Britain.<ref name=double>{{cite book\n |last=Double\n |first=Oliver\n |year= 2005\n |title=Getting The Joke: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ePTAwAAQBAJ&dq\n |publisher=A&C Black\n |pages=34, 37\n |isbn=9780413774767\n |quote=[C]omedians like Max Miller, [[Tommy Trinder]], [[Ted Ray (comedian)|Ted Ray]], [[Billy Russell (comedian)|Billy Russell]], [[Suzette Tarri]], [[Beryl Reid]] and [[Frankie Howerd]] performed something which was stand-up comedy in all but name. These performers were known as 'front-cloth comics.' The name derives from the staging of British variety theatre, in which acts which used the full stage\u2014such as sketch comedians who normally used the set\u2014alternated with ones which could be performed in front of the [stage] curtain\u2014the front-cloth comedians\u2026Front-cloth comedy existed at least as early as the 1920s\u2026[British] [f]ront-cloth comedians\u2026[survived] their US equivalents, the monologists, because British variety survived decades longer than American vaudeville\u2026[F]ront-cloth comics on the variety theatres had used catchphrases, costumes and comic personas, their acts fleshed out with songs and even dances}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Hunter\n |first1=I.Q.\n |last2=Porter\n |first2=Laraine\n |year=2012\n |title=British Comedy Cinema\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AIs_PX9-EkYC&dq\n |publisher=Routledge\n |page=\n |isbn= 9781136508370\n |quote=In 1929, he finally settled on [[Frank Randle]] and became a \u2018front-cloth\u2019 comic, performing his character sketch routines.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Double\n |first=Oliver\n |date=19 September 2012\n |title=Britain Had Talent: A History of Variety Theatre\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mz4HCwAAQBAJ\n |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education\n |page=\n |isbn= 9781137265623\n |quote=The line connecting Max Miller to modern comedians such as [[Michael McIntyre]] is by no means unbroken, but the fact is that the very form of stand-up evolved from music hall song, and started life as the front cloth comedy of variety.}}</ref> Notable front-cloth comics who rose through the [[variety show|variety theatre circuit]] were [[Morecambe and Wise]], [[Arthur Askey]], [[Ken Dodd]] and [[Max Miller (comedian)|Max Miller]].<ref>{{cite news\n| author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| date         = 22 March 2018\n| title        = The last of Vaudeville: Ken Dodd died on March 11th\n| url          = https://www.economist.com/obituary/2018/03/22/ken-dodd-died-on-march-11th\n| url-access   = limited\n| work         = The Economist\n| access-date  = 17 August 2019\n| quote        =[Ken Dodd] was the last of the front-cloth comedians, meaning they dropped a cloth behind you while they cleared up the stage from the Liberty Horses and got it ready for the man who pulled doves out of his jacket, and there you were, but with an act that had been burnished until it was a jewel. And he knew he was the last, for all the greats, from Max Miller on, had crossed the boards before him.}}</ref><ref name=double/> Until 1968, the heavy censorship regime of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]] required all comedians to submit their acts for [[censorship]]. The act would be returned with unacceptable sections underlined in blue pencil (possibly giving rise to the term \"blue\" for a comedian whose act is considered bawdy or smutty). The comedian was then obliged not to deviate from the act in its edited form.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nThe rise of the post-war comedians coincided with the rise of television and radio, and the traditional music hall circuit suffered greatly as a result.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} By the 1970s, music hall entertainment was virtually dead. Alternative circuits had evolved, such as [[working men's club]]s.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> Some of the more successful comedians on the working men's club circuit\u2014including [[Bernard Manning]], [[Bobby Thompson (comedian)|Bobby Thompson]], [[Frank Carson]] and [[Stan Boardman]]\u2014eventually made their way to television via such shows as ''[[The Wheeltappers and Shunters Social Club]]''. The \"alternative\" comedy scene also began to evolve. Some of the earliest successes came from [[folk club]]s, where performers such as [[Billy Connolly]], [[Mike Harding]] and [[Jasper Carrott]] started as relatively straight musical acts whose between-song banter developed into complete comedy routines. The 1960s had also seen the satire boom, including the creation of the club, [[The Establishment (club)|the Establishment]], which, amongst other things, gave British audiences their first taste of extreme American stand-up comedy from [[Lenny Bruce]].<ref>\"So Farewell Then: The Untold Life of Peter Cook\" Cook, Wendy E. {{ISBN|0-00-722893-7}}, p. 139-144</ref> [[Victoria Wood]] launched her stand-up career in the early 1980s, which included observational conversation mixed with comedy songs. Wood was to become one of the country's most successful comedians, in 2001 selling out the [[Royal Albert Hall]] for 15 nights in a row.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 1979, the first American-style stand-up comedy club, the [[Comedy Store, London|Comedy Store]] was opened in London by [[Peter Rosengard]], where many alternative comedy stars of the 1980s, such as [[Dawn French]] and [[Jennifer Saunders]], [[Alexei Sayle]], [[Craig Ferguson]], [[Rik Mayall]] and [[Ade Edmondson]] began their careers.<ref>Wilmut, R and Rosengard, P ''Didn't You Kill My Mother-In-Law: The Story Of Alternative Comedy In Britain.'' {{ISBN|978-0-413-17390-4}}</ref> The stand-up comedy circuit rapidly expanded from London across the UK. The present British stand-up comedy circuit arose from the 'alternative' comedy revolution of the 1980s, with political and observational humor being the prominent styles to flourish. In 1983, young drama teacher Maria Kempinska created [[Jongleurs]] Comedy Clubs, now the largest stand-up comedy chain in Europe. Stand up comedy is believed to have been performed originally as a one-man show. Lately, this type of show started to involve a group of young comedians, especially in Europe.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}[[File:Hope WWII 44.jpg|right|thumb|160px|[[Bob Hope]], the United States of America's most famous stand-up comedian during [[World War II]]]]\n\n====Spain====\nAlthough the antecedents of this genre can be traced back to the monologues of [[Miguel Gila]] in the 1950s, [[:es:Comedia en vivo#Espa\u00f1a|the rise of live comedy in Spain]] took a long time in comparison with the American continent. The first generalized relationship with this comic genre occurred in 1999 with the creation of the [[Comedy Central Spain|Paramount Comedy]] channel, which included the ''New Comics'' program as one of its flagship programs, where monologuists such as [[\u00c1ngel Mart\u00edn]], Jos\u00e9 Juan Vaquero, [[David Broncano]], and [[Joaqu\u00edn Reyes (actor)|Joaqu\u00edn Reyes]] stood out.\nAlso, in 1999 began the journey of the program [[The club of comedy]], an open adaptation of the popular comic format. In its first stage (1999-2005), it underwent several chain changes and released comedians like [[Luis Piedrahita]], [[Alexis Valdes]] or [[:es:Goyo Jim\u00e9nez|Goyo Jim\u00e9nez]]. In its new stage, starting in 2011 in [[La Sexta]] and presented by [[Eva Hache]], it tries to start in the genre of comic monologue media characters from different artistic fields such as: [[Imanol Arias]], [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Gil]], [[Isabel Ordaz]] and [[Santiago Segura]].\nSpecial mention deserves the [[:es:Buenafuente|Buenafuente]] program, started in 2005. The presenter, [[Andreu Buenafuente]], made an initial monologue of about 9 to 11 minutes where he links current issues with everyday humorous situations. This became the most famous part of the program and made him one of the most recognized comedians in Spain, for his connection with the public and his ability to improvise.\nOn the other hand, the comedian [[Ignatius Farray]] became one of the most representative icons of this genre today.\n\n== History of stand-up in the Americas ==\n\n===United States===\n[[File:George Carlin 1969.JPG|thumb|right|160px|<center>[[George Carlin]] in 1969</center>]]\nStand-up comedy in the United States got its start from '''[[monologist]]s''' performing [[Stump speech (minstrelsy)|stump-speech monologues]] from within the [[minstrel show]]s of the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://news.psu.edu/story/141330/2008/09/12/research/probing-question-what-are-roots-stand-comedy\n |title=Probing Question: What are the roots of stand-up comedy?\n |last=Parker\n |first=Bethany\n |date=12 September 2008\n |department=Research\n |website=PennState News\n |publisher=The Pennsylvania State University \n |location=University Park, Pennsylvania\n |access-date=24 February 2019\n |quote=American stand-up comedy has its beginnings in the minstrel shows of the early 1800s}}</ref> It also has roots in various traditions of popular entertainment of the late 19th century, including [[vaudeville]], English [[music hall]], [[burlesque]] or [[Variety show|early variety shows]], [[humorist]] monologues by personalities such as [[Mark Twain]], and [[circus clown]] antics.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.britannica.com/art/stand-up-comedy\n |title=Stand-up comedy\n |last= Zoglin\n |first=Richard\n |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\n |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> With the turn of the century and spread of urban and industrial living, the structure, pacing and timing, and material of American humor began to change. Comedians of this era often depended on fast-paced joke delivery, slapstick, outrageous or lewd innuendo, and donned an ethnic persona\u2014African, Scottish, German, Jewish\u2014and built a routine based on popular stereotypes. Jokes were generally broad and material was widely shared, or in some cases, stolen. Industrialized American audiences sought entertainment as a way to escape and confront city living.\n\nThe founders of modern American stand-up comedy include [[Moms Mabley]], [[Jack Benny]], [[Bob Hope]], [[George Burns]], [[Fred Allen]], [[Milton Berle]] and [[Frank Fay (American actor)|Frank Fay]], all of whom came from vaudeville or the [[Chitlin' Circuit]].<ref>\"'Whoopi Goldberg Presents Moms Mabley'\" ZAP 2 IT: http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/11/whoopi-goldberg-presents-moms-mabley-eddie-murphy-bill-cosby-and-arsenio-hall-all-owe-a-debt.html</ref> They spoke directly to the audience as themselves, in front of the curtain, known as performing \"in one\". Frank Fay gained acclaim as a \"[[master of ceremonies]]\" at New York's [[Palace Theatre (Broadway)|Palace Theater]]. Vaudevillian [[Charlie Case|Charlie Case (also spelled Charley Case)]] is often credited with the first form of stand-up comedy, performing humorous monologues without props or costumes. This had not been done before during a vaudeville show.\n\nNightclubs and resorts became the new breeding ground for stand-ups. Acts such as [[Alan King (comedian)|Alan King]], [[Danny Thomas]], [[Martin and Lewis]], [[Don Rickles]], [[Joan Rivers]] and [[Jack E. Leonard]] flourished in these venues.\n\nIn the 1950s and into the 1960s, stand-ups such as [[Mort Sahl]] began developing their acts in small folk clubs like San Francisco's [[hungry i]] (owned by impresario [[Enrico Banducci]] and origin of the ubiquitous \"brick wall\" behind comedians)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/16/local/me-banducci16|title=Enrico Banducci, 85; owned hungry i nightclub|last=McLellan|first=Dennis|date=2007-10-16|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> or New York's [[The Bitter End|Bitter End]]. These comedians added an element of social satire and expanded both the language and boundaries of stand-up, venturing into politics, [[race relations]], and [[off-color humor|sexual humor]]. [[Lenny Bruce]] became known as 'the' obscene comic when he used language that usually led to his arrest.<ref>''Make Em Laugh: The Funny Business of America'' Maslon, Laurence E. {{ISBN|978-0-446-50531-4}}, p.340 \u2013 p.341</ref> After Lenny Bruce, arrests for obscene language on stage nearly disappeared until [[George Carlin]] was arrested on 21 July 1972 at [[Milwaukee]]'s [[Summerfest]] after performing the routine \"[[Seven dirty words|Seven Words You Can Never Say on Television]]\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=626471\n|title=Carlin's naughty words still ring in officer's ears\n|author=Jim Stingl\n|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]\n|date=June 30, 2007\n|accessdate=2008-03-23\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929124942/http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=626471 |archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> (the case against Carlin was eventually dismissed).\n\nOther notable comics from this era include [[Woody Allen]], [[Shelley Berman]], [[Phyllis Diller]], and [[Bob Newhart]]. Some [[African American|Black American]] comedians such as [[Redd Foxx]], [[George Kirby]], [[Bill Cosby]], and [[Dick Gregory]] began to cross over to white audiences during this time.\n\nIn the 1970s, several entertainers became major stars based on stand-up comedy performances. [[Richard Pryor]] and George Carlin followed Lenny Bruce's acerbic style to become icons. Stand-up expanded from clubs, resorts, and coffee houses into major concerts in sports arenas and amphitheaters. [[Steve Martin]] and Bill Cosby had levels of success with gentler comic routines. The older style of stand-up comedy (no social satire) was kept alive by [[Rodney Dangerfield]] and [[Buddy Hackett]], who enjoyed revived careers late in life. [[Don Rickles]], whose legendary style of relentless merciless attacks on both fellow performers and audience members alike kept him a fixture on TV and in Vegas from the 1960s all the way to the 2000s, when he appeared in the wildly popular [[Pixar]] ''[[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]]'' films as [[Mr Potato Head]], who just happened to share Don's grouchy onstage mannerisms. Television programs such as ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' helped publicize the careers of other stand-up comedians, including [[Janeane Garofalo]], [[Bill Maher]] and [[Jay Leno]].\n\nFrom the 1970s to the '90s, different styles of comedy began to emerge, from the madcap stylings of [[Robin Williams]], to the odd observations of [[Jerry Seinfeld]] and [[Ellen DeGeneres]], the ironic musings of [[Steven Wright]], to the mimicry of [[Whoopi Goldberg]], and [[Eddie Murphy]]. These comedians would serve to influence the next generation of comedians.\n\n===Mexico===\n\nIn terms of [[:es:Comedia en vivo#M\u00e9xico|live comedy in Mexico]], the predecessors of this comic style are:\n* [[:es:Los Tepichines|The Tepichines]] are a comic duo who were predecessors of a style consisting of parodies and double senses with creativity\n* [[Miguel Galv\u00e1n]] (1957-2008) Originally from Juan Aldama, Zacatecas. He dropped out of architecture at the Universidad del Valle de M\u00e9xico to take theater classes at the \"Dimitrio Sarr\u00e1s Actors Studio\" for three years.\n* Mara Escalante, is an actress, comedian and Mexican singer. She is known for the television series Mar\u00eda de Todos los \u00c1ngeles, in which she has two characters, including the protagonist. She began her career in the mid-1990s.\n* [[Polo Polo]] (1944-), whose routines are characterized by a high content of sexual references, with a touch of misogyny, relayed as a personal anecdote.\n* [[Adal Ramones]] (1961-) was one of the first to transport the genre to Mexico from his nocturnal program, using the comic monologue.\n* [[Evelio Arias Ramos|Evelio with V Chica]] (Evelio Arias Ramos, 1966-2008).\n* [[Eugenio Derbez]]\n\nThe new generation of comedians decided to use their own lives as the theme of their comedy, imitating the American style:\n\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Su\u00e1rez Gom\u00eds]], son of Mexican comedian [[H\u00e9ctor Su\u00e1rez]], is currently the host of the Latin American version of the comedy program Stand Up Comedy Central Presents, broadcast by Comedy Central from 2011 until 2014.\n* [[Adal Ramones]] since 2013 leads the program called [[:es:STANDparados|STANDparados]] broadcast by [[:es:Distrito Comedia|Comedy District]] before [[Classic TV]].\n* Kikis, (1980) comedian since late 2011, openly lesbian, has participated in [[Comedy Central Latin America]] as well as with [[Adal Ramones]] in STANDparados Comedy District.\n* Luiki Wiki (1985-) began making comedy in January 2013 in Mexico City and later moved to Monterrey NL to start the first Open Mic in Monterrey (an event in which comedians can participate to try out new material with a real audience) together with other comedians of the genre. Later they created the first collective of comedy in Monterrey called For Laughter Standup Comedy. Luiki Wiki has participated in programs such as Es de Noche and I already arrived with Ren\u00e9 Franco and as with [[Adal Ramones]] in the 3rd season of the STANDparados program aired by Comedy District.\n* [[:es:Franco Escamilla|Franco Escamilla]] (1981-) Comedian, musician, radio announcer and founder of \"La Diablo Squad\". He is mainly known for his comedy shows, has performed throughout the Mexican Republic and Latin America, even starting his own \"World Tour\", arriving to have confirmed performances in Europe and the United States, including trips to Japan and Australia. Currently known as the largest representative of Stand up Comedy in this country.\n* Hugo \"El Cojo Fel\u00edz\" (1988-), is a comedian, radio announcer, part of the devil Squad, has the radio program \"La Hora Fel\u00edz\" with the \"Uncle Rober\" and is considered the best pen in Mexico.\n* Roberto Andrade Cer\u00f3n the \"Uncle Rober\" (1979-) is a comedian, writer, radio announcer and has \"La Cojo Feliz\" the radio program \"La Hora Fel\u00edz\".\n*Daniel Sosa \n*Alex Fernandez\n\n=== Brazil ===\nThe one-man-show genre, which is similar, but allows other approaches (enacting characters, songs and scenes) was introduced in Brazil by Jos\u00e9 Vasconcellos in the 60's. Taking a step closer to the North American format, Chico Anysio and J\u00f4 Soares maintained the format - specially in their live nation-wide talks shows, and generally, in the opening monologues - bringing to Brazil a genre more similar to what we currently know as Stand-up.\n\nStand-up began to be interesting news in 2005 in ''S\u00e3o Paulo'', when the first club was created, called ''Clube de Com\u00e9dia Stand-Up:'' composed of Marcelo Mansfield, Rafinha Bastos, Oscar Filho, Marcela Leal and M\u00e1rcio Ribeiro. In S\u00e3o Paulo the comedy club would present in Beverly Hills, the traditional comedy venue in Moema. Shortly afterwards it migrated to Mr. Blues and Bleeker Street, in ''Vila Madalena''. In ''Rio de Janeiro'', ''Com\u00e9dia em P\u00e9, (''Comedy Standing Up): composed of Cl\u00e1udio Torres Gonzaga, F\u00e1bio Porch\u00e1t, Fernando Caruso and Paulo Carvalho, had its debue at the venue ''Rio Design Leblon''. These were the first stand-up performances in the country.\n\nIn 2006, the comic J\u00f4 Soares watched ''Clube de Com\u00e9dia'' in S\u00e3o Paulo and invited the comic Diogo Portugal for an interview in his talk show. That was a definitive moment to call attention towards the genre. He mentioned many different shows that he was a part of and attracted the public attention and media coverage to the bars that held these presentations. In Curitiba, with this momentum, many other stand-up nights began opening up. In S\u00e3o Paulo, Danilo Gentili, that had just become a part of ''Clube da Com\u00e9dia,'' invited M\u00e1rio Ribeiro and gathered other young comics that were frequent spectators at the club, to create ''Com\u00e9dia Ao Vivo'' (Live Comedy): composed of Dani Calabresa, Luiz Fran\u00e7a, F\u00e1bio Rabin.\n\nWith the show CQC - ''Custe o Que Custar'', on the channel Band, a nation-wide tv outlet, in 2008, the genre took gained its permanent spot on the national stage. With bug names like Danilo Gentili, Rafinha Bastos and Oscar Filho, the curiosity grew exponentially. \n\nFollowing CQC's example many channels and tv shows on Brazil's national television invested in Stand-up comedy. After this many other groups gained recognition in the clubs and live performances around the two biggest cities of Brazil.\n\n== History of stand-up in Asia ==\n===India===\n[[File:Kapil sharma.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kapil Sharma (comedian)|Kapil Sharma]] an Indian stand up comedian, known for comedy nights with Kapil]]\nModern stand-up comedy in India is a young art form, however [[Chakyar koothu]] was prominent in [[Trivandrum]] and southern [[Kerala]] during the 16th and 17th centuries. It had all the attributes of modern stand-up comedy and is widely considered to be the oldest known staged comedy act anywhere in the world.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nEven though the history of live comedy performances in India traces its early roots back to 1980s, for a long time stand-up comedians were only given supporting/filler acts in various performances (dance or music).{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 1986, India's [[Johnny Lever]] performed in a charity show called \"Hope 86\", in front of the whole Hindi film industry as a filler and was loved by audience. His talent was recognized, and he would later be described as \"the iconic comedian of his generation\".<ref>[http://www.mid-day.com/videos/johnny-lever-on-phalke-awards/3660 Johnny Lever on Phalke Awards<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-johny-lever-the-missing-comic-in-hindi-films-1596571 Johny Lever: The missing comic in Hindi films | Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIt was not until 2005, when the TV show ''[[The Great Indian Laughter Challenge]]'' garnered huge popularity and stand-up comedy in itself started getting recognised. Thus, a lot more comedians became popular and started performing various live and TV shows. The demand for comedy content continues to increase. Some popular comedians around 2005-2008 include Raju Srivastav, Kapil Sharma, Sunil Pal etc. Most of them performed their acts in Hindi.\n\n[[File:Raju-Srivastav.jpg|right|thumb|160px|right|thumb|150px|New generation stand up comedian [[Raju Srivastav]]]]\n[[Raju Srivastav]] first appeared on the comedy talent show ''[[The Great Indian Laughter Challenge]]''. He finished as second runner-up and then took part in the spin-off, The Great Indian Laughter Challenge \u2014 Champions, in which he won the title of \"The King of Comedy\".<ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/bombay/report-raju-shrivastav-threatened-asked-not-to-joke-about-dawood-1226205 Raju Shrivastav threatened, asked not to joke about Dawood]</ref> Srivastava was a participant on season 3 of ''[[Bigg Boss (Season 3)|Bigg Boss]]''. He has participated in the comedy show ''Comedy Ka Maha Muqabla''.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/bangalore/Raju-Srivastav-tickles-the-funny-bone-at-Le-Meridien-Bangalore/articleshow/30159461.cms Raju Srivastav tickles the funny bone at Le Meridien, Bangalore]</ref>\n\n[[Kapil Sharma (comedian)|Kapil Sharma]] is ranked no. 3 at the most admired Indian personality list by [[The Economic Times]] in 2015.<ref name=\"The Economic Times\">{{cite news|title=Kapil Sharma ranked no.3 in Admired list|url= http://m.economictimes.com/slideshows/people/20-most-admired-people-in-india/kapil-sharma/slideshow/47260028.cms}}</ref> Currently he is hosting the most popular Indian comedy show \"[[The Kapil Sharma Show]]\" after \"[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]\".<ref name=\"TimesofIndia\">{{cite news |title= Kapil Sharma plays the \"Traffic monitor\" at India Gate |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/news-and-gossip/Kapil-Sharma-plays-the-Traffic-monitor-at-India-Gate/articleshow/22334306.cms |newspaper= The Times of India |date= 26 September 2013}}</ref> Sharma had been working in the comedy show ''Hasde Hasande Raho'' on MH One, until he got his first break in [[The Great Indian Laughter Challenge]], one of the nine reality television shows he has won. He became the winner of the show in 2007 for which he won 10 lakhs as prize money.<ref name=\"TimesofIndia\"/>\n\nSharma participated in Sony Entertainment Television\u2019s ''[[Comedy Circus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siasat.com/english/news/parvati-singhal-kapil-crown-comedy-king |title=Parvati Singhal, Kapil crown Comedy King |publisher=Siasat |date=2010-08-29 |accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref> He became the winner of all six seasons of \"[[Comedy Circus]]\" he participated in.<ref>{{cite web|title= Kapil wins another season of Comedy circus|url = http://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/Kapil-wins-yet-another-season-of-Comedy-Circus/articleshow/11131528.cms}}</ref> He has hosted dance reality show ''[[Jhalak Dikhhla Jaa (season 6)|Jhalak Dikhhla Jaa Season 6]]''<ref>[http://forbesindia.com/celebprofile/kapil-sharma/186 Kapil sharma`s profile in Forbes list] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225093429/http://forbesindia.com/celebprofile/kapil-sharma/186 |date=2014-12-25 }}</ref> and also hosted comedy show ''[[Chhote Miyan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Aparna Banerji |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090724/jplus.htm#3 |title=Lady laughter sends T-town rolling |publisher=Tribune India |date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2014-07-21}}</ref><ref name=toi13>{{cite news| title = Daily soaps weren't creatively satisfying: Manish Paul | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-08-11/tv/41293838_1_kapil-sharma-manish-paul-humour|date=11 August 2013 | accessdate = 2013-08-16 | newspaper = [[The Times of India]] }}</ref> Sharma also participated in the show ''[[Ustaadon Ka Ustaad]]''.\n\nAround 2008-2009, two other popular comedians [[Papa CJ]] and Vir Das returned to India and started making their marks on Indian comedy scene. Both of them were exposed to UK and US comedy routines and they performed mostly in English. At the same time, a few more youngsters got inspired and started taking plunge into stand-up comedy.\n\nSince 2011, the stand-up comedy has been getting substantial appreciation.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} The Comedy Store from London opened an outlet in Mumbai's Palladium Mall where people would regularly enjoy comedians from UK. The Comedy Story also supported local comedians and helped them grow. This outlet eventually become Canvas Laugh Club in Mumbai.\n\nAround 2011, people started organizing different comedy open mic events in Mumbai, Delhi (and Gurgaon), Bangalore. All of this happened in association with growth of a counterculture in Indian cities which catered to the appetite of younger generations for live events for comedy, poetry, storytelling, and music. Various stand up events were covered by popular news channels such NDTV / Aajtak etc. and were appreciated by millions of viewers.\n\nAs a result of these developments, plus the increasing penetration of [[YouTube]] (along with [[Internet]]/[[World Wide Web]]), Indian stand up comedy started reaching further masses. While the established comedians such as Vir Das, Papa CJ were independently growing through various corporate / international performances, other comedians such as [[Vipul Goyal]], [[Biswa Kalyan Rath]], [[Kenny Sebastian]], [[Kanan Gill]] grew popular through YouTube videos.\n\nThe industry, still in its early stages, now sees a lot more influx of aspiring comedians as it transforms the ecosystem around it.\n\n==Training and improvisation==\n\n[[Mark Twain]] and [[Jerry Seinfeld]],  both American masters of stand-up comedy, believe in practice and rehearsal. Twain prepared, rehearsed, revised and adapted his material for his popular humorous presentations.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Chasing the Last Laugh - Mark Twain's raucous and redemptive round-the-world-comedy-tour|last=Zacks|first=Richard|publisher=Doubleday|year=2016|isbn=9780385536448|location=New York, London|pages=}}</ref> Seinfeld says: \"Most contemporary comedy is profane, outraged and disposable\" but his philosophy is to give the best that he has.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/jerry-seinfeld-touring-australia-in-2017-you-will-see-the-best-that-i-have-20161027-gscpg9.html|title=Jerry Seinfeld touring Australia in 2017: 'You will see the best that I have'|last=Purcell|first=Andrew|date=3 November 2016|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=6 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106233932/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/jerry-seinfeld-touring-australia-in-2017-you-will-see-the-best-that-i-have-20161027-gscpg9.html|archive-date=2016-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nComedy schools work with new comics to workshop material, assisting comics work to overcome stage fright and better their writing skills by helping their classmates improve their sets.<ref>{{cite web|title=How to Become a Comedian|url=http://www.theartcareerproject.com/become-comedian/|website=theartcareerproject.com|publisher=The Art Career Project|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> Comedy schools offer [[improvisation]] classes for comics so that they are more comfortable straying from written material such as when dealing with [[heckler]]s. Improvisation is also necessary when working among crowd and interacting with the audience.\n\n==Festivals==\n{{Main|Comedy festival}}\n\n[[File:Janeane Garofalo Jan 15, 2008.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Janeane Garofalo]] performing at \"[[Seth Herzog|Sweet]]\" in New York City in 2008]]\n\nComedy festivals are used by industry professionals to seek out new comedians to hire.<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Frances-White\n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur\n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Jim Jefferies\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=176\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=Go to festivals, because that's where you get noticed by the media...[and] gauge [yourself against] everybody else.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Buddy Mora\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=280\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I [Buddy Morra] go to the Montreal and Aspen comedy festivals, but I haven\u2019t seen much that\u2019s knocked me out.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Mendrinos\n |first=James\n |year=2004\n |title=The Idiot\u2019s Complete Guide To Comedy Writing\n |location=375 Hudson Street, New York, NY 10014\n |publisher=Alpha: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc.\n |page=199\n |isbn=1-59257-231-6\n |quote=Jim McCue, the founder of ''The Boston International Comedy and Movie Festival'', spoke about the role of the festival in the industry: \u2018A festival is a great way to get attention for someone who might not have the connections other people do. This festival is constantly looking for under-appreciated talent. Hopefully, we can do our part and let people see the next generation of comedy genius.\u2019}}</ref>\n\nStand-up comedy is the focus of four major international festivals: the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland; [[Just for Laughs]] in [[Montreal, Quebec]], [[Toronto, Ontario]], and Vancouver, British Columbia in Canada; HBO's [[U.S. Comedy Arts Festival]] in [[Aspen, CO]], and the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] in [[Melbourne]], Australia.\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2007/mar/16/scotland.canada.australia\n |title=Five top comedy festivals around the world\n |last=Brown\n |first=Georgia\n |date=16 March 2007\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> A number of other festivals operate around the world, including [[The Comedy Festival]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], the Vancouver Comedy Festival, the [[New York Comedy Festival]], the Boston Comedy and Film Festival, the [[New York Underground Film Festival]], the [[Sydney Comedy Festival]], and the [[Cat Laughs]] Comedy Festival in [[Kilkenny]], [[Ireland]]. Radio hosts [[Opie and Anthony]] also produce a comedy tour called [[Opie and Anthony's Traveling Virus Comedy Tour]], featuring their own co-host, [[Jim Norton (American comedian)|Jim Norton]] as well as several other stand-up comedians regularly featured on their radio show. There is also a festival in Hong Kong called the [[HK International Comedy Festival]].\n\n==Stand-up circuits==\n===Defunct American circuits===\n\n====Theatre Owners Booking Association (T.O.B.A.)====\n{{Main Article|Theatre Owners Booking Association}}\nThis was black vaudeville that predated the Chitlin' Circuit.\n\n====Chitlin' Circuit====\n{{Main article|Chitlin' Circuit}}\nThe Chitlin' Circuit was a \"collection of all-black venues, clubs, [and] theaters\".<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.thehistoryofstandup.com/episodes/s2-ep-03-the-apollo-and-the-chitlin-circuit\n| title=S2 EP. 03: THE APOLLO AND THE CHITLIN\u2019 CIRCUIT\n| website=The History of Standup\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| date=18 June 2019\n| time= 3:12-4:00\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=The Chitlin\u2019 Circuit was a collection of all-black venues, clubs, [and] theaters\u2014that was in the United States during the era of, basically racial segregation, and this is not just in the South my friend. This is in the North as well, where a lot of African-American families came north during what\u2019s called the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]] and a number of clubs opened up specifically in these neighborhoods\u2014which were [[redlining|redlined]]\u2014and subsequently launched some of the greatest music and comedy acts we\u2019ve ever known. And so the Apollo Theater was in the chitlin circuit. Not only in it, the crown jewel.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Nesteroff\n| first        = Kliph\n| date         = 22 December 2015\n| title        = Make 'Em Laugh: 'The Comedians' Tells The Story Of Stand-Up\n| url          = https://www.npr.org/2015/12/22/460613321/make-em-laugh-the-comedians-tells-the-story-of-stand-up\n| work         = NPR\n| access-date  = 20 August 2019\n| quote        = The Chitlin' Circuit was African-American comedians performing for African-American audiences because comedy was segregated back then\u2026But it was not acceptable in those days for a black comedian to address a white crowd, because as a comedian on stage, you are superior to your audience. You are giving them your point of view \u2014 and in those days it wasn't allowed, so the Chitlin' Circuit alleviated that thing.}}</ref> The [[Apollo Theater]] was the performers' most sought after venue.<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = McNary\n| first        = Dave\n| date         = 13 February 2019\n| title        = Apollo Theater Documentary Selected as Tribeca Festival Opener\n| url          = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/apollo-theater-documentary-tribeca-festival-opener-1203138125/\n| work         = Variety\n| access-date  = 20 August 2019\n| quote        = The Apollo began operating in 1934 during the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and became the most prized venue on the \u2018Chitlin\u2019 Circuit\u2019 during the time of racial segregation in the United States.}}</ref> Notable performers for this circuit include [[Richard Pryor]], [[Moms Mabley]], [[Dick Gregory]], [[Redd Foxx]], and the duo [[Tim and Tom]].<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Barnes\n| first        = Mo\n| date         = 9 January 2019\n| title        = A conversation with Luenell: When does Black comedy become hurtful?\n| url          = https://rollingout.com/2019/01/09/a-conversation-with-luenell-when-does-black-comedy-become-hurtful/\n| work         = rollingout\n| access-date  = 20 August 2019\n| quote        = Comedians such as Redd Foxx, Dick Gregory, Richard Pryor and Moms Mabley were popular first in clubs on the \u2018Chitlin\u2019 Circuit\u2019 in urban hubs.}}</ref>\n\n====Borscht Belt====\n{{Main Article|Borscht Belt}}\nAlso called the ''Jewish Alps'', they hired performers that included stand-up comedians.<ref name=hefner>{{cite news\n| author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| date         = 28 September 2017\n| title        = What Hugh Hefner did for comedy\n| url          = https://www.chortle.co.uk/features/2017/09/28/38011/what_hugh_hefner_did_for_comedy#\n| work         = Chortle\n| access-date  = 17 August 2019\n| quote        =[Hugh Hefner\u2019s] clubs providing a bridge between the old-school resorts of the Catskill mountains and the comedy club explosion of the 1980s.}}</ref> The [[Catskill Mountains]] are depicted in ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]''.<ref name=hefner/>\n\n====Playboy comedy circuit====\nBefore the advent of full-fledged American comedy clubs, [[Hugh Hefner]] created a chain of [[Playboy Club]]s and employed people like [[Dick Gregory]],<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Parker\n| first        = Ryan\n| date         = 27 September 2017\n| title        = Hugh Hefner Gave Dick Gregory His Big Break\n| url          = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugh-hefner-gave-dick-gregory-his-big-break-1043953\n| work         = The Hollywood Reporter\n| access-date  = 17 August 2019}}</ref> [[Mort Sahl]], [[Steve Martin]], and [[Lenny Bruce]].<ref name=hefner/><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/s2-ep-02-the-playboy-circuit/id1052359696?i=1000441141679\n| title=S2 Ep. 02: The Playboy Circuit\n| website=Apple Podcasts\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| date=11 June 2019\n| time=0:00-2:07\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=Hugh Hefner...decides in 1960...to open a club in Chicago called the Playboy Club and then opens a number of these clubs all around the country, creates this circuit where comedians...this is before comedy clubs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/s2-ep-02-the-playboy-circuit/id1052359696?i=1000441141679\n| title=S2 Ep. 02: The Playboy Circuit\n| website=Apple Podcasts\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| others=[[Tom Dreesen]]\n| date=11 June 2019\n| time=23:00-23:30\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=When I started out in show business, there were no comedy clubs. Every nightclub in America had a comic...They [Playboy] had two showrooms, ''The Penthouse'' and ''The Playroom''...When they\u2019re ready to start the show...The girl singer would go on and do 3 or 4 songs and then, she would finish, and we\u2019d come on and we\u2019d be doing like 45 minutes and she would do 15 like minutes}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/s2-ep-02-the-playboy-circuit/id1052359696?i=1000441141679\n| title=S2 Ep. 02: The Playboy Circuit\n| website=Apple Podcasts\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| others=Dick Capri\n| date=11 June 2019\n| time=24:30-25:20\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=They [Playboy] gave you nothing\u2026they did not pay transportation and they did not pay for the hotel room; you could eat there where the employees ate\u2026and the top money at that time was a 1,000 dollars a week, and I did not get that; [[Jackie Gayle]], he was the top comedian of the playboy clubs in those days you know, and I got $500 a week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Martin\n |first=Steve\n |year=2007\n |title=Born Standing Up: A Comic's Life\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Scribner\n |pages=156\n |isbn=978-1-4165-5364-9\n |quote=In March 1975 my agent, Mart Klein, secured a job in San Francisco, two weeks headlining the Playboy Club for fifteen hundred dollars per week\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bornstandingupco00mart\n }}</ref> Hugh Hefner ok'd [[Burns and Carlin at the Playboy Club Tonight]], which was not recorded in a Playboy club.\n\n===Contemporary circuits===\n\n====Open mic circuit (UK)====\nThe open mic scene is referred to as the open mic circuit in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qbx97b/life-as-an-amateur-comic-on-the-open-mic-circuit-246\n |title=What Life Is Like As an Amateur Comic On the Open-Mic Circuit\n |last= Larner\n |first=Sam\n |date=25 November 2015\n |website=VICE UK\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/correspondents/2012/09/06/16101/100_ways_to_save_the_open-mic_circuit\n |title=100 ways to save the open-mic circuit\n |date=6 September 2012\n |website=Chortle\n |access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====College circuit====\nThere are two associations that lead the college circuit: the [[Association for the Promotion of Campus Activities]] (APCA) (which has 200 member colleges) and the [[National Association for Campus Activities]] (NACA) (which has 1,100 member colleges).<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Schwenson\n |first=Dave\n |year=2005\n |title=COMEDY FAQS AND ANSWERS: HOW THE STAND-UP BIZ REALLY WORKS\n |location=New York, NY\n |publisher=ALLWORTH PRESS\n |page=171\n |isbn=1-58115-411-9}}</ref>\n\nComedians in the USA and Canada audition for NACA to hundreds of college and university bookers,<ref name=NF>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/09/thats-not-funny/399335/\n |title=That's Not Funny! Today's college students can't seem to take a joke.\n |last=Flanagan\n |first=Caitlin\n |date=September 2015\n |website=The Atlantic\n |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> first with a 90-second video submission, and then a ten-minute, in-person audition to perform hour-long sets.<ref name=CCPC>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/08/30/despite-struggles-comics-find-lucrative-business-college-campuses\n |title=College Comedy: Provocative Yet\u2026 PC?\n |last=Bauer-Wolf\n |first=Jeremy\n |date=30 August 2018\n |website=INSIDE HIGHER ED\n |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSets must not [[trauma trigger|trigger]] students by \"punching down,\" contain any denigrating material,<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people=Chris Fleming (comedian), Michael Moynihan (Vice News), Jason Meier (Emerson College booker), Kat Michael (Simmons College booker), Katy Hamm (Lesly University booker), Judy Gold (comedian)\n | date =24 May 2018\n | title =College Campuses Can Be Minefields For Comedians (HBO)\n | medium =Streaming\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBu3g4kiwck\n | access-date =8 February 2019\n | format =YouTube\n | time =3:32-3:39\n | location=Boston\n | publisher =VICE News Tonight: HBO\n |quote=[A comedian] can talk about [their] experience, but [they] can't make fun of someone else's identity.}}</ref> or contain dark or blue humor; it must be \"intelligent humor\"<ref name=CCPC /> and contain subjects that college-aged adults express contempt for.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.popmatters.com/havent-you-learned-how-to-take-a-joke-2531912988.html\n |title=Haven't You Learned How to Take a Joke? The Comedy-on-Campus Debates\n |last=Ellis\n |first=Iain\n |date=8 February 2018\n |website=popMATTERS: Culture\n |access-date=10 February 2019\n |quote=Thus, college comedians can mock those groups \"liberal\" students deride\u2014Evangelical Christians, Scientologists, working-class rural males\u2014yet they dare not even flirt with jokes about race, gender, and sexuality.}}</ref>\n\nHigher education, that was once seen as the bastion of free speech is now criticized by comedians for being too [[Political correctness|PC (politically correct)]].<ref name=NF/> Many famous comedians no longer desire to perform at colleges and universities.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/11/chris-rock-frank-rich-in-conversation.html\n |title=In Conversation Chris Rock: What's killing comedy. What's saving America.\n |last=Rich\n |first=Frank\n |date=1 December 2014\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=10 February 2019\n |quote=I stopped playing colleges\u2026because they\u2019re way too conservative\u2026in their social views and their willingness not to offend anybody.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/college/2015/06/08/jerry-seinfeld-says-comedians-avoid-college-gigs-students-are-so-pc/37403583/\n |title=Jerry Seinfeld says comedians avoid college gigs, students are 'so PC'\n |last=Schramm\n |first=Michael\n |date=8 June 2015\n |website=USA Today\n |publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, LLC.\n |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people=Chris Fleming (comedian), Michael Moynihan (Vice News), Jason Meier (Emerson College booker), Kat Michael (Simmons College booker), Katy Hamm (Lesly University booker), Judy Gold (comedian)\n | date =24 May 2018\n | title =College Campuses Can Be Minefields For Comedians (HBO)\n | medium =Streaming\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBu3g4kiwck\n | access-date =8 February 2019\n | format =YouTube\n | time =4:15-4:26\n | location=Boston\n | publisher =VICE News Tonight: HBO\n | quote=Judy gold is one of many famous comics, including Jerry Seinfeld and Chris Rock who say they avoid playing college campuses, because they believe younger audiences can't take a joke.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.popmatters.com/havent-you-learned-how-to-take-a-joke-2531912988.html\n |title=Haven't You Learned How to Take a Joke? The Comedy-on-Campus Debates\n |last=Ellis\n |first=Iain\n |date=8 February 2018\n |website=popMATTERS: Culture\n |access-date=10 February 2019\n |quote=It is notable that the majority of the most vociferous critics of today's student audiences\u2014Seinfeld, Maher, Gottfried, Louis CK, Dennis Miller, Larry the Cable Guy\u2014are middle-aged (or older), white, presumably heterosexual males...Ricky Gervais...too}}</ref>\n\n====Cruise circuit (CLIA)====\nThe [[Cruise Lines International Association]] contains 60 cruise liners. Comedians work an average of two days per week; this circuit is said to not aid in moving up in the field.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\">{{cite web\n |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/jul/14/entertainers-careers-buoyed-on-the-cruise-ship-cir/\n |title=Entertainers' careers buoyed on the cruise ship circuit\n |date=14 July 2000\n |website=Las Vegas Sun\n |publisher=Las Vegas Sun\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> Cruiseliners have both clean comedy and blue comedy at different times during the day, but opinionated political material is frowned upon.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/best-of-cruising/2014/09/10/the-best-cruise-lines-for-comedy-shows/15413043/\n |title=The best cruise lines for comedy\n |last=Golden\n |first=Fran\n |date=11 September 2014\n |website=Great Falls Tribune\n |publisher=USA Today Network\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> Hecklers are tolerated more in a cruise setting.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://travel.nine.com.au/2018/05/15/15/50/era-of-the-comedy-cruise\n |title=Five reasons to set sail on a comedy cruise\n |last=Scott\n |first=Katherine\n |date=June 2018\n |website=honey: travel\n |publisher=Nine Digital Pty Ltd\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Corporate circuit====\nCorporate circuit comedy must be clean comedy that neither swears nor references sexual acts;<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.standupcomedyclinic.com/34/\n |title=Corporate Comedy\n |last=Corely\n |first=Jerry\n |website=Jerry Corley's Comedy Clinic\n |publisher=Stand Up Comedy Clinic\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> church (or \u201csqueaky clean\u201d) comedy is preferred; two celebrities that perform this type of comedy are Jim Gaffigan and Brian Regan.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2016/0709/Why-clean-comedy-is-becoming-big-business\n |title=Why clean comedy is becoming big business\n |last1=Goodale\n |first1=Gloria\n |last2=Wood\n |first2=Daniel B.\n |date=9 July 2016\n |website=The Christian Science Monitor \n |publisher=The Christian Science Monitor\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> In a lecture given at the University of Oxford, Stewart Lee stated that his character is unable to do corporate gigs, because he takes on the role of being superior to his audience.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Stewart Lee\n | date =3 July 2013\n | title =On Not Writing\n | medium =YouTube\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IrXVaytvJtQ\n | access-date =13 February 2019\n | format =Lecture\n | time =46:40-47:40\n |location=St Edmund Hall\n | publisher =University of Oxford\n | quote =I can\u2019t ever do the lucrative, corporate gigs that\u2026because in that\u2026people can get paid a lot of money for doing half an hour at a bankers' convention, but you have to be the sort of person that appears to please people\u2026[and not treat them as] deficient}}</ref>\n\n====Christian comedy circuit (CCA)====\nThe [[Christian comedy|Christian Comedy]] Association started in the 90s, in an attempt to use comedy as a \"spiritual vehicle.\"<ref name=CCA>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/zng4je/gods-comics-inside-the-world-of-christian-standup-comedy-456 |title=God's Comics: Inside the World of Christian Stand-Up\n |last=Leon\n |first=Harmon\n |date=1 July 2015\n |website=VICE\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref> Comedian [[Doug Stanhope]] has criticized Christian comedy.<ref name=CCA/> Heckling is almost nonexistent in the church circuit.<ref name=CCA/> Christian comedy is clean comedy that claims to help one's soul.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.readingeagle.com/life/article/christian-ventriloquist-ryan-bomgardner-believes-god-wants-us-to-laugh\n |url-access=limited\n |title=Christian ventriloquist Ryan Bomgardner believes God wants us to laugh\n |last=Posten\n |first=Bruce\n |date=15 August 2014\n |website=Reading Eagle\n |access-date=18 February 2019\n |quote=I define Christian comedy as clean comedy that can be good for the soul. I believe God wants us to laugh}}</ref>\n\n==Salary==\nMany comedians have day jobs.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.laughspin.com/2013/06/24/12-jobs-comedians-had-before-they-were-famous-kevin-hart-jon-stewart-louis-c-k-and-more\n |title=12 jobs comedians had before they were famous: Kevin Hart, Jon Stewart, Louis C.K. and more!\n |last= Guglielmi \n |first=Jodi\n |date=24 June 2013\n |website=LaughSpin\n |publisher=LaughSpin\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906172555/http://www.laughspin.com/2013/06/24/12-jobs-comedians-had-before-they-were-famous-kevin-hart-jon-stewart-louis-c-k-and-more\n |archive-date=6 September 2013\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> In a comedian's first five years, they will lose money from travelling and performing.<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url= http://www.spentpodcast.com/episodes-1/2016/4/18/episode-002\n| title=Mark Normand: Funny for Money 002\n| website=SPENT\n| publisher=\n| host=Lindsay Goldwert\n| date=18 April 2016\n| time=4:14-4:40\n| access-date=\n| quote =I didn\u2019t start getting anywhere until\u2026five years in, financially\u2026even then, it was month to month [in New York City].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Buck\n| first        = Jerry\n| date         = 9 December 1987\n| title        = Comedian has last laugh\n| others       = Yakov Smirnoff\n| url          = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19871209&id=kXJeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yWENAAAAIBAJ&pg=3044,1787128\n| work         = Observer Reporter (AP TV Writer)\n| access-date  = 8 April 2019\n| quote\t       = It took four or five years before I [Yakov Smirnoff] could make a living as a comedian.}}</ref><ref name=Leno>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Jay Leno\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |pages=124\u2013125\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I've [Jay Leno] always told comedians that if you can do this for seven years, I mean physically make it to the stage for seven years, you\u2019ll always make a living...You start to get paid at the end of the fourth or fifth year\u2014I mean paid in terms of here\u2019s $500 dollars for one night, not $15 or $20 for a set.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|year=2006\n|chapter=My Ride is Here: Ant\n|editor1-last=Shydner\n|editor1-first=Ritch\n|editor2-last=Schiff\n|editor2-first=Mark\n|title=I Killed: True Stories of the Road From America\u2019s Top Comics\n|url=http://www.standupstories.com\n|url-status=dead\n|others=[[Ant (comedian)]]\n|edition=First Paperback\n|location=New York\n|publisher=Three Rivers Press\n|page=10\n|isbn=978-0-307-38229-0\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501193623/http://www.standupstories.com:80/\n|archive-date=1 May 2012\n|access-date=31 March 2020\n|quote=Early in a comic\u2019s career, you get calls from\u2026bookers\u2026I would never again take a gig where it cost me more to get there than the pay, but back then I just needed stage time.}}</ref> Comedians will sometimes be paid for their performances with alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/exmax4/how-to-be-a-touring-stand-up-comic\n |title=How to Be a Touring Stand-Up Comic\n |last= Koester\n |first=Megan\n |date=26 June 2014\n |website=VICE\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref> A stand-up's first comedy job will often be emceeing.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=12\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=The first paying position a comic can land is to emcee or host a show.}}</ref> While it can take around a decade to make a living at comedy,<ref name=Leno/> unknown comedians may achieve great financial success.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Chris Dipetta\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/67 67]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=People like [[Jay Leno|Leno]] and [[Steven Wright|Wright]] can make ten thousand dollars a show now\u2014that\u2019s not shocking. What\u2019s shocking is that I\u2019m a virtually unknown comic and I make about one hundred twenty-five thousand dollars a year.}}</ref>\n\nHosts and MCs are paid $0-$200, depending on location and the time of week (emcees average $25<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=79\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=An emcee will make usually from $10-$35 a show. It's usually $25.}}</ref>); showcase spots get $10-$75; features get approximately $300-$600; a headliner with no following gets $150-$1500, depending on many factors; headliners with a following or TV credits can make $1,500-$10,000 per show.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Ron White\n | year =2018\n | title = Ron White: If you Quit Listening, I\u2019ll Shut Up\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.netflix.com/title/80244900\n | access-date =29 March 2020\n | format =Motion Picture\n | time =39:21-39:41\n | quote =I was the feature act at ''The Punchline Comedy Club'' in Sacramento, California. And\u2026traditionally in American comedy clubs, there\u2019s three acts: there\u2019s an opening act that makes between a hundred and two hundred [dollars] a week for nine shows, there's a feature act\u2026makes between four and five hundred bucks a week for nine shows, and a headliner, who can make absolutely anything depending on who they are.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Strauss\n| first        = Duncan\n| date         = 3 November 1988\n| title        = Comedy: The Clubbing of America: The rise of comedy club chains\n| url          = https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/comedy-the-clubbing-of-america-70535/\n| work         = Rolling Stone\n| access-date  = 10 September 2019\n| quote        = At the better chains, middle acts earn a weekly salary of $600 and up; headliners, anywhere from $2000 to $10,000, plus air fare and lodging \u2013 usually at the club's 'comedy condo' in town...The chief variable is drawing power, based on accumulated TV and movie credits.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://comedyhints.com/what-to-expect-when-youre-expecting-to-be-paid-at-a-club/\n |title=What to Expect when You're Expecting...to be Paid at a Club\n |last=Hofstetter\n |first=Steve\n |date=2 July 2015\n |website=Comedy Hints: Helping Comedians Help Themselves\n |access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-34571446\n |title=No laughing matter: The secrets behind comedy success\n |last= O\u2019Brien\n |first=Jane\n |date=21 October 2015\n |website=BBC News\n |publisher=BBC\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=If it's somebody starting off in the business it could be $1,500 a show. For somebody who's had some TV credits you could go from $4,500 to $7,500.}}</ref> The headliner makes \"10 times\" more money than the feature act.<ref name=\"MSU\"/> Famous headliners get paid from \"door deals,\" or a percentage of the revenue, based on the number of seats sold; these comics rely on their notoriety to fill seats, which makes them more money than headliners with no following.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=87\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=the famous comics have what\u2019s called a \u201cdoor deal\u201d and get paid based on the amount of people in the crowd.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Rick Messina\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/68 68]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=It depends on the TV exposure of the comic, whether the comic draws and if he can command a higher ticket price.}}</ref> Comics will sell merchandise after their shows; this will make up for other expenses, like traveling.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.rd.com/culture/things-stand-up-comedian-wont-tell-you/\n |title=13 Things a Stand-Up Comedian Won't Tell You\n |last= Breidbart\n |first=Shaun Eli |date=2018-07-09\n |website=Reader\u2019s Digest\n |publisher=Trusted Media Brands, Inc.\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=Those T-shirts and CDs we sell are what we make our real money on...And when we do book a paying gig? We spend most of the money on transportation to get there.}}</ref>\n\nMark Normand states that a set on [[Conan (talk show)|Conan]] will pay \"a couple grand\" for five minutes.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://qz.com/810609/comedians-explain-the-improbable-economics-of-stand-up/\n |title=Comedians explain the improbable economics of stand-up\n |last=Goldwert\n |first=Lindsay\n |date=16 October 2016\n |website=QUARTZ\n |publisher=Quartz Media, Inc.\n |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> In 2012, [[Comedy Central]] routinely offered $15,000 for a half-hour special.<ref name=NYTC/> As of 2015, Comedy Central will pay comedians about $20,000 for a thirty-minute set; an hour, Comedy Central special can be up to $150,000;<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/09/what-comedy-pays.html\n |title=What Comedy Pays\n |last=mattoo\n |first=Priyanka\n |date=22 September 2015\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=7 February 2019}}</ref> as of 2018, [[Netflix]] will pay comedians $26,000+ for a fifteen-minute set; Netflix pays celebrity-comedians different amounts from one another.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/01/how-much-does-netflix-pay-for-15-minutes-of-stand-.html\n |title=How Much Does Netflix Pay for 15 Minutes of Stand-Up?\n |last=Simons\n |first=Seth\n |date=24 January 2018\n |website=PASTE\n |access-date=3 February 2019}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/netflix-is-driving-la-comedy-gold-rush-1119236\n |title='I Sold the Same Special Twice!' How Netflix Is Driving an L.A. Comedy Gold Rush\n |last= Abramovitch\n |first=Seth\n |date=15 June 2018\n |website=The Hollywood Reporter\n |publisher=Prometheus Global Media, LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote= Netflix is wooing superstar comics with eight-figure deals, including Dave Chappelle (a reported $60 million), Louis C.K. ($26 million), Amy Schumer ($20 million) and Jim Gaffigan ($10 million).}}</ref>\n\nThe cruise-circuit comedian can make up to $10,000 per week,<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> some $85,000 per year; and, a college-circuit comedian can make six figures per year or thousands of dollars per gig.<ref name=NYTC>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/04/arts/stand-ups-and-their-salaries.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=Clever, How They Earn That Laugh\n |last=Zinoman\n |first=Jason\n |last2=Megan\n |first2=Angelo\n |date=2012-11-02\n |website=The New York Times\n |access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.dailyeasternnews.com/2009/03/27/quick-witted-burress-set-for-laughs/\n |title='Quick-witted' Burress set for laughs\n |last=Holm \n |first=Heather\n |date=26 March 2009\n |website=Daily Eastern News: Tell the truth and don\u2019t be afraid\n |publisher=The Daily Eastern News\n |access-date=8 February 2019\n |quote=[[Hannibal Burress]] was the most popular comedian in Caponera\u2019s (2009) price range of $2,000.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/09/thats-not-funny/399335/\n |title=That's Not Funny! Today's college students can't seem to take a joke.\n |last=Flanagan\n |first=Caitlin\n |date=September 2015\n |website=The Atlantic\n |access-date=26 January 2019\n |quote=Keith is one of the kings of the college circuit. A few years ago, he was the most-booked college comic, playing 120 campuses. He charges $2,300 for a single performance.}}</ref> Christian circuit comedy headliners make $1,500-$2,500 per show.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/zng4je/gods-comics-inside-the-world-of-christian-standup-comedy-456 |title=God's Comics: Inside the World of Christian Stand-Up\n |last=Leon\n |first=Harmon\n |date=1 July 2015\n |website=VICE\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=18 February 2019\n |quote=Headliners can reap $1,500 to $2,500 per church comedy show}}</ref> Although one source states that newer comics on the national (L.A.) circuit make $1,250-$2,500 per week, another source claims that this is very innacurate, and the amount of money one makes is closer to $20 for a spot.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/netflix-is-driving-la-comedy-gold-rush-1119236\n |title='I Sold the Same Special Twice!' How Netflix Is Driving an L.A. Comedy Gold Rush\n |last= Abramovitch\n |first=Seth\n |date=15 June 2018\n |website=The Hollywood Reporter\n |publisher=Prometheus Global Media, LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=A newer comic on the national circuit can earn anywhere from $1,250 to $2,500 per week, according to one prominent touring agent; more established names can pull in anywhere from $10,000 to $100,000 in the same period.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/06/comedians-reveal-what-the-l-a-stand-up-scene-actually-pays.html\n |title=Comedians Reveal What the L.A. Stand-up Scene Actually Pays\n |last=Caffir\n |first=Justin\n |date=20 June 2018\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote= it\u2019s very hard to make that amount even on the road\u2026To mislead someone with a figure that is beyond an exaggeration and just ridiculous.}}</ref>\n\nFamous comedians may pay lesser comedians thousands of dollars for jokes and hire them on as writers,<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=36\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=Bigger name comics have been known to pay thousands for jokes and hire writers...After a famous comic has an HBO Special, they almost always hire writers to help them pump out more material.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Barry Sand\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/239\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/239 239\u2013240]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Comics need material badly, especially once they get to be in demand\u2014they\u2019ve got to keep coming up with the stuff...Often, once a comic becomes successful, his requirements for material begin to exceed his ability to create it\u2014particularly in the case of TV spots, which \u2018eat\u2019 it instantly.\n }}</ref> but many famous comedians do not reveal this, as it is considered a taboo to admit purchasing material for stand-up comedy sets.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/09/should-all-standup-comics-write-their-own-jokes.html\n |title=Should All Standup Comics Write Their Own Jokes?\n |last= Hesse\n |first=Josiah \n |date=25 September 2014\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref> Comedians may knowingly sell plagiarized jokes.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=[[Rita Rudner]]\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/241\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/241 241]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[T]hat\u2019s another thing people do\u2014write down jokes they see on TV, then sell them to other comics who don\u2019t realize what they\u2019re doing.\n }}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nMany of the earliest vaudeville-era stand-ups gained their greater recognition on radio. They often opened their programs with topical monologues, characterized by [[ad-lib]]s and discussions about anything from the latest films to a missed birthday. Each program tended to be divided into the opening monologue, musical number, followed by a [[sketch comedy|skit]] or story routine. A \"feud\" between [[Fred Allen]] and [[Jack Benny]] was used as comic material for nearly a decade.\n\n[[Home Box Office|HBO]] presented comedians uncensored for the first time, beginning with [[Robert Klein]] in 1975, and was instrumental in reaching larger audiences. George Carlin was a perennial favorite, who appeared in 14 HBO comedy specials.\n\nContinuing that tradition, most modern stand-up comedians use television or motion pictures to reach a level of success and recognition unattainable in the comedy-club circuit alone.\n\nLate-night talk shows and award show ceremonies are commonly hosted by comedians, delivering monologues similar to stand-up.\n\nSince the mid-2000s, online video-sharing sites such as [[YouTube]] have also provided a venue for stand-up comedians, and many comedians' performances can be viewed online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailybits.com/watch-stand-up-comedians-on-youtube/|title=Watch Stand Up Comedians on YouTube|accessdate=2008-09-27 |work= Daniel Scocco |publisher=Dailybits.com |date=2008-09-23}}</ref>\n\nAn Amazon TV show, ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'', depicts the fictional life of a woman comedian, set in the late 1950s. She often interacts with [[Lenny Bruce]].\n\n== List of comedians ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[List of comedians]]\n* [[List of humorists]]\n* [[List of stand-up comedians]]\n* [[List of musical comedians]]\n* [[List of Australian comedians]]\n* [[List of British comedians]]\n* [[List of Canadian comedians]]\n* [[List of Finnish comedians]]\n* [[List of German language comedians]]\n* [[List of Indian comedians]]\n* [[List of Italian comedians]]\n* [[List of Mexican comedians]]\n* [[List of Puerto Rican comedians]]\n* [[List of Filipino Comedian]]\n}}\n\n== Other types of stand-up ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Macchietta]] \u2014 Italian 19th century comedy act\n* [[Manzai]] \u2014 style of [[Double act]] comedy in Japan\n* [[Mandan (comedy)|Mandan]] \u2014 style of stand-up comedy in Japan\n* [[Rakugo]] \u2014 Japanese verbal solo entertainment similar to stand-up comedy, but kneeling instead of standing.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Barry\n |first=Dave\n |author-link=Dave Barry\n |year=1992\n |title=Dave Barry Does Japan\n |publisher=Ballantine Books\n |location=New York\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/davebarrydoesjap00dave/page/129 129]\n |isbn=0-449-90810-0\n |url=https://archive.org/details/davebarrydoesjap00dave/page/129\n }}</ref>\n* [[Xiangsheng]] \u2014 Chinese traditional stand-up comedy \n}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* {{Portal-inline|Comedy |size=tiny}}\n* [[2019 in stand-up comedy]]\n* [[Aesthetic distance]]\n* [[Comedy troupe]]\n* [[Improvisational theatre]]\n* [[List of humor research publications]]\n* [[Non sequitur (literary device)|Non-sequitur]]\n* [[Radio comedy]]\n* [[Roast (comedy)|Roast]]\n* [[Situation comedy]]\n* [[Stage name]]\n* ''[[The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith]]''\n* [[The Clown's Prayer]]\n* ''[[The History of Comedy]]''\n* [[Theories of humor]]\n* ''[[WTF with Marc Maron]]''\n* ''[[You Made It Weird with Pete Holmes]]''\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/09/the-joke-i-most-regret.html\n |title=The Joke I Most Regret: Comedians reflect on old material, evolution, and accountability.\n |last=Abriss\n |first=Erik\n |date=6 September 2018\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |access-date=3 February 2019}}\n*{{cite journal\n| last= Conway\n| first= Andrew\n| date= 11 December 1995\n| others=Collected by Robert Nelson, Scott Meltzer, Ngaio Bealum and Dave Gomez\n| title= You're Ugly, Your Dick Is Small, and Everybody Fucks Your Mother\u2014The Stand-Up Comedian's Response to the Heckler\n| url= http://www.juggling.org/~conway/juggler/MAL.TXT \n| format=Text\n| journal=Maledicta, the International Journal of Verbal Aggression\n| location=Santa Rosa, CA\n| publisher=Maledicta Press\n| volume= 11\n| isbn=978-0916500313\n| access-date=25 March 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/the-filter/11013908/10-things-no-one-tells-you-about-stand-up-comedy.html\n |title=10 things no one tells you about stand-up comedy\n |last=Dessau\n |first=Bruce\n |date=11 August 2014\n |website=The Telegraph\n |access-date=27 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/may/23/germany.features11\n |title=Lost in translation\n |last=Lee\n |first=Stewart\n |date=23 May 2006\n |website=The Guardian\n |access-date=26 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.pattonoswalt.com/index.cfm?page=spew&id=167\n |title=A Closed Letter to Myself About Thievery, Heckling and Rape Jokes\n |last=Oswalt\n |first=Patton\n |date=14 June 2014\n |website=Patton Oswalt\n |publisher=Patton Oswalt\n |access-date=3 February 2019}}\n* {{cite journal\n| last       = Pauline\n| first      = Sherlock\n| year       = 2016\n| title      =The Tyrannies of Distance: From Cairns to the Melbourne International Comedy Festival\n| url        = https://journals.jcu.edu.au/etropic/article/view/3304/3249\n| journal    = James Cook University: eTropic\n| location   = Australia\n| volume     = 15\n| issue      = 1\n| pages      = 79-88\n| access-date = 25 March 2020}}\n*{{cite news\n| last         = Ruben\n| first        = Adam\n| date         = 17 July 2019\n| title        = What can scientists learn from stand-up comedy?\n| url          = https://www.sciencemag.org/careers/2019/07/what-can-scientists-learn-stand-comedy\n| work         = Science Magazine\n| publisher    = American Association for the Advancement of Science.\n| access-date  = 31 July 2019}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.comedysoapbox.com/resources.cfm\n |title=Resources\n |last1=[[Steve Hofstetter|Hoffstetter]]\n |first1=Steve\n |last2=McDermott\n |first2=Danny\n |website=COMEDYSOAPBOX\n |access-date=26 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/comedy/\n |title=Vulture: Comedy\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/comedy\n |title=The Guardian: Comedy\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://headgum.com/good-one-a-podcast-about-jokes\n |title=Good One: A Podcast About Jokes\n |last=Fox\n |first=Jesse David\n |year=2015\u20132019\n |website=HEADGUM\n |publisher=HEADGUM, LLC\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://www.letstalkaboutsets.com/\n |title=Let's Talk About Sets\n |last1=McBride\n |first1=Jeff\n |last2=Tweed\n |first2=Harrison\n |website=letstalkaboutsets\n |publisher=Jeffcorp Enterprises: A Jeff Company\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}\n*{{cite web\n |url=https://thepodglomerate.com/shows/historyofstandup/\n |title=The History of Standup\n |last1=[[Wayne Federman|Federman]]\n |first1=Wayne\n |last2=Steven\n |first2=Andrew \n |publisher=The Podglomerate\n |website=Podglomerate\n |access-date=10 March 2019}}\n\n{{Comedy footer}}\n\n[[Category:Stand-up comedy| ]]\n[[Category:Comedy genres]]\n[[Category:Comedy theatre]]\n[[Category:Humour]]\n[[Category:Live stand-up comedy shows| ]]\n[[Category:Show business terms]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect2|Stand-up|Stand Up Comedy|the U2 song|Stand Up Comedy (song)|other uses|Stand Up (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Ahmed Mamow Parkteatret (231834).jpg|thumb|Ahmed Mamow on the stage at Late Night Fredag on Parkteatret]]\n\n'''Stand-up comedy''' is a [[Comedy|comic]] style in which a [[comedian]] performs in front of a live audience, usually speaking directly to them. The performer is commonly known as a '''comic''', '''stand-up comic''', '''comedian''', '''comedienne''', '''stand-up comedian''', or simply a '''stand-up'''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Fisher, J ''Tommy Cooper: Always Leave Them Laughing'' {{ISBN|978-0-00-721511-9}}</ref> Comedians give the illusion that they are [[dialogue|dialoguing]], but in actuality, they are [[monologue|monologuing]] a grouping of humorous [[narrative|stories]], [[jokes]] and [[one-line joke|one-liners]], typically called a [[shtick]], routine, [[Performer|act]], or set.{{refn| <ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=https://www.thehistoryofstandup.com/episodes/s2-ep-06-meltdown\n | title=S2 Ep. 06: Meltdown\n | website=The History of Standup\n | publisher=The Podglomerate\n | host=[[Wayne Federman]]\n | others=[[Dana Gould]]\n | date=9 July 2019\n | time=21:40-21:54\n | access-date=27 August 2019\n | quote=A low ceiling and proximity to the stage is important because standup comedy is not a performance. It is a conversation in which the comedian does all of the talking.\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andreamorris/2018/07/26/a-robot-stand-up-comedian-learns-the-nuts-and-bolts-of-comedy/\n |title=A Robot Stand-Up Comedian Learns The Nuts And Bolts Of Comedy\n |last=Morris\n |first=Andrea\n |date=26 July 2018\n |website=Forbes\n |publisher=Forbes Media LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=[A lot of] stand-up comedy\u2026as a general art form\u2026is pre-scripted}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/16 16]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Jerry Seinfeld explains: \u2018Comedy is a dialogue, not a monologue\u2014that\u2019s what makes an act click. The laughter becomes the audience\u2019s part, and the comedian responds\u2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Stewart Lee\n | date =3 July 2013\n | title =On Not Writing\n | medium =YouTube\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IrXVaytvJtQ\n | access-date =13 February 2019\n | format =Lecture\n | time =48:54-48:58\n |location=St Edmund Hall\n | publisher =University of Oxford\n | quote =On the whole, you have to give the illusion that it\u2019s a dialogue}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=190\n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/90 90]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=A comic's material about his life may have some connection to reality, but basically an act is just that, an ''act''\u2014it\u2019s a fictionalized account with a few actual facts thrown in to make the act believable and, perhaps, more relevant to people\u2019s lives.}}</ref>}} Some stand-up comedians use [[prop comedy|props]], [[comedy music|music]] or [[Magic (illusion)|magic tricks]]<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Martin\n |first=Steve\n |year=2007\n |title=Born Standing Up: A Comic's Life\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Scribner\n |pages=40\u201342\n |isbn=978-1-4165-5364-9\n |quote=I was demonstrating tricks eight to twelve hours a day\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bornstandingupco00mart\n }}</ref> to enhance their acts. Stand-up comedy is stated to be the \"freest form of comedy writing\" that is regarded as a fictionalized \"extension of\" the person performing.{{refn|<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Jerry Seinfeld\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=199\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=That\u2019s the goal\u2014to become yourself.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Mendrinos\n |first=James\n |year=2004\n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc.\n |page=12\n |isbn=1-59257-231-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://craftsmanship.net/the-art-of-the-joke/\n |title=The Art of the Joke\n |last= Munro\n |first=David\n |year=2018\n |website=CRAFTSMANSHIP Quarterly: The Architecture of Excellence\n |publisher=The Craftsmanship Initiative\n |access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2012/08/stand-up-comedians-and-their-alternate-on-stage-personas.html\n |title=Stand-Up Comedians and Their Alternate On-Stage Personas\n |last=Evans\n |first=Bradford\n |date=7 August 2012\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/90 90\u201391]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[A stand-up\u2019s] act [is a] fictionalized account with a few actual facts thrown in to make the act believable and, perhaps more relevant to people\u2019s lives...Every stand-up goes onstage as a character to some extent. Some may adopt a persona that\u2019s very similar to their own personality, but it\u2019s still a separate entity...even observational comics...use truth...as a foundation on which to build jokes by taking the truth to its farthest [sic] extreme.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/262\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/262 262]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=(loosely) autobiographical comedy is the dominant form of stand-up today.\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Gary Shandling\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=209\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I [Gary Shandling] think you can only be on stage what you are in real life.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last         = Katzif\n | first        = Mike\n | date         = 16 November 2018\n | title        = Mo Amer: Working The Classroom Comedy Circuit\n | url          = https://www.npr.org/2018/11/16/668601188/mo-amer-working-the-classroom-comedy-circuit\n | work         = NPR\n | access-date  = 11 September 2019\n | quote        = [I]f you're not real\u2026people will sniff that out.}}</ref>}}\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Bridget Christie Parkteatret Crap \u00e5pp\u00e5 Park (181801).jpg|right|thumb|Bridget Christie at Parkteatret. The event is part of Crap Comedy festival 2017 and took place on 28. January 2017 in Oslo.]]\n[[File:Jinx Yeo at restaurant Kaisla.jpg|thumb|right|Jinx Yeo, a [[Singapore]]an stand-up comedian, performing in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]].]]\nSome of the main types of humor in stand-up comedy include [[observational comedy]], [[ribaldry|blue comedy]], [[black comedy|dark comedy]], [[clean comedy]], and [[cringe comedy]].\n[[Alternative comedy|Alternative stand-up comedy]] deviates from the traditional, mainstream comedy by breaking either joke structure, performing in an untraditional scene, or breaking an audience's expectations; this includes the use of [[shaggy dog story|shaggy dog stories]] and [[anti-humor|anti-jokes]].\n\nStand-up comedy is often performed in corporate events, [[comedy club]]s, [[bar]]s and [[pub]]s, [[nightclub]]s, [[Neo-Burlesque|neo-burlesques]], [[college]]s and [[theatre]]s (audiences will give applause breaks more often in theaters<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Louis C.K.\n | date =22 April 2011\n | title =Talking Funny\n | trans-title =\n | medium =Film\n | time =11:55-12:12}}</ref>).<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Chris Dipetta\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/68 68]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=The average club seats [250] people}}</ref> Outside live performance, stand-up is often distributed commercially via [[television]], [[DVD]], [[Compact disc|CD]] and the [[internet]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref name=\"signonsandiego.com\">[http://www.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20050624/news_1c24ferrell.html ''Fearless delivery sets Will Ferrell apart.''] ''The Denver Post'', 24 June 2005. Accessed on 29 March 2010.</ref>\n\nIt can take an amateur comedian about 10 years to perfect the technique needed to be a professional comedian;<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=George Wallace\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=240\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=How did you answer them? 'By being [[George Wallace (American comedian)|George Wallace]], and finding out who you are as a comedian. And that takes between seven and eleven years.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Jerry Seinfeld\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=200\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=How long did it take you to figure out your individual comedic essence? 'I'd [Jerry Seinfeld] say ten years.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Louis C.K., Charlie Rose\n | date =7 May 2014\n | title =Louis C.K.\n | medium =TV Show\n | language =English\n | url =https://charlierose.com/videos/19176\n | access-date =3 February 2019\n | format =Interview\n | time =3:59-4:03\n | publisher =HBO\n |quote=A stage presence comes pretty quickly [but] how to write jokes and how to generate material and know it\u2019s going to work; [concerning these, the] first ten years are building the [base] skills}}</ref> this is a constant process of learning through failure.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = Bobby Lee (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =1:02:38-1:02:48\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =Bombing is a necessary event. It\u2019s the only way one gets better, but every time it happens, it\u2019s very painful.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people = John Thomson (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =1:02:52-1:02:55\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =You\u2019ve got to die to get good.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2014/03/18/hannibal-buress-bombing-can-be-good/\n |title=Hannibal Buress: 'Bombing Can Be Good'\n |last=Seabaugh\n |first=Julie\n |others=Hannibal Buress\n |date=18 March 2014\n |website=The Village VOICE\n |publisher=VILLAGE VOICE, LLC\n |access-date=4 February 2019\n |quote= Yeah, bombing can be good\u2026you grow up and realize it\u2019s about continuing to work. It\u2019s about making progress.}}</ref>\n\nAs the name implies, \"stand-up\" comedians usually perform their material while standing, though this is not mandatory. Similar acts performed while seated can be referred to as \"sit-down comedy\".\n\n\"Comedians are more likely to exhibit psychotic[-like] traits\" than the average person; most comedians display \"magical thinking\" and are \"introverted[ly]\" \"[[Anhedonia|anhedoni[c]]]\".<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/02/the-dark-psychology-of-being-a-good-comedian/284104/\n |title=The Dark Psychology of Being a Good Comedian\n |last=Khazan\n |first=Olga\n |date=27 February 2014\n |website=The Atlantic\n |access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Stand-up comedy show==\n\n[[File:Tiffany Haddish at Incirlik.jpg|thumb|right|Tiffany Haddish, comedian, tells jokes to audience members during a performance October 21, 2013, at Incirlik Air Base, Turkey.]]\n\nIn stand-up comedy, the feedback of the audience is instant and crucial for the comedian's act, even from the moment they enter the venue.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Lee\n |first=Stewart\n |year=2010\n |title=How I Escaped My Certain Fate: The Life and Deaths of a Stand-up Comedian\n |location=London, UK\n |publisher=faber and faber Ltd\n |page=43\n |isbn=978-0-571-25481-1\n |quote=A show begins the moment the audience walk into a venue.}}</ref> Audiences expect a stand-up comedian to provide a constant stream of laughs, calculated at four to six laughs per minute,{{refn|<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Chris Rock (interviewee)\n | year =2017\n | title =Dying Laughing\n | medium =Motion picture\n | language =English\n | time =11:24-11:31\n | publisher =Gravitas Ventures\n | quote =A lot of comedians just want laugh, laugh, laugh\u2026every, what is it, 15 seconds they say?}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2017/oct/04/learning-laughter-an-experts-guide-on-how-to-master-standup-comedy \n |title=Learning laughter: an expert's guide on how to master standup comedy\n |last=Nevins\n |first=Jake\n |date=4 October 2017\n |website=The Guardian\n |access-date=26 January 2019\n |quote= Comedy club audiences...expect upwards of four laughs per minute.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.realfirststeps.com/4164/jokes-minute-standup-comedy-material/\n |title=How Many Jokes Are In A Minute Of Stand-up Comedy Material?\n |last=Roye\n |first=Steve\n |website=Stand-up Comedy Tips\n |access-date=26 January 2019\n |quote=If a comedian wants to generate headliner laughter levels, they need to average 4-6+ laughs per minute.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/253\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/253 253\u2013254]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=As each comic\u2019s usage of material varies (some say they use as few as two jokes a minute, other comics say they need a laugh every fifteen seconds or the act goes \u2018in the toilet\u2019)}}</ref>}} and a performer is always under pressure to deliver, especially the first two minutes.{{refn|<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Frances-White\n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur\n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Stephen K Amos\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=209\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=The first two minutes is very important with a stand-up}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Pete Lee\n | year =2017\n | title =I Need You To Kill\n | medium =Motion picture\n | time =31:27-31:56\n | publisher =Comedy Dynamics\n | quote =I call the first two minutes, your flash. And that\u2019s where you\u2026go up there and\u2026hook them with whatever material it is, so that they know exactly what\u2019s funny about you and they trust you and they\u2019ll come along with you for everything.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2004/aug/16/edinburgh04.edinburghfestival3\n |title=How can he show his face?\n |last=MacInnes\n |first=Paul\n |date=15 August 2004\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |others=Karen Koren\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote= If you don't make them laugh in the first two minutes, you're fucked}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Neill\n |first=Geoffrey\n |date=22 December 2015\n |title=Hitting Your Funny Bone: Writing Stand-up Comedy, and Other Things That Make You Swear\n |location=San Bernardino, CA\n |page=Chapter 5\n |isbn=9781515180661\n |quote=If you have a strong first minute\u2026the minutes that follow will be great, too.}}</ref>}} The late [[Phyllis Diller]] holds the record for most laughs per minute, at twelve laughs per minute.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote from Phyllis Diller, 'who is listed in ''The Guinness Book of World Records'' as having gotten the most laughs per minute of any comic alive or dead'\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=181\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=I [Phyllis Diller] actually got twelve laughs in one minute from an audience\u2026Most comics do setup, payoff, setup, payoff, in other words six jokes per minute. In my case of twelve, ''one'' setup got ''twelve'' payoffs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last= Gorman\n| first= Steve\n| date= 20 August 2012\n| title= Pioneering comedian Phyllis Diller dies at age 95\n| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainment-us-diller/pioneering-comedian-phyllis-diller-dies-at-age-95-idUSBRE87J0PZ20120821\n| work= Reuters\n| access-date= 28 March 2020\n| quote= Diller prided herself on keeping her jokes tightly written and boasted that she held a world record for getting 12 laughs a minute.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last= King\n| first= Susan\n| date= 22 December 2006\n| title= Diller can still pack a punch line\n| url= https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-dec-22-et-diller22-story.html\n| work= Los Angeles Times\n| access-date= 28 March 2020\n| quote=[Phyllis Diller] still holds the Guinness Book of World Records for doling out 12 punch lines a minute.}}</ref>\n\n===Basic format===\n====Opener, feature, headliner====\nA show begins with an opening act, known as a host, ''[[wikt:Special:search/compere|comp\u00e8re]]'' (UK),<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/1664527.pdf\n |title=Stand-up as interaction: Performance and Audience in Comedy Venues\n |last=Rutter\n |first=Jason\n |year=1997\n |department=Department of Sociology\n |website=CORE\n |publisher=University of Saford: Institute for Social Research\n |pages=149\u2013150\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> [[master of ceremonies]] (MC/emcee), or simply \"opener\" who, for 10\u201312 minutes,<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.malonecomedy.com/blog/10-rules-to-mceeing-a-comedy-show\n |title=8 Rules to Emceeing a Comedy Show\n |last=Malone\n |first=Michael\n |website=Malone Comedy\n |publisher=Wav Records\n |access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> usually warms up the crowd, interacts with audience members, makes announcements, and then introduces the other performers;<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |pages=67\u201368\n |isbn=9781468004847}}</ref> this is followed by a \"middle\"/\"feature\" act that lasts 15\u201320 minutes but is expected to have \"30 minutes of solid material\"; the feature act is followed by the headliner, who performs for \"an hour.\"<ref name=MSU>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=195\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Ron White\n | year =2018\n | title = Ron White: If you Quit Listening, I\u2019ll Shut Up\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.netflix.com/title/80244900\n | access-date =15 April 2020\n | format =Motion Picture\n | time =39:21-39:41\n | quote =[T]raditionally in American comedy clubs, there\u2019s three acts: there\u2019s an opening act...a feature act\u2026and [then] a headliner}}</ref> An opener can also double as a feature for travelling headliners, with the opener performing a 25-minute set.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Martin\n |first=Steve\n |year=2007\n |title=Born Standing Up: A Comic's Life\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Scribner\n |pages=136, 139\n |isbn=978-1-4165-5364-9\n |quote=One week, I opened for a show...I was now capable of doing two different twenty-five-minute sets per evening\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bornstandingupco00mart}}</ref>\n\n====Showcase format====\nShowcase format has a host/MC with several other acts who perform for roughly equal lengths of time.<ref>{{cite book\n|year=2006\n|chapter=A Little Comedy From The Audience: Vic Henley\n|editor1-last=Shydner\n|editor1-first=Ritch\n|editor2-last=Schiff\n|editor2-first=Mark\n|title=I Killed: True Stories of the Road From America\u2019s Top Comics\n|url=http://www.standupstories.com\n|url-status=dead\n|others=[[Vic Henley]]\n|edition=First Paperback\n|location=New York\n|publisher=Three Rivers Press\n|page=222\n|isbn=978-0-307-38229-0\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501193623/http://www.standupstories.com:80/\n|archive-date=1 May 2012\n|access-date=15 April 2020\n|quote=[[The Comedy Store (London)\n|The Comedy Store in London]]\u2026[is] a showcase format, with a host and five comics doing sets, with\u2026[a] guest thrown in from time to time.}}</ref>\n\n===One-person show===\n{{Main|Solo performance}}\n\nThese one-hour, headlining performances focus on storytelling.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote by Mark Travis\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=213\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=A one-person show has a story line. While a stand-up comic focuses on getting an immediate reaction from the audience after every joke, a person doing a solo show takes the audience on a journey.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote by [[Christopher Titus]]\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=216\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=A one-person show is not just an hour of stand-up. It has to be dramatic ''and'' funny.}}</ref> One-person, stand-up comedy shows became popular in the 1990s, with no consensus for what separates stand-up acts from one-person shows.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/02/theater-review-birbiglias-thank-god-for-jokes.html\n |title=Mike Birbiglia\u2019s New One-Man Show: Stories About Jokes; Jokes About Stories\n |last=Fox\n |first=Jesse David\n |date=28 February 2017\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=28 March 2020\n |quote=Though there have been one-person shows for ages, the first\u00a0comedian\u00a0to do a one-person show in a big way was Lily Tomlin\u2026However, it wasn\u2019t until the \u201890s, correlating with the rise of storytelling, that the stand-up one-person show really blew up\u2026for the shows that consisted of thematically stringing funny stories together, it was always hard to decide what exactly made them one-man shows and not stand-up acts.}}</ref>\n\n===Open mic===\n{{Main|Open mic}}\n\nMany smaller venues hold open mic events, where anyone can take the stage and perform for the audience. This offers an opportunity for amateur performers to hone their craft and perhaps to break into the profession, or for established professionals to work on their material.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.pattonoswalt.com/index.cfm?page=spew&id=167\n |title=A Closed Letter to Myself About Thievery, Heckling and Rape Jokes\n |last=Oswalt\n |first=Patton\n |date=14 June 2014\n |website=Patton Oswalt\n |publisher=Patton Oswalt\n |access-date=3 February 2019\n |quote=Open mikes are where, as a comedian [like Daniel Tosh and his controversy], you\u2019re supposed to be allowed to fuck up.}}\n</ref> Industry scouts will sometimes go to watch open mics.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://saraschaefer.com/2012/03/advice-to-a-young-comedian-myself/\n |title=Advice to a Young Comedian (& Myself)\n |last=Schaefer\n |first=Sara\n |date=16 March 2012\n |website=Sara Schaefer\n |access-date=1 February 2019\n |quote=the next day, my friend who was also on the show [in a theatre above a porn shop across from the Port Authority], told me a scout from casting at Fox was in the audience and they wanted to meet with him.}}</ref> Breaking into the business requires \"10 minute[s]\" of \"A\" material. Roadhouses (remote clubs) start booking people for \"20 minutes of 'A' material\".<ref name=MSU /> \"A\" material means getting a big laugh at least \"75% of the time\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=197\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref>\n\n===Bringer shows===\n\"Bringer shows\" are open mics that require amateur performers to bring a specified number of paying guests to receive stage time. Some view this as exploitation, while others disagree.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/correspondents/2012/09/10/16114/what_do_bringer_shows_really_bring_to_the_circuit%3F\n |title=What do 'bringer' shows REALLY bring to the circuit?\n |last=Dunican\n |first=Angus\n |date=10 September 2012\n |website=Chortle\n |access-date=28 January 2019\n |quote=it gets tarred with the brush of new-act exploitation and lumped in with less scrupulous nights and the insidious blight of pay-to-play...[but] I, personally, have found it to be a very nice room.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/article/how-to-quit-your-job-get-into-comedy.html\n |title=I Want Out How to Leave the Boring Job You Don't Like and Start Your Comedy Career\n |last= Kelly-Clyne\n |first=Luke\n |date=20 September 2018\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=\n |quote= In order to get stage time at [bringer shows]\u2026you [have to] bring\u20265 to 15 friends, each of whom must show up and agree to buy at least two drinks\u2026Some people think bringers are a scam, and they kind of are. They\u2019re a cash grab for club owners}}</ref> The guests usually have to pay a cover charge and there is often a minimum number of drinks that must be ordered. These shows usually have a \"showcase\" format. Different comedy clubs have different requirements for their bringer shows. Gotham Comedy Club in New York City, for example, usually has ten-person bringers, while Broadway Comedy Club in New York City usually has six-person bringers.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.jimrichardson.com/stand-upcomedyworkshop.com/audition/bringerShows.html\n |title=Evil \"Bringer Shows\" & \"Pay-to-Play Shows\" Are even worse Than the already discredited Open Mic system\n |last=Richardson\n |first=Jim\n |date=11 December 2013\n |website=Jim Richardson's Organized Comedy\n |access-date=28 January 2019\n |quote=Some clubs require 10 bringers/show. If you show up with 9 people, you will not get on and your friends will not get their money back.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/24/arts/my-brief-weird-life-as-a-stand-up-comic.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=My Brief, Weird Life as a Stand-Up Comic\n |last=Strauss\n |first=Neil\n |date=24 January 1999\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |access-date=2 February 2019\n |quote=Clubs like Caroline's will ask for 15 people.}}</ref> In the '90s, the New York Comedy Club had pre-shows that were bringer shows; they also had audition scams with an \"accelerated pre-show program.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/24/arts/my-brief-weird-life-as-a-stand-up-comic.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=My Brief, Weird Life as a Stand-Up Comic\n |last=Strauss\n |first=Neil\n |date=24 January 1999\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |access-date=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Guest set===\nThis is an unpaid, five-to-ten-minute time slot (during the emcee's time slot of a professional show) that is essentially an audition to get booked for paid gigs.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=63\n |isbn=9781468004847}}</ref>\n\n==The comedian's set==\n===Stand-up joke===\nIn stand-up comedy, a \"canned\" [[joke]]<ref>{{cite book\n |editor=Salvatore Attardo\n |year=2014\n |title=Encyclopedia of Humor Studies\n |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AXtZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA417&dq=%22canned+joke%22#v=onepage&q=%22canned%20joke%22&f=false\n |publisher=SAGE Publications, Inc.\n |page=417\n |isbn=978-1-4129-9909-0\n |quote=A canned joke is a generally short narrative ending in a punchline\u2026[that] the speaker has memorized.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/1664527.pdf\n |title=Stand-up as interaction: Performance and Audience in Comedy Venues\n |last=Rutter\n |first=Jason\n |year=1997\n |department=Department of Sociology\n |website=CORE\n |publisher=University of Saford: Institute for Social Research\n |pages=188\u2013189\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> is made of a \"[[premise]]...[[Point of view (philosophy)|point of view]]\" and \"[[subversion|twist]]\" ending.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Mendrinos \n |first=James \n |year=2004 \n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc. \n |page=46 \n |isbn=1-59257-231-6\n |quote=[T]he Universal Joke Formula: Premise + Point of View + Twist = Joke}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |page=104\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=we can craft a joke just by creating and then defeating that specific expectation...introduction, validation, violation}}</ref> A joke contains the least amount of information necessary to be conveyed, understood, and laughed at;<ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://archive.org/details/psychologyofhumo00martrich\n |title=The Psychology of Humor: An Integrative Approach\n |last=Martin\n |first=Rod A.\n |year=2007\n |orig-year=2006\n |department=Department of Psychology: University of Western Ontario\n |website=Internet Archive\n |publisher=Burlington, MA : Elsevier Academic Press\n |location=Ontario, Canada\n |page=2\n |type=Interactive Online Book\n |isbn=978-0123725646\n |access-date=18 February 2019\n |quote=a joke is a context-free and self-contained unit of humor that carries within itself all the information needed for it to be understood and enjoyed.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Neill\n |first=Geoffrey\n |date=22 December 2015\n |title=Hitting Your Funny Bone: Writing Stand-up Comedy, and Other Things That Make You Swear\n |location=San Bernardino, CA\n |page=Chapter 4\n |isbn=9781515180661\n |quote=A setup is the information a person needs to get the joke.}}</ref> the setup contains the information needed by the audience in order to understand the punchline.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=126\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0\n |quote=The setup is the essential information the audience needs in order to get the punchline}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=14\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5\n |quote=A joke\u2026must have all the information implicit in the setup, so\u2026the punchline\u2026makes sense.}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=https://www.letstalkaboutsets.com/048/\n | title=Episode 48 The Setup\n | website=Let\u2019s Talk About Sets\n | host=Jeff McBride, Harrison Tweed\n | others=Geoffrey Asmus\n | time=12:45-13:05\n | access-date=29 August 2019\n | quote=It\u2019s the first half of the joke\u2026It\u2019s the first part\u2026I\u2019ve seen it said that it\u2019s the part that gives all the information you need, so that people understand the joke, but I would take it a step a little bit to the side of that\u2026[the setup] is whatever is needed to make the joke work.}}</ref> Most of stand-up comedy's jokes are the [[Theories of humor#Incongruous juxtaposition theory|juxtaposition of two incongruous things]].{{refn|<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Mendrinos \n |first=James \n |year=2004 \n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy \n |others=Bret Watson \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc. \n |page=51 \n |isbn=1-59257-231-6 \n |quote=It seems like 99% of comedy comes from juxtaposing two things that don't seem to go together}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n |url=https://www.standupcomedyclinic.com/powerful-tool-joke-writing/ \n |title=The Most Powerful Tool for Your Joke Writing \n |last=Corley \n |first=Jerry \n |website=standupcomedyclinic \n |access-date=27 January 2019 \n |quote=You turn it into a juxtaposition of two ideas and create jokes.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |url=https://archive.org/details/psychologyofhumo00martrich\n |title=The Psychology of Humor: An Integrative Approach\n |last=Martin\n |first=Rod A.\n |year=2007\n |orig-year=2006\n |department=Department of Psychology: University of Western Ontario\n |website=Internet Archive\n |publisher=Burlington, MA : Elsevier Academic Press\n |location=Ontario, Canada\n |page=85\n |type=Interactive Online Book\n |isbn=978-0123725646\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/1664527.pdf\n |title=Stand-up as interaction: Performance and Audience in Comedy Venues\n |last=Rutter\n |first=Jason\n |year=1997\n |department=Department of Sociology\n |website=CORE\n |publisher=University of Saford: Institute for Social Research\n |page=17\n |access-date=8 March 2019\n |quote= Incongruity has been and remains the most influential approach to the study of humour even though superiority predates it by approximately two thousand years.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Luu\n| first        = Chi\n| date         = 12 June 2019\n| title        = The Dubious Art of the Dad Joke\n| url          = https://daily.jstor.org/the-dubious-art-of-the-dad-joke/\n| work         = JSTOR\n| publisher  = ITHAKA\n| access-date  = 15 June 2019\n|quote = At its core, humor seems to be all about incongruity.}}</ref>}} According to the founding editor of [[The Onion]], there are eleven types of jokes.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://bigthink.com/stephen-johnson/every-joke-falls-in-one-of-these-11-categories-according-to-the-founder-of-the-onion\n |title=Every Joke Falls in One of 11 Categories, Says Founding Editor of The Onion\n |last=Johnson\n |first=Stephen\n |date=24 March 2017\n |website=Big Think\n |publisher=The Big Think, Inc. \n |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref> Stand-up comedians will normally deliver their jokes in the form of a [[Joke#Telling jokes|typical joke structure]], using [[comic timing|comedic timing]] to deliver the setup and then the [[punch line]].<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=1 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> Stand-ups will normally frame their stories as having happened \"recently.\"<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://mentalfloss.com/article/88012/11-wisecracking-secrets-stand-comedians\n |title=11 Wisecracking Secrets of Stand-Up Comedians\n |last= Raga\n |first=Suzanne\n |date=27 October 2016\n |website=Mental Floss\n |publisher=Minute Media\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=[C]omedians will often say that something happened to them recently when it really happened years ago\u2014or may have never happened at all.}}</ref> The comedian's delivery of a joke\u2014the pause, inflection, \"ener[gy],\" and look\u2014is \"everything\".<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =George Carlin, Charlie Rose\n | date =26 March 1996\n | title =George Carlin\n | medium =TV Show\n | language =English\n | url =https://charlierose.com/videos/19176\n | access-date =1 February 2019\n | format =Interview\n | time =7:29-7:37\n | publisher =HBO\n}}</ref> Comedians often include taglines (dependent punchlines that follow another punchline)<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=38\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=Taglines are...very short [jokes that are]...delivered right as the original laughter from the punchline is dying down.}}</ref> and toppers (independent afterthoughts that follow a punchline).<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Mendrinos \n |first=James \n |year=2004 \n |title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to Writing Comedy \n |others=Bret Watson \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=ALPHA: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc. \n |page=93 \n |isbn=1-59257-231-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=61 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> \nSome sources may use tags, toppers, and afterthoughts as synonyms.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://nakedspeaker.com/2010/09/24/writing-for-stand-up-part-3-refining-jokes/\n |title=Writing for stand up part 3: Refining Jokes\n |author=Andrew\n |date=24 September 2010\n |website=thenakedspeaker: a public speaking blog\n |publisher=WordPress\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nA jokoid is a placeholder joke, which will eventually be superseded by a funnier joke.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |page=106\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=A jokoid fills the place on the page where a genuinely funny joke will eventually go}}</ref> Stock jokes are similar to jokoids (as placeholders) and are hack jokes that are for \"specific situations\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=36\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=Stock jokes are jokes that a comic has...that are pretty much hack jokes used for specific situations...they should only be used in certain situations until you can think of something better.}}</ref> A [[paraprosdokian]] is a popular method that is used by comedians, creating a surprising punchline that causes the listener to reinterpret the setup.<ref>{{cite book\n|last1=Leighton\n|first1=H. Vernon\n|year=2020\n|chapter=A Theory of Humor (Abridged) and the Comic Mechanisms of John Kennedy Toole\u2019s \u2018\u2019A Confederacy of Dunces\u2019\u2019\n|editor-last=Marsh\n|editor-first=Leslie\n|title=Theology and Geometry: Essays on John Kennedy Toole\u2019s A Confederacy of Dunces (Politics, Literature, & Film)\n|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Theology_and_Geometry/BjHNDwAAQBAJ?gbpv=0\n|location=United Kingdom\n|publisher=Lexington Books\n|publication-date= 29 January 2020\n|pages=2-4\n|isbn=978-1-4985-8547-7\n|access-date=27 March 2020\n|quote=it is useful to examine the famous paraprosdokian, \u2018I\u2019ve had a perfectly wonderful evening, but this wasn\u2019t it.\u2019\u2026Within the cognitive incongruity aspect of humor\u2026Comedians often rely on shared knowledge with the audience to provide the second interpretation toward which the joke will pivot\u2026As the paraprosdokian above illustrates, in some humor events, the brain begins tentatively to assign the event of one interpretation but then is forced in surprise to reassign the event to a second interpretation.}}</ref> Stand-ups will often use the [[rule of three (writing)|rule of three]].<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =[[Simon Amstell]], [[Eddie Izzard]]\n | year =2011\n | title =The Art of Stand-Up\n | medium =TV\n | language =English\n | location =United Kingdom\n | publisher =BBC: One\n | quote =Simon Amstell states, 'I transcribed a couple of the tapes just to figure out what he [Eddie Izzard] was doing cause it just seemed so (pause) It wasn\u2019t like setup-punch. I would sort of underline words\u2026is that the rule of three? I don\u2019t know what ''that'' is.' Eddie Izzard states, 'it should be\u2014establish, reaffirm, and then you kill it on the third...you can keep reaffirming before you twist.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Hannibal Buress, Marcus Raboy\n | date =2014\n | title =Live from Chicago \n | medium =Audio\n | publisher =COMEDY CENTRAL\n | quote =They have a parades department. New Orleans police department has a parades department. There\u2019s homicide, there\u2019s narcotics, and there\u2019s parades. There\u2019s other departments too, but you know, rule of three, for comedy.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/151 151]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |quote=[Three is the] cadence [that makes] it the most important number in comedy.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/151\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |pages=123\u2013124\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5}}</ref> Comedians will normally include [[stylistic device|stylistic]] and [[comedic device|comedic]] devices, such as [[Figure of speech#Tropes|tropes]], [[idioms]], [[stop consonant]]s, and [[List of forms of word play|wordplay]].<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/63 63]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/63\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/249\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/249 249]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Seinfeld adds, \u2018any k sound is good\u2014it\u2019s a very strong letter that impinges on people.'\n }}</ref>\n\nA comedian's ideas and jokes will fail nine times out of ten; this may require a comedian to write hundreds of jokes to achieve enough successful ones to fill a set.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |pages=12\u201313\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=For every ten jokes you tell, nine will be trash\u2026you\u2019ll need hundreds and hundreds of failed jokes to build a decent body of work.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Louis C.K., Charlie Rose\n | date =7 May 2014\n | title =Louis C.K.\n | medium =TV Show\n | language =English\n | url =https://charlierose.com/videos/19176\n | access-date =3 February 2019\n | format =Interview\n | time =2:20-2:38\n | publisher =HBO\n |quote=failure is the road to being a great comic\u2026failure is not succeeding in the moment}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/109 109]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |quote=For every ten jokes written, only one might be acceptable\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/109\n }}</ref>\n\n===The set===\nA traditional set is made of jokes (setup and punchline), bits (a joke or \"3 or 4 jokes\"), and chunks (multiple bits linked by a topic that may last \"10-15 minutes\").<ref>{{cite web \n |url=http://www.goldcomedy.com/resources/put-together-five-minute-set/ \n |title=How to Write a 5-Minute Comedy Set \n |last=WAITHE \n |first=ELSA \n |website=Gold Comedy \n |access-date=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Craig Anton\n | date =28 January 2010\n | title =I Am Comic\n | medium =film\n | time =3:42-4:53\n | publisher =IFC Films\n | quote =a bit, 3 or 4 jokes in and around one central theme or idea\u2026[and then] 10-15 minutes, we call that a chunk}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Abby Stein\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/248\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/248 248]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=A \u2018bit,\u2019 Reiser explains, \u2018is a group of words used to incorporate a premise and all variations thereof\u2019\n }}</ref> Long bits must have the biggest laugh at their endings.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/magazine/100000001965963/jerry-seinfeld-how-to-write-a-joke-.html?action=click&contentCollection=magazine&module=lede&region=caption&pgtype=article\n |url-access=limited\n |title=Jerry Seinfeld: How to Write a Joke\n |last=Woodward\n |first=Jenny\n |date=20 December 2012\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=New York Times Company\n |format=video\n |access-date=1 February 2019\n |quote=If you have a long bit, the biggest laugh has to be at the end. It has to be. It can't be in the middle or the beginning.}}</ref> \nOnce a setup is established for a bit, the subsequent jokes should decrease in length.<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Helitzer\n |first1=Mel\n |last2=Shatz\n |first2=Mark\n |year=2005\n |title=Comedy Writing secrets: the best-selling book on how to think funny, write funny, act funny, and get paid for it\n |edition=2nd\n |location=Cincinnati, Ohio\n |publisher=Writer's Digest Books\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/245 245]\n |isbn=978-1-58297-357-9\n |quote=Since the setup has already been established, the second, third, and fourth jokes are short, shorter, shortest.\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comedywritingsec00heli_0/page/245\n }}</ref>\nA segue is the link between jokes.<ref name=\"Dean 2000 187\">{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=187 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=111\u2013112 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0}}</ref> \nA callback is a reference to a previous joke.<ref name=\"Dean 2000 187\"/><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=112\u2013114, 118 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=53\n |isbn=9781468004847}}</ref> Bombing refers to when a comedian has failed to get an intended laugh.<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Dean \n |first=Greg \n |year=2000 \n |title=Step by Step to Stand-up Comedy \n |location=Portsmouth, NH \n |publisher=Heinemann \n |page=190 \n |isbn=0-325-00179-0}}</ref> A stand-up comedian uses a [[persona]] or [[Character (arts)|character]] to deliver their jokes.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/91 91]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Every stand-up goes onstage as a character to some extent. Some may adopt a persona that\u2019s very similar to their own personality, but it\u2019s still a separate entity\u2014a person telling jokes as opposed to telling the truth, which no \u2018real\u2019 person does. Even observational comics, who base their material in reality, use the truth not as an end but as a foundation on which to build jokes by taking the truth to its farthest [sic] extreme.}}</ref> The quality of a comedian's material is more important than their persona,<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Budd Friedman\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=261\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=[W]hat\u2019s more important, material or delivery? I had to say it\u2019s the material.}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Budd Friedman\n | date =28 January 2010\n | title =I Am Comic\n | medium =film\n | time =31:25-31:34\n | publisher =IFC Films\n | quote =when the material is good, you can overlook anything}}</ref> unless they are well known.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/science-news/8496960/Why-comedians-get-laughs-for-even-their-worst-jokes.html\n |title=Why comedians get laughs for even their worst jokes\n |last=Alleyne\n |first=Richard\n |date=6 May 2011\n |website=The Telegraph\n |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=We argue that using the name of someone who people consider funny generates an expectancy of humour when hearing a joke.}}</ref> Other sources say that personality trumps material.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Irvin Arthur\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=274\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I [Irvin Arthur] firmly believe that it\u2019s the persona first, and then the material.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Abby Stein\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/252\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/252 252]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[P]ersonality is far more important than material\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Carter\n |first=Judy\n |year=2001\n |title=The Comedy Bible\n |others=Quote from Johnny Carson, quoted from ''The Great Comedians'', by Larry Wilde (1972)\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster\n |page=162\n |isbn=978-0-7432-0125-4\n |quote=Your delivery can save you if the material isn\u2019t up to par.}}</ref> A good comedian will create a [[Humor in Freud|tendentious-like tension]] that the audience releases with laughter.{{refn|<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Oliver Double\n | year =2011\n | title =The Art of Stand-Up\n | medium =TV\n | language =English\n | location =United Kingdom\n | time =47:23-47:48\n | publisher =BBC: One\n | quote =The classic theorist would be Freud. Tendentious jokes\u2026a difficult or edgy subject is going to create a certain tension in the audience, and having created the tension, if your punchline is funny, the laugh is bigger.\n | editor=Alan Yentob}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/24/arts/my-brief-weird-life-as-a-stand-up-comic.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=My Brief, Weird Life as a Stand-Up Comic\n |last=Strauss\n |first=Neil\n |date=24 January 1999\n |website=The New York Times\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |access-date=2 February 2019\n |quote=A good standup creates a tension in the room, which the audience wants to break with laughter. If you can do this, any punch line will work as a release valve.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Vorhaus\n |first=John\n |year=1994\n |title=The Comic Toolbox: How to Be Funny Even If You're Not\n |location=Los Angeles\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |page=53\n |isbn=1-879505-21-5\n |quote=Every time you start a joke, you create some tension...If the joke works, then all that stored is released at the punchline in the form of laughter.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.humanityinaction.org/knowledgebase/174-when-the-truth-hurts-tell-a-joke-why-america-needs-its-comedians\n |title=When the Truth Hurts, Tell a Joke: Why America Needs Its Comedians\n |last1= Cohen\n |first1=Roger\n |last2= Richards\n |first2=Ryan\n |website=Humanity in Action\n |publisher=Humanity In Action Inc.\n |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>}} This is known as a \"relief/release\" laugh.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Sarah Silverman\n | date =30 May 2017\n | title =Sarah Silverman: A Speck of Dust\n | medium =film\n | time =17:26-17:34\n | quote =I would call that a relief laugh\u2026like release laugh.}}</ref> A comedian's stand-up persona/voice consists of the type of material they perform, the format of the material, the aggregate set, the comedian's rapport with the audience, and the comedian's \"own identity.\"<ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |pages=88\u201389\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n | url=http://www.comedianscomedian.com/67-gary-delaney-live/\n | title=The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith: 67 \u2013 GARY DELANEY (LIVE)\n | website=The Comedian\u2019s Comedian\n | publisher=Stuart Goldsmith\n | host=Stuart Goldsmith\n | date=5 March 2014\n | time=5:00-5:38\n | access-date=3 February 2019\n | quote =You start off, and you want to be like your heroes\u2026you start out under the naive belief that you get to choose your style\u2026[but] your style of comedy chooses you\u2026it's a misnomer when people say you need to think about your persona\u2026its all bollocks about persona and timing. I didn\u2019t set out to be a one-liner comic, but I was shit at everything else.}}</ref>\n\n===Crowd work===\nWhen a set is consistently bombing, most comedians will perform \"crowd work\" by communicating with audience members to [[Face (sociological concept)|save face]]; much of crowd work is prewritten with added [[improvisation]].\n<ref>{{cite book \n |last=Rosenfield \n |first=Stephen \n |year=2018 \n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois \n |publisher=Chicago Review Press \n |pages=66\u201372 \n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref> Some comedians will use small talk that directs audience members to answer \"a question\" that the comedian \"[has] a topper\" for. Other comedians will become more intimate with their questions until they get multiple big laughs, before moving on.\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.comedianscomedian.com/125-dara-o-briain/\n |title=125 \u2013 DARA \u00d3 BRIAIN\n |last=Goldsmith\n |first=Stuart\n |website=The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith\n |access-date=29 January 2019\n |quote=don't stop [your crowd work with a single audience member] until you've got [approximately] 4 big laughs.}}</ref> The result of crowd work is often an [[in-joke|inside joke]].\n\n===Tight five===\nA \"tight five\" is a five-minute stand-up routine that is well-rehearsed and consists of a stand-up comedian\u2019s best material that reliably gets laughs.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/168 168]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=After deciding to become a stand-up\u2026[[Cathy Ladman]] worked to develop \u2018five decent minutes\u2019}}</ref>\nIt is often used for auditions or delivered when audience response is minimal.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.comedyofchicago.com/2013/12/a-tight-five.html\n |title=A Tight Five...\n |last=Maxwell\n |first=Dobie\n |date=December 2013\n |website=Comedy of Chicago\n |access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.goldcomedy.com/resources/put-together-five-minute-set/\n |title=How to Write a 5-Minute Comedy Set\n |last=Waithe\n |first=Elsa\n |date=2017-11-06\n |website=Gold Comedy\n |publisher=Gold Comedy\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=\u2018tight five\u2019 \u2014five minutes of solid go-to jokes that show who you are and reliably get laughs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.realfirststeps.com/599/5-minutes-standup-comedy-material/\n |title=Your First 5 Minutes Of Stand-up Comedy Material\n |last=Roye\n |first=Steve\n |date=26 February 2019\n |website=Real First Steps\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=A tight 5 minutes of stand-up comedy material generates an average 4-6+ collective audience laughs each performing minute.}}</ref> A tight five is the stepping stone to getting a paid spot.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Rosenfield\n |first=Stephen\n |year=2018\n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois\n |publisher=Chicago Review Press\n |page=195\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0\n |quote=If you have an all 'A' [material] 5-minute set, you'll get paid nothing.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/169 169]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[[Fran Capo]] [states that]\u2026an audition is usually five minutes.}}</ref>\n\n===Memory techniques===\nComics memorize their jokes through the use of on-stage practice/blocking.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.jimrichardson.com/stand-upcomedyworkshop.com/audition/memorizingJokes.html\n |title=The physical brain prefers concrete over abstract activities: How to Easily Memorize Your Jokes\n |last=Richardson\n |first=Jim\n |date=29 December 2013\n |website=Jim Richardson's Organized Comedy\n |access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref> Some comedians employ a [[mnemonic]] device called the [[method of loci]] (memory palace technique) to remember their jokes.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/nickmorgan/2015/03/05/the-public-speaking-secrets-of-comedians/\n |title=The Public Speaking Secrets Of Comedians\n |last=Morgan\n |first=Nick\n |date=5 March 2015\n |website=Forbes\n |publisher=Forbes Media LLC. \n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=To avoid going blank on stage, use the Memory Palace.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Gary Delaney\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=124\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=I'm currently using memory palaces or I think the loci method}}</ref> Some write their jokes over and over, while others have a set list in front of them; for professionals, this may be on cue cards or a stage monitor.\n<ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Hannibal Buress\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=121\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=I will put a set list on the stage monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite book \n |last=Rosenfield \n |first=Stephen \n |year=2018 \n |title=Mastering Stand-Up: The Complete Guide to Becoming a Successful Comedian\n |location=Chicago, Illinois \n |publisher=Chicago Review Press \n |pages=176\u2013178\n |isbn=978-1-61373-692-0}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\nThe term \"punching down\" is sometimes used to describe jokes that are made at the expense of disenfranchised groups or their members. It carries with it the assumption that comedy should be directed at the powerful rather than the afflicted.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.maskmagazine.com/the-joy-issue/life/stand-up-punch-down\n |url-access=subscription\n |title=a brief history of punch-down comedy\n |last=Cohen\n |first=Sascha\n |website=Mask\n |publisher=Maskmag\n |access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> Claiming one can \"smell the road\" on a comic is a [[pejorative]] phrase for a comedian who has compromised their own originality to get laughs while travelling.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Kris Tinkle, Pete Holmes, W. Kamau Bell\n | date =30 April 2014\n | title =I Am Road Comic\n | medium =Motion Picture\n | time =38:16-38:38\n | publisher =Comedy Dynamics}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Chad Daniels, Louis Lee\n | year =2017\n | title =I Need You To Kill\n | medium =Motion Picture\n | time =1:07:26-1:08:18\n | publisher =Comedy Dynamics}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/69 69]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=George Calfa, who feels that he\u2019s been forced to downplay the degree of real creativity in his act in order to pander to road crowds and bookers}}</ref> Comedian [[Seth Meyers]] coined the term \"clapter\": when an audience cheers or applauds for a joke that they agree with but that is not funny enough to get a laugh.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Sacks\n |first=Mike\n |year=2014\n |title=Poking a Dead Frog: Conversations with Today's Top Comedy Writers\n |location=NY, NY\n |publisher=Penguin Books\n |page=3\n |isbn=978-0-14-312378-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/30-Rock-Tina-Fey-Clarifies-Her-Remark-About-Daily-Show-9612.html\n |title=30 Rock's Tina Fey Clarifies Her Remark About The Daily Show\n |last=West\n |first=Kelly\n |year=2008\n |website=CINEMA BLEND\n |publisher=gateway blend: ENTERTIANMENT\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Heckler===\n{{Main|Heckler}}\n\nIn stand-up, a heckler is a person who interrupts a comedian's set. Comedians will often have a repertoire of [[insult|comebacks]] for hecklers.<ref>{{cite book \n |last1=Frances-White \n |first1=Deborah \n |last2=Shandur \n |first2=Marsha \n |year=2016 \n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy \n |others=Jim Jefferies \n |location=NY, New York \n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc \n |pages=230\u2013231 \n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0 \n |quote=I have a list of three or four [comebacks]...and the rest will be off the cuff}}</ref> Comedians will sometimes get into physical altercations with hecklers.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/theatreblog/2010/aug/24/heckling-comedy-goes-bad\n |title=When heckling goes bad\n |last=Kettle\n |first=James\n |date=24 August 2010\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |access-date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hack===\n{{Main|Hack (comedy)}}\nA hack is a pejorative term for a comedian with rushed, unoriginal, low-quality, or [[clich\u00e9]] material.{{refn|<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.nathansmart.com/akhh.pdf\n |title=The Hack's Handbook: A Starter Kit\n |last=Kindler\n |first=Andy\n |year=2007\n |orig-year=1991\n |publisher=National Lampoon\n |location=Harvard University\n |language=English\n |access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/jmv7b4/how-not-to-be-a-stand-up-comedian\n |title=How Not to Be a Stand-Up Comedian\n |last=Koester\n |first=Megan\n |date=23 April 2013\n |website=Vice\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Schwenson\n |first=Dave\n |year=2005\n |title=COMEDY FAQS AND ANSWERS: HOW THE STAND-UP BIZ REALLY WORKS\n |location=New York, NY\n |publisher=ALLWORTH PRESS\n |page=68\n |isbn=1-58115-411-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |author=Stas Bekman: stas (at) stason.org\n |url=http://stason.org/TULARC/art/hack-stand-up-comedy/\n |title=The Complete Guide To Hack Stand-Up Comedy\n |publisher=Stason.org\n |accessdate=12 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.letstalkaboutsets.com/048/\n| title=Episode 48 The Setup\n| website=Let\u2019s Talk About Sets\n| host=Jeff McBride, Harrison Tweed\n| time=8:35-8:49\n| access-date=29 August 2019\n| quote=One definition of hack is that you [the stand-up comedian] are thinking about what the audience wants instead of what you think is funny\u2026as opposed to being the artist that comes up with something new.}}</ref>}} One proposed amelioration to hackneyed material is an essay by [[George Orwell]] called \"[[Politics and the English Language#Remedy of Six Rules|Politics and the English Language: The Six Rules]]\".<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Murray\n |first=Logan\n |date=25 June 2010\n |title=Be A Great Stand-Up\n |edition=2nd\n |location=London, Great Britain\n |publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.\n |page=92\n |isbn=978-1-444-10726-5}}</ref>\n\n===Joke theft===\n{{Main|Joke theft}}\n\nWhen someone is accused of stealing a joke, the accused's defense is sometimes [[cryptomnesia]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2010/11/is-there-eve-a-justification-for-joke-stealing.html\n |title=Is There Ever a Justification for Joke Stealing?\n |last=Voss\n |first=Erik\n |date=4 November 2010\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=12 March 2019}}</ref> or [[parallel thinking]].<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Abby Stein\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/242\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/242 242]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[T]here are also cases of simple coincidence and, often in the case of observational material, parallel thinking.\n }}</ref>\n\n===Warm-up comedian===\n{{Main|Warm-up comedian}}\n\nA [[opening act|warm-up act]] (crowd warmer) performs at comedy clubs, before the filming of a television comedy in front of a studio audience, or the beginning of music concerts to prepare the crowd for the show or main act.\n\n==History of stand-up in Europe==\n\n====British Isles====\n[[File:Max Miller statue.JPG|right|thumb|160px|Bronze statue of Britain's [[Max Miller (comedian)|Max Miller]]]]\n\nEarly twentieth-century '''front-cloth comics''' started in [[Music Hall|music halls]], paving the way for stand-up comedy in Great Britain.<ref name=double>{{cite book\n |last=Double\n |first=Oliver\n |year= 2005\n |title=Getting The Joke: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ePTAwAAQBAJ&dq\n |publisher=A&C Black\n |pages=34, 37\n |isbn=9780413774767\n |quote=[C]omedians like Max Miller, [[Tommy Trinder]], [[Ted Ray (comedian)|Ted Ray]], [[Billy Russell (comedian)|Billy Russell]], [[Suzette Tarri]], [[Beryl Reid]] and [[Frankie Howerd]] performed something which was stand-up comedy in all but name. These performers were known as 'front-cloth comics.' The name derives from the staging of British variety theatre, in which acts which used the full stage\u2014such as sketch comedians who normally used the set\u2014alternated with ones which could be performed in front of the [stage] curtain\u2014the front-cloth comedians\u2026Front-cloth comedy existed at least as early as the 1920s\u2026[British] [f]ront-cloth comedians\u2026[survived] their US equivalents, the monologists, because British variety survived decades longer than American vaudeville\u2026[F]ront-cloth comics on the variety theatres had used catchphrases, costumes and comic personas, their acts fleshed out with songs and even dances}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Hunter\n |first1=I.Q.\n |last2=Porter\n |first2=Laraine\n |year=2012\n |title=British Comedy Cinema\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AIs_PX9-EkYC&dq\n |publisher=Routledge\n |page=\n |isbn= 9781136508370\n |quote=In 1929, he finally settled on [[Frank Randle]] and became a \u2018front-cloth\u2019 comic, performing his character sketch routines.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Double\n |first=Oliver\n |date=19 September 2012\n |title=Britain Had Talent: A History of Variety Theatre\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mz4HCwAAQBAJ\n |publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education\n |page=\n |isbn= 9781137265623\n |quote=The line connecting Max Miller to modern comedians such as [[Michael McIntyre]] is by no means unbroken, but the fact is that the very form of stand-up evolved from music hall song, and started life as the front cloth comedy of variety.}}</ref> Notable front-cloth comics who rose through the [[variety show|variety theatre circuit]] were [[Morecambe and Wise]], [[Arthur Askey]], [[Ken Dodd]] and [[Max Miller (comedian)|Max Miller]].<ref>{{cite news\n| author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| date         = 22 March 2018\n| title        = The last of Vaudeville: Ken Dodd died on March 11th\n| url          = https://www.economist.com/obituary/2018/03/22/ken-dodd-died-on-march-11th\n| url-access   = limited\n| work         = The Economist\n| access-date  = 17 August 2019\n| quote        =[Ken Dodd] was the last of the front-cloth comedians, meaning they dropped a cloth behind you while they cleared up the stage from the Liberty Horses and got it ready for the man who pulled doves out of his jacket, and there you were, but with an act that had been burnished until it was a jewel. And he knew he was the last, for all the greats, from Max Miller on, had crossed the boards before him.}}</ref><ref name=double/> Until 1968, the heavy censorship regime of the [[Lord Chamberlain's Office]] required all comedians to submit their acts for [[censorship]]. The act would be returned with unacceptable sections underlined in blue pencil (possibly giving rise to the term \"blue\" for a comedian whose act is considered bawdy or smutty). The comedian was then obliged not to deviate from the act in its edited form.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nThe rise of the post-war comedians coincided with the rise of television and radio, and the traditional music hall circuit suffered greatly as a result.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} By the 1970s, music hall entertainment was virtually dead. Alternative circuits had evolved, such as [[working men's club]]s.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> Some of the more successful comedians on the working men's club circuit\u2014including [[Bernard Manning]], [[Bobby Thompson (comedian)|Bobby Thompson]], [[Frank Carson]] and [[Stan Boardman]]\u2014eventually made their way to television via such shows as ''[[The Wheeltappers and Shunters Social Club]]''. The \"alternative\" comedy scene also began to evolve. Some of the earliest successes came from [[folk club]]s, where performers such as [[Billy Connolly]], [[Mike Harding]] and [[Jasper Carrott]] started as relatively straight musical acts whose between-song banter developed into complete comedy routines. The 1960s had also seen the satire boom, including the creation of the club, [[The Establishment (club)|the Establishment]], which, amongst other things, gave British audiences their first taste of extreme American stand-up comedy from [[Lenny Bruce]].<ref>\"So Farewell Then: The Untold Life of Peter Cook\" Cook, Wendy E. {{ISBN|0-00-722893-7}}, p. 139-144</ref> [[Victoria Wood]] launched her stand-up career in the early 1980s, which included observational conversation mixed with comedy songs. Wood was to become one of the country's most successful comedians, in 2001 selling out the [[Royal Albert Hall]] for 15 nights in a row.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 1979, the first American-style stand-up comedy club, the [[Comedy Store, London|Comedy Store]] was opened in London by [[Peter Rosengard]], where many alternative comedy stars of the 1980s, such as [[Dawn French]] and [[Jennifer Saunders]], [[Alexei Sayle]], [[Craig Ferguson]], [[Rik Mayall]] and [[Ade Edmondson]] began their careers.<ref>Wilmut, R and Rosengard, P ''Didn't You Kill My Mother-In-Law: The Story Of Alternative Comedy In Britain.'' {{ISBN|978-0-413-17390-4}}</ref> The stand-up comedy circuit rapidly expanded from London across the UK. The present British stand-up comedy circuit arose from the 'alternative' comedy revolution of the 1980s, with political and observational humor being the prominent styles to flourish. In 1983, young drama teacher Maria Kempinska created [[Jongleurs]] Comedy Clubs, now the largest stand-up comedy chain in Europe. Stand up comedy is believed to have been performed originally as a one-man show. Lately, this type of show started to involve a group of young comedians, especially in Europe.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}[[File:Hope WWII 44.jpg|right|thumb|160px|[[Bob Hope]], the United States of America's most famous stand-up comedian during [[World War II]]]]\n\n====Spain====\nAlthough the antecedents of this genre can be traced back to the monologues of [[Miguel Gila]] in the 1950s, [[:es:Comedia en vivo#Espa\u00f1a|the rise of live comedy in Spain]] took a long time in comparison with the American continent. The first generalized relationship with this comic genre occurred in 1999 with the creation of the [[Comedy Central Spain|Paramount Comedy]] channel, which included the ''New Comics'' program as one of its flagship programs, where monologuists such as [[\u00c1ngel Mart\u00edn]], Jos\u00e9 Juan Vaquero, [[David Broncano]], and [[Joaqu\u00edn Reyes (actor)|Joaqu\u00edn Reyes]] stood out.\nAlso, in 1999 began the journey of the program [[The club of comedy]], an open adaptation of the popular comic format. In its first stage (1999-2005), it underwent several chain changes and released comedians like [[Luis Piedrahita]], [[Alexis Valdes]] or [[:es:Goyo Jim\u00e9nez|Goyo Jim\u00e9nez]]. In its new stage, starting in 2011 in [[La Sexta]] and presented by [[Eva Hache]], it tries to start in the genre of comic monologue media characters from different artistic fields such as: [[Imanol Arias]], [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Gil]], [[Isabel Ordaz]] and [[Santiago Segura]].\nSpecial mention deserves the [[:es:Buenafuente|Buenafuente]] program, started in 2005. The presenter, [[Andreu Buenafuente]], made an initial monologue of about 9 to 11 minutes where he links current issues with everyday humorous situations. This became the most famous part of the program and made him one of the most recognized comedians in Spain, for his connection with the public and his ability to improvise.\nOn the other hand, the comedian [[Ignatius Farray]] became one of the most representative icons of this genre today.\n\n== History of stand-up in the Americas ==\n\n===United States===\n[[File:George Carlin 1969.JPG|thumb|right|160px|<center>[[George Carlin]] in 1969</center>]]\nStand-up comedy in the United States got its start from '''[[monologist]]s''' performing [[Stump speech (minstrelsy)|stump-speech monologues]] from within the [[minstrel show]]s of the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://news.psu.edu/story/141330/2008/09/12/research/probing-question-what-are-roots-stand-comedy\n |title=Probing Question: What are the roots of stand-up comedy?\n |last=Parker\n |first=Bethany\n |date=12 September 2008\n |department=Research\n |website=PennState News\n |publisher=The Pennsylvania State University \n |location=University Park, Pennsylvania\n |access-date=24 February 2019\n |quote=American stand-up comedy has its beginnings in the minstrel shows of the early 1800s}}</ref> It also has roots in various traditions of popular entertainment of the late 19th century, including [[vaudeville]], English [[music hall]], [[burlesque]] or [[Variety show|early variety shows]], [[humorist]] monologues by personalities such as [[Mark Twain]], and [[circus clown]] antics.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.britannica.com/art/stand-up-comedy\n |title=Stand-up comedy\n |last= Zoglin\n |first=Richard\n |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\n |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> With the turn of the century and spread of urban and industrial living, the structure, pacing and timing, and material of American humor began to change. Comedians of this era often depended on fast-paced joke delivery, slapstick, outrageous or lewd innuendo, and donned an ethnic persona\u2014African, Scottish, German, Jewish\u2014and built a routine based on popular stereotypes. Jokes were generally broad and material was widely shared, or in some cases, stolen. Industrialized American audiences sought entertainment as a way to escape and confront city living.\n\nThe founders of modern American stand-up comedy include [[Moms Mabley]], [[Jack Benny]], [[Bob Hope]], [[George Burns]], [[Fred Allen]], [[Milton Berle]] and [[Frank Fay (American actor)|Frank Fay]], all of whom came from vaudeville or the [[Chitlin' Circuit]].<ref>\"'Whoopi Goldberg Presents Moms Mabley'\" ZAP 2 IT: http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2013/11/whoopi-goldberg-presents-moms-mabley-eddie-murphy-bill-cosby-and-arsenio-hall-all-owe-a-debt.html</ref> They spoke directly to the audience as themselves, in front of the curtain, known as performing \"in one\". Frank Fay gained acclaim as a \"[[master of ceremonies]]\" at New York's [[Palace Theatre (Broadway)|Palace Theater]]. Vaudevillian [[Charlie Case|Charlie Case (also spelled Charley Case)]] is often credited with the first form of stand-up comedy, performing humorous monologues without props or costumes. This had not been done before during a vaudeville show.\n\nNightclubs and resorts became the new breeding ground for stand-ups. Acts such as [[Alan King (comedian)|Alan King]], [[Danny Thomas]], [[Martin and Lewis]], [[Don Rickles]], [[Joan Rivers]] and [[Jack E. Leonard]] flourished in these venues.\n\nIn the 1950s and into the 1960s, stand-ups such as [[Mort Sahl]] began developing their acts in small folk clubs like San Francisco's [[hungry i]] (owned by impresario [[Enrico Banducci]] and origin of the ubiquitous \"brick wall\" behind comedians)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/16/local/me-banducci16|title=Enrico Banducci, 85; owned hungry i nightclub|last=McLellan|first=Dennis|date=2007-10-16|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> or New York's [[The Bitter End|Bitter End]]. These comedians added an element of social satire and expanded both the language and boundaries of stand-up, venturing into politics, [[race relations]], and [[off-color humor|sexual humor]]. [[Lenny Bruce]] became known as 'the' obscene comic when he used language that usually led to his arrest.<ref>''Make Em Laugh: The Funny Business of America'' Maslon, Laurence E. {{ISBN|978-0-446-50531-4}}, p.340 \u2013 p.341</ref> After Lenny Bruce, arrests for obscene language on stage nearly disappeared until [[George Carlin]] was arrested on 21 July 1972 at [[Milwaukee]]'s [[Summerfest]] after performing the routine \"[[Seven dirty words|Seven Words You Can Never Say on Television]]\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=626471\n|title=Carlin's naughty words still ring in officer's ears\n|author=Jim Stingl\n|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]\n|date=June 30, 2007\n|accessdate=2008-03-23\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929124942/http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=626471 |archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> (the case against Carlin was eventually dismissed).\n\nOther notable comics from this era include [[Woody Allen]], [[Shelley Berman]], [[Phyllis Diller]], and [[Bob Newhart]]. Some [[African American|Black American]] comedians such as [[Redd Foxx]], [[George Kirby]], [[Bill Cosby]], and [[Dick Gregory]] began to cross over to white audiences during this time.\n\nIn the 1970s, several entertainers became major stars based on stand-up comedy performances. [[Richard Pryor]] and George Carlin followed Lenny Bruce's acerbic style to become icons. Stand-up expanded from clubs, resorts, and coffee houses into major concerts in sports arenas and amphitheaters. [[Steve Martin]] and Bill Cosby had levels of success with gentler comic routines. The older style of stand-up comedy (no social satire) was kept alive by [[Rodney Dangerfield]] and [[Buddy Hackett]], who enjoyed revived careers late in life. [[Don Rickles]], whose legendary style of relentless merciless attacks on both fellow performers and audience members alike kept him a fixture on TV and in Vegas from the 1960s all the way to the 2000s, when he appeared in the wildly popular [[Pixar]] ''[[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]]'' films as [[Mr Potato Head]], who just happened to share Don's grouchy onstage mannerisms. Television programs such as ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' and ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' helped publicize the careers of other stand-up comedians, including [[Janeane Garofalo]], [[Bill Maher]] and [[Jay Leno]].\n\nFrom the 1970s to the '90s, different styles of comedy began to emerge, from the madcap stylings of [[Robin Williams]], to the odd observations of [[Jerry Seinfeld]] and [[Ellen DeGeneres]], the ironic musings of [[Steven Wright]], to the mimicry of [[Whoopi Goldberg]], and [[Eddie Murphy]]. These comedians would serve to influence the next generation of comedians.\n\n===Mexico===\n\nIn terms of [[:es:Comedia en vivo#M\u00e9xico|live comedy in Mexico]], the predecessors of this comic style are:\n* [[:es:Los Tepichines|The Tepichines]] are a comic duo who were predecessors of a style consisting of parodies and double senses with creativity\n* [[Miguel Galv\u00e1n]] (1957-2008) Originally from Juan Aldama, Zacatecas. He dropped out of architecture at the Universidad del Valle de M\u00e9xico to take theater classes at the \"Dimitrio Sarr\u00e1s Actors Studio\" for three years.\n* Mara Escalante, is an actress, comedian and Mexican singer. She is known for the television series Mar\u00eda de Todos los \u00c1ngeles, in which she has two characters, including the protagonist. She began her career in the mid-1990s.\n* [[Polo Polo]] (1944-), whose routines are characterized by a high content of sexual references, with a touch of misogyny, relayed as a personal anecdote.\n* [[Adal Ramones]] (1961-) was one of the first to transport the genre to Mexico from his nocturnal program, using the comic monologue.\n* [[Evelio Arias Ramos|Evelio with V Chica]] (Evelio Arias Ramos, 1966-2008).\n* [[Eugenio Derbez]]\n\nThe new generation of comedians decided to use their own lives as the theme of their comedy, imitating the American style:\n\n* [[H\u00e9ctor Su\u00e1rez Gom\u00eds]], son of Mexican comedian [[H\u00e9ctor Su\u00e1rez]], is currently the host of the Latin American version of the comedy program Stand Up Comedy Central Presents, broadcast by Comedy Central from 2011 until 2014.\n* [[Adal Ramones]] since 2013 leads the program called [[:es:STANDparados|STANDparados]] broadcast by [[:es:Distrito Comedia|Comedy District]] before [[Classic TV]].\n* Kikis, (1980) comedian since late 2011, openly lesbian, has participated in [[Comedy Central Latin America]] as well as with [[Adal Ramones]] in STANDparados Comedy District.\n* Luiki Wiki (1985-) began making comedy in January 2013 in Mexico City and later moved to Monterrey NL to start the first Open Mic in Monterrey (an event in which comedians can participate to try out new material with a real audience) together with other comedians of the genre. Later they created the first collective of comedy in Monterrey called For Laughter Standup Comedy. Luiki Wiki has participated in programs such as Es de Noche and I already arrived with Ren\u00e9 Franco and as with [[Adal Ramones]] in the 3rd season of the STANDparados program aired by Comedy District.\n* [[:es:Franco Escamilla|Franco Escamilla]] (1981-) Comedian, musician, radio announcer and founder of \"La Diablo Squad\". He is mainly known for his comedy shows, has performed throughout the Mexican Republic and Latin America, even starting his own \"World Tour\", arriving to have confirmed performances in Europe and the United States, including trips to Japan and Australia. Currently known as the largest representative of Stand up Comedy in this country.\n* Hugo \"El Cojo Fel\u00edz\" (1988-), is a comedian, radio announcer, part of the devil Squad, has the radio program \"La Hora Fel\u00edz\" with the \"Uncle Rober\" and is considered the best pen in Mexico.\n* Roberto Andrade Cer\u00f3n the \"Uncle Rober\" (1979-) is a comedian, writer, radio announcer and has \"La Cojo Feliz\" the radio program \"La Hora Fel\u00edz\".\n*Daniel Sosa \n*Alex Fernandez\n\n=== Brazil ===\nThe one-man-show genre, which is similar, but allows other approaches (enacting characters, songs and scenes) was introduced in Brazil by Jos\u00e9 Vasconcellos in the 60's. Taking a step closer to the North American format, Chico Anysio and J\u00f4 Soares maintained the format - specially in their live nation-wide talks shows, and generally, in the opening monologues - bringing to Brazil a genre more similar to what we currently know as Stand-up.\n\nStand-up began to be interesting news in 2005 in ''S\u00e3o Paulo'', when the first club was created, called ''Clube de Com\u00e9dia Stand-Up:'' composed of Marcelo Mansfield, Rafinha Bastos, Oscar Filho, Marcela Leal and M\u00e1rcio Ribeiro. In S\u00e3o Paulo the comedy club would present in Beverly Hills, the traditional comedy venue in Moema. Shortly afterwards it migrated to Mr. Blues and Bleeker Street, in ''Vila Madalena''. In ''Rio de Janeiro'', ''Com\u00e9dia em P\u00e9, (''Comedy Standing Up): composed of Cl\u00e1udio Torres Gonzaga, F\u00e1bio Porch\u00e1t, Fernando Caruso and Paulo Carvalho, had its debue at the venue ''Rio Design Leblon''. These were the first stand-up performances in the country.\n\nIn 2006, the comic J\u00f4 Soares watched ''Clube de Com\u00e9dia'' in S\u00e3o Paulo and invited the comic Diogo Portugal for an interview in his talk show. That was a definitive moment to call attention towards the genre. He mentioned many different shows that he was a part of and attracted the public attention and media coverage to the bars that held these presentations. In Curitiba, with this momentum, many other stand-up nights began opening up. In S\u00e3o Paulo, Danilo Gentili, that had just become a part of ''Clube da Com\u00e9dia,'' invited M\u00e1rio Ribeiro and gathered other young comics that were frequent spectators at the club, to create ''Com\u00e9dia Ao Vivo'' (Live Comedy): composed of Dani Calabresa, Luiz Fran\u00e7a, F\u00e1bio Rabin.\n\nWith the show CQC - ''Custe o Que Custar'', on the channel Band, a nation-wide tv outlet, in 2008, the genre took gained its permanent spot on the national stage. With bug names like Danilo Gentili, Rafinha Bastos and Oscar Filho, the curiosity grew exponentially. \n\nFollowing CQC's example many channels and tv shows on Brazil's national television invested in Stand-up comedy. After this many other groups gained recognition in the clubs and live performances around the two biggest cities of Brazil.\n\n== History of stand-up in Asia ==\n===India===\n[[File:Kapil sharma.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Kapil Sharma (comedian)|Kapil Sharma]] an Indian stand up comedian, known for comedy nights with Kapil]]\nModern stand-up comedy in India is a young art form, however [[Chakyar koothu]] was prominent in [[Trivandrum]] and southern [[Kerala]] during the 16th and 17th centuries. It had all the attributes of modern stand-up comedy and is widely considered to be the oldest known staged comedy act anywhere in the world.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nEven though the history of live comedy performances in India traces its early roots back to 1980s, for a long time stand-up comedians were only given supporting/filler acts in various performances (dance or music).{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 1986, India's [[Johnny Lever]] performed in a charity show called \"Hope 86\", in front of the whole Hindi film industry as a filler and was loved by audience. His talent was recognized, and he would later be described as \"the iconic comedian of his generation\".<ref>[http://www.mid-day.com/videos/johnny-lever-on-phalke-awards/3660 Johnny Lever on Phalke Awards<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-johny-lever-the-missing-comic-in-hindi-films-1596571 Johny Lever: The missing comic in Hindi films | Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIt was not until 2005, when the TV show ''[[The Great Indian Laughter Challenge]]'' garnered huge popularity and stand-up comedy in itself started getting recognised. Thus, a lot more comedians became popular and started performing various live and TV shows. The demand for comedy content continues to increase. Some popular comedians around 2005-2008 include Raju Srivastav, Kapil Sharma, Sunil Pal etc. Most of them performed their acts in Hindi.\n\n[[File:Raju-Srivastav.jpg|right|thumb|160px|right|thumb|150px|New generation stand up comedian [[Raju Srivastav]]]]\n[[Raju Srivastav]] first appeared on the comedy talent show ''[[The Great Indian Laughter Challenge]]''. He finished as second runner-up and then took part in the spin-off, The Great Indian Laughter Challenge \u2014 Champions, in which he won the title of \"The King of Comedy\".<ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/bombay/report-raju-shrivastav-threatened-asked-not-to-joke-about-dawood-1226205 Raju Shrivastav threatened, asked not to joke about Dawood]</ref> Srivastava was a participant on season 3 of ''[[Bigg Boss (Season 3)|Bigg Boss]]''. He has participated in the comedy show ''Comedy Ka Maha Muqabla''.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/events/bangalore/Raju-Srivastav-tickles-the-funny-bone-at-Le-Meridien-Bangalore/articleshow/30159461.cms Raju Srivastav tickles the funny bone at Le Meridien, Bangalore]</ref>\n\n[[Kapil Sharma (comedian)|Kapil Sharma]] is ranked no. 3 at the most admired Indian personality list by [[The Economic Times]] in 2015.<ref name=\"The Economic Times\">{{cite news|title=Kapil Sharma ranked no.3 in Admired list|url= http://m.economictimes.com/slideshows/people/20-most-admired-people-in-india/kapil-sharma/slideshow/47260028.cms}}</ref> Currently he is hosting the most popular Indian comedy show \"[[The Kapil Sharma Show]]\" after \"[[Comedy Nights with Kapil]]\".<ref name=\"TimesofIndia\">{{cite news |title= Kapil Sharma plays the \"Traffic monitor\" at India Gate |url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tv/news-and-gossip/Kapil-Sharma-plays-the-Traffic-monitor-at-India-Gate/articleshow/22334306.cms |newspaper= The Times of India |date= 26 September 2013}}</ref> Sharma had been working in the comedy show ''Hasde Hasande Raho'' on MH One, until he got his first break in [[The Great Indian Laughter Challenge]], one of the nine reality television shows he has won. He became the winner of the show in 2007 for which he won 10 lakhs as prize money.<ref name=\"TimesofIndia\"/>\n\nSharma participated in Sony Entertainment Television\u2019s ''[[Comedy Circus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siasat.com/english/news/parvati-singhal-kapil-crown-comedy-king |title=Parvati Singhal, Kapil crown Comedy King |publisher=Siasat |date=2010-08-29 |accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref> He became the winner of all six seasons of \"[[Comedy Circus]]\" he participated in.<ref>{{cite web|title= Kapil wins another season of Comedy circus|url = http://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/Kapil-wins-yet-another-season-of-Comedy-Circus/articleshow/11131528.cms}}</ref> He has hosted dance reality show ''[[Jhalak Dikhhla Jaa (season 6)|Jhalak Dikhhla Jaa Season 6]]''<ref>[http://forbesindia.com/celebprofile/kapil-sharma/186 Kapil sharma`s profile in Forbes list] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225093429/http://forbesindia.com/celebprofile/kapil-sharma/186 |date=2014-12-25 }}</ref> and also hosted comedy show ''[[Chhote Miyan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Aparna Banerji |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2009/20090724/jplus.htm#3 |title=Lady laughter sends T-town rolling |publisher=Tribune India |date=2009-07-24 |accessdate=2014-07-21}}</ref><ref name=toi13>{{cite news| title = Daily soaps weren't creatively satisfying: Manish Paul | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-08-11/tv/41293838_1_kapil-sharma-manish-paul-humour|date=11 August 2013 | accessdate = 2013-08-16 | newspaper = [[The Times of India]] }}</ref> Sharma also participated in the show ''[[Ustaadon Ka Ustaad]]''.\n\nAround 2008-2009, two other popular comedians [[Papa CJ]] and Vir Das returned to India and started making their marks on Indian comedy scene. Both of them were exposed to UK and US comedy routines and they performed mostly in English. At the same time, a few more youngsters got inspired and started taking plunge into stand-up comedy.\n\nSince 2011, the stand-up comedy has been getting substantial appreciation.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}} The Comedy Store from London opened an outlet in Mumbai's Palladium Mall where people would regularly enjoy comedians from UK. The Comedy Story also supported local comedians and helped them grow. This outlet eventually become Canvas Laugh Club in Mumbai.\n\nAround 2011, people started organizing different comedy open mic events in Mumbai, Delhi (and Gurgaon), Bangalore. All of this happened in association with growth of a counterculture in Indian cities which catered to the appetite of younger generations for live events for comedy, poetry, storytelling, and music. Various stand up events were covered by popular news channels such NDTV / Aajtak etc. and were appreciated by millions of viewers.\n\nAs a result of these developments, plus the increasing penetration of [[YouTube]] (along with [[Internet]]/[[World Wide Web]]), Indian stand up comedy started reaching further masses. While the established comedians such as Vir Das, Papa CJ were independently growing through various corporate / international performances, other comedians such as [[Vipul Goyal]], [[Biswa Kalyan Rath]], [[Kenny Sebastian]], [[Kanan Gill]] grew popular through YouTube videos.\n\nThe industry, still in its early stages, now sees a lot more influx of aspiring comedians as it transforms the ecosystem around it.\n\n==Training and improvisation==\n\n[[Mark Twain]] and [[Jerry Seinfeld]],  both American masters of stand-up comedy, believe in practice and rehearsal. Twain prepared, rehearsed, revised and adapted his material for his popular humorous presentations.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Chasing the Last Laugh - Mark Twain's raucous and redemptive round-the-world-comedy-tour|last=Zacks|first=Richard|publisher=Doubleday|year=2016|isbn=9780385536448|location=New York, London|pages=}}</ref> Seinfeld says: \"Most contemporary comedy is profane, outraged and disposable\" but his philosophy is to give the best that he has.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/jerry-seinfeld-touring-australia-in-2017-you-will-see-the-best-that-i-have-20161027-gscpg9.html|title=Jerry Seinfeld touring Australia in 2017: 'You will see the best that I have'|last=Purcell|first=Andrew|date=3 November 2016|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=6 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106233932/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/jerry-seinfeld-touring-australia-in-2017-you-will-see-the-best-that-i-have-20161027-gscpg9.html|archive-date=2016-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nComedy schools work with new comics to workshop material, assisting comics work to overcome stage fright and better their writing skills by helping their classmates improve their sets.<ref>{{cite web|title=How to Become a Comedian|url=http://www.theartcareerproject.com/become-comedian/|website=theartcareerproject.com|publisher=The Art Career Project|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> Comedy schools offer [[improvisation]] classes for comics so that they are more comfortable straying from written material such as when dealing with [[heckler]]s. Improvisation is also necessary when working among crowd and interacting with the audience.\n\n==Festivals==\n{{Main|Comedy festival}}\n\n[[File:Janeane Garofalo Jan 15, 2008.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Janeane Garofalo]] performing at \"[[Seth Herzog|Sweet]]\" in New York City in 2008]]\n\nComedy festivals are used by industry professionals to seek out new comedians to hire.<ref>{{cite book\n |last1=Frances-White\n |first1=Deborah\n |last2=Shandur\n |first2=Marsha\n |year=2016\n |title=Off the Mic: The World's Best Stand-up Comedians Get Serious About Comedy\n |others=Jim Jefferies\n |location=NY, New York\n |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing Plc\n |page=176\n |isbn=978-1-4725-2638-0\n |quote=Go to festivals, because that's where you get noticed by the media...[and] gauge [yourself against] everybody else.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Buddy Mora\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |location=Los Angeles\n |pages=280\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I [Buddy Morra] go to the Montreal and Aspen comedy festivals, but I haven\u2019t seen much that\u2019s knocked me out.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Mendrinos\n |first=James\n |year=2004\n |title=The Idiot\u2019s Complete Guide To Comedy Writing\n |location=375 Hudson Street, New York, NY 10014\n |publisher=Alpha: A member of Penguin Group (USA) Inc.\n |page=199\n |isbn=1-59257-231-6\n |quote=Jim McCue, the founder of ''The Boston International Comedy and Movie Festival'', spoke about the role of the festival in the industry: \u2018A festival is a great way to get attention for someone who might not have the connections other people do. This festival is constantly looking for under-appreciated talent. Hopefully, we can do our part and let people see the next generation of comedy genius.\u2019}}</ref>\n\nStand-up comedy is the focus of four major international festivals: the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland; [[Just for Laughs]] in [[Montreal, Quebec]], [[Toronto, Ontario]], and Vancouver, British Columbia in Canada; HBO's [[U.S. Comedy Arts Festival]] in [[Aspen, CO]], and the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] in [[Melbourne]], Australia.\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2007/mar/16/scotland.canada.australia\n |title=Five top comedy festivals around the world\n |last=Brown\n |first=Georgia\n |date=16 March 2007\n |website=The Guardian\n |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> A number of other festivals operate around the world, including [[The Comedy Festival]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], the Vancouver Comedy Festival, the [[New York Comedy Festival]], the Boston Comedy and Film Festival, the [[New York Underground Film Festival]], the [[Sydney Comedy Festival]], and the [[Cat Laughs]] Comedy Festival in [[Kilkenny]], [[Ireland]]. Radio hosts [[Opie and Anthony]] also produce a comedy tour called [[Opie and Anthony's Traveling Virus Comedy Tour]], featuring their own co-host, [[Jim Norton (American comedian)|Jim Norton]] as well as several other stand-up comedians regularly featured on their radio show. There is also a festival in Hong Kong called the [[HK International Comedy Festival]].\n\n==Stand-up circuits==\n===Defunct American circuits===\n\n====Theatre Owners Booking Association (T.O.B.A.)====\n{{Main Article|Theatre Owners Booking Association}}\nThis was black vaudeville that predated the Chitlin' Circuit.\n\n====Chitlin' Circuit====\n{{Main article|Chitlin' Circuit}}\nThe Chitlin' Circuit was a \"collection of all-black venues, clubs, [and] theaters\".<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.thehistoryofstandup.com/episodes/s2-ep-03-the-apollo-and-the-chitlin-circuit\n| title=S2 EP. 03: THE APOLLO AND THE CHITLIN\u2019 CIRCUIT\n| website=The History of Standup\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| date=18 June 2019\n| time= 3:12-4:00\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=The Chitlin\u2019 Circuit was a collection of all-black venues, clubs, [and] theaters\u2014that was in the United States during the era of, basically racial segregation, and this is not just in the South my friend. This is in the North as well, where a lot of African-American families came north during what\u2019s called the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]] and a number of clubs opened up specifically in these neighborhoods\u2014which were [[redlining|redlined]]\u2014and subsequently launched some of the greatest music and comedy acts we\u2019ve ever known. And so the Apollo Theater was in the chitlin circuit. Not only in it, the crown jewel.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Nesteroff\n| first        = Kliph\n| date         = 22 December 2015\n| title        = Make 'Em Laugh: 'The Comedians' Tells The Story Of Stand-Up\n| url          = https://www.npr.org/2015/12/22/460613321/make-em-laugh-the-comedians-tells-the-story-of-stand-up\n| work         = NPR\n| access-date  = 20 August 2019\n| quote        = The Chitlin' Circuit was African-American comedians performing for African-American audiences because comedy was segregated back then\u2026But it was not acceptable in those days for a black comedian to address a white crowd, because as a comedian on stage, you are superior to your audience. You are giving them your point of view \u2014 and in those days it wasn't allowed, so the Chitlin' Circuit alleviated that thing.}}</ref> The [[Apollo Theater]] was the performers' most sought after venue.<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = McNary\n| first        = Dave\n| date         = 13 February 2019\n| title        = Apollo Theater Documentary Selected as Tribeca Festival Opener\n| url          = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/apollo-theater-documentary-tribeca-festival-opener-1203138125/\n| work         = Variety\n| access-date  = 20 August 2019\n| quote        = The Apollo began operating in 1934 during the [[Harlem Renaissance]] and became the most prized venue on the \u2018Chitlin\u2019 Circuit\u2019 during the time of racial segregation in the United States.}}</ref> Notable performers for this circuit include [[Richard Pryor]], [[Moms Mabley]], [[Dick Gregory]], [[Redd Foxx]], and the duo [[Tim and Tom]].<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Barnes\n| first        = Mo\n| date         = 9 January 2019\n| title        = A conversation with Luenell: When does Black comedy become hurtful?\n| url          = https://rollingout.com/2019/01/09/a-conversation-with-luenell-when-does-black-comedy-become-hurtful/\n| work         = rollingout\n| access-date  = 20 August 2019\n| quote        = Comedians such as Redd Foxx, Dick Gregory, Richard Pryor and Moms Mabley were popular first in clubs on the \u2018Chitlin\u2019 Circuit\u2019 in urban hubs.}}</ref>\n\n====Borscht Belt====\n{{Main Article|Borscht Belt}}\nAlso called the ''Jewish Alps'', they hired performers that included stand-up comedians.<ref name=hefner>{{cite news\n| author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| date         = 28 September 2017\n| title        = What Hugh Hefner did for comedy\n| url          = https://www.chortle.co.uk/features/2017/09/28/38011/what_hugh_hefner_did_for_comedy#\n| work         = Chortle\n| access-date  = 17 August 2019\n| quote        =[Hugh Hefner\u2019s] clubs providing a bridge between the old-school resorts of the Catskill mountains and the comedy club explosion of the 1980s.}}</ref> The [[Catskill Mountains]] are depicted in ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]''.<ref name=hefner/>\n\n====Playboy comedy circuit====\nBefore the advent of full-fledged American comedy clubs, [[Hugh Hefner]] created a chain of [[Playboy Club]]s and employed people like [[Dick Gregory]],<ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Parker\n| first        = Ryan\n| date         = 27 September 2017\n| title        = Hugh Hefner Gave Dick Gregory His Big Break\n| url          = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugh-hefner-gave-dick-gregory-his-big-break-1043953\n| work         = The Hollywood Reporter\n| access-date  = 17 August 2019}}</ref> [[Mort Sahl]], [[Steve Martin]], and [[Lenny Bruce]].<ref name=hefner/><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/s2-ep-02-the-playboy-circuit/id1052359696?i=1000441141679\n| title=S2 Ep. 02: The Playboy Circuit\n| website=Apple Podcasts\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| date=11 June 2019\n| time=0:00-2:07\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=Hugh Hefner...decides in 1960...to open a club in Chicago called the Playboy Club and then opens a number of these clubs all around the country, creates this circuit where comedians...this is before comedy clubs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/s2-ep-02-the-playboy-circuit/id1052359696?i=1000441141679\n| title=S2 Ep. 02: The Playboy Circuit\n| website=Apple Podcasts\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| others=[[Tom Dreesen]]\n| date=11 June 2019\n| time=23:00-23:30\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=When I started out in show business, there were no comedy clubs. Every nightclub in America had a comic...They [Playboy] had two showrooms, ''The Penthouse'' and ''The Playroom''...When they\u2019re ready to start the show...The girl singer would go on and do 3 or 4 songs and then, she would finish, and we\u2019d come on and we\u2019d be doing like 45 minutes and she would do 15 like minutes}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/s2-ep-02-the-playboy-circuit/id1052359696?i=1000441141679\n| title=S2 Ep. 02: The Playboy Circuit\n| website=Apple Podcasts\n| publisher=The Podglomerate.Learn\n| host=Wayne Federman\n| others=Dick Capri\n| date=11 June 2019\n| time=24:30-25:20\n| access-date=17 August 2019\n| quote=They [Playboy] gave you nothing\u2026they did not pay transportation and they did not pay for the hotel room; you could eat there where the employees ate\u2026and the top money at that time was a 1,000 dollars a week, and I did not get that; [[Jackie Gayle]], he was the top comedian of the playboy clubs in those days you know, and I got $500 a week.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Martin\n |first=Steve\n |year=2007\n |title=Born Standing Up: A Comic's Life\n |location=New York\n |publisher=Scribner\n |pages=156\n |isbn=978-1-4165-5364-9\n |quote=In March 1975 my agent, Mart Klein, secured a job in San Francisco, two weeks headlining the Playboy Club for fifteen hundred dollars per week\n |url=https://archive.org/details/bornstandingupco00mart\n }}</ref> Hugh Hefner ok'd [[Burns and Carlin at the Playboy Club Tonight]], which was not recorded in a Playboy club.\n\n===Contemporary circuits===\n\n====Open mic circuit (UK)====\nThe open mic scene is referred to as the open mic circuit in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qbx97b/life-as-an-amateur-comic-on-the-open-mic-circuit-246\n |title=What Life Is Like As an Amateur Comic On the Open-Mic Circuit\n |last= Larner\n |first=Sam\n |date=25 November 2015\n |website=VICE UK\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/correspondents/2012/09/06/16101/100_ways_to_save_the_open-mic_circuit\n |title=100 ways to save the open-mic circuit\n |date=6 September 2012\n |website=Chortle\n |access-date=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====College circuit====\nThere are two associations that lead the college circuit: the [[Association for the Promotion of Campus Activities]] (APCA) (which has 200 member colleges) and the [[National Association for Campus Activities]] (NACA) (which has 1,100 member colleges).<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Schwenson\n |first=Dave\n |year=2005\n |title=COMEDY FAQS AND ANSWERS: HOW THE STAND-UP BIZ REALLY WORKS\n |location=New York, NY\n |publisher=ALLWORTH PRESS\n |page=171\n |isbn=1-58115-411-9}}</ref>\n\nComedians in the USA and Canada audition for NACA to hundreds of college and university bookers,<ref name=NF>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/09/thats-not-funny/399335/\n |title=That's Not Funny! Today's college students can't seem to take a joke.\n |last=Flanagan\n |first=Caitlin\n |date=September 2015\n |website=The Atlantic\n |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> first with a 90-second video submission, and then a ten-minute, in-person audition to perform hour-long sets.<ref name=CCPC>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/08/30/despite-struggles-comics-find-lucrative-business-college-campuses\n |title=College Comedy: Provocative Yet\u2026 PC?\n |last=Bauer-Wolf\n |first=Jeremy\n |date=30 August 2018\n |website=INSIDE HIGHER ED\n |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nSets must not [[trauma trigger|trigger]] students by \"punching down,\" contain any denigrating material,<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people=Chris Fleming (comedian), Michael Moynihan (Vice News), Jason Meier (Emerson College booker), Kat Michael (Simmons College booker), Katy Hamm (Lesly University booker), Judy Gold (comedian)\n | date =24 May 2018\n | title =College Campuses Can Be Minefields For Comedians (HBO)\n | medium =Streaming\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBu3g4kiwck\n | access-date =8 February 2019\n | format =YouTube\n | time =3:32-3:39\n | location=Boston\n | publisher =VICE News Tonight: HBO\n |quote=[A comedian] can talk about [their] experience, but [they] can't make fun of someone else's identity.}}</ref> or contain dark or blue humor; it must be \"intelligent humor\"<ref name=CCPC /> and contain subjects that college-aged adults express contempt for.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.popmatters.com/havent-you-learned-how-to-take-a-joke-2531912988.html\n |title=Haven't You Learned How to Take a Joke? The Comedy-on-Campus Debates\n |last=Ellis\n |first=Iain\n |date=8 February 2018\n |website=popMATTERS: Culture\n |access-date=10 February 2019\n |quote=Thus, college comedians can mock those groups \"liberal\" students deride\u2014Evangelical Christians, Scientologists, working-class rural males\u2014yet they dare not even flirt with jokes about race, gender, and sexuality.}}</ref>\n\nHigher education, that was once seen as the bastion of free speech is now criticized by comedians for being too [[Political correctness|PC (politically correct)]].<ref name=NF/> Many famous comedians no longer desire to perform at colleges and universities.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/11/chris-rock-frank-rich-in-conversation.html\n |title=In Conversation Chris Rock: What's killing comedy. What's saving America.\n |last=Rich\n |first=Frank\n |date=1 December 2014\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=10 February 2019\n |quote=I stopped playing colleges\u2026because they\u2019re way too conservative\u2026in their social views and their willingness not to offend anybody.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/college/2015/06/08/jerry-seinfeld-says-comedians-avoid-college-gigs-students-are-so-pc/37403583/\n |title=Jerry Seinfeld says comedians avoid college gigs, students are 'so PC'\n |last=Schramm\n |first=Michael\n |date=8 June 2015\n |website=USA Today\n |publisher=Gannett Satellite Information Network, LLC.\n |access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media\n | people=Chris Fleming (comedian), Michael Moynihan (Vice News), Jason Meier (Emerson College booker), Kat Michael (Simmons College booker), Katy Hamm (Lesly University booker), Judy Gold (comedian)\n | date =24 May 2018\n | title =College Campuses Can Be Minefields For Comedians (HBO)\n | medium =Streaming\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBu3g4kiwck\n | access-date =8 February 2019\n | format =YouTube\n | time =4:15-4:26\n | location=Boston\n | publisher =VICE News Tonight: HBO\n | quote=Judy gold is one of many famous comics, including Jerry Seinfeld and Chris Rock who say they avoid playing college campuses, because they believe younger audiences can't take a joke.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.popmatters.com/havent-you-learned-how-to-take-a-joke-2531912988.html\n |title=Haven't You Learned How to Take a Joke? The Comedy-on-Campus Debates\n |last=Ellis\n |first=Iain\n |date=8 February 2018\n |website=popMATTERS: Culture\n |access-date=10 February 2019\n |quote=It is notable that the majority of the most vociferous critics of today's student audiences\u2014Seinfeld, Maher, Gottfried, Louis CK, Dennis Miller, Larry the Cable Guy\u2014are middle-aged (or older), white, presumably heterosexual males...Ricky Gervais...too}}</ref>\n\n====Cruise circuit (CLIA)====\nThe [[Cruise Lines International Association]] contains 60 cruise liners. Comedians work an average of two days per week; this circuit is said to not aid in moving up in the field.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\">{{cite web\n |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2000/jul/14/entertainers-careers-buoyed-on-the-cruise-ship-cir/\n |title=Entertainers' careers buoyed on the cruise ship circuit\n |date=14 July 2000\n |website=Las Vegas Sun\n |publisher=Las Vegas Sun\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> Cruiseliners have both clean comedy and blue comedy at different times during the day, but opinionated political material is frowned upon.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/best-of-cruising/2014/09/10/the-best-cruise-lines-for-comedy-shows/15413043/\n |title=The best cruise lines for comedy\n |last=Golden\n |first=Fran\n |date=11 September 2014\n |website=Great Falls Tribune\n |publisher=USA Today Network\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> Hecklers are tolerated more in a cruise setting.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://travel.nine.com.au/2018/05/15/15/50/era-of-the-comedy-cruise\n |title=Five reasons to set sail on a comedy cruise\n |last=Scott\n |first=Katherine\n |date=June 2018\n |website=honey: travel\n |publisher=Nine Digital Pty Ltd\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Corporate circuit====\nCorporate circuit comedy must be clean comedy that neither swears nor references sexual acts;<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.standupcomedyclinic.com/34/\n |title=Corporate Comedy\n |last=Corely\n |first=Jerry\n |website=Jerry Corley's Comedy Clinic\n |publisher=Stand Up Comedy Clinic\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> church (or \u201csqueaky clean\u201d) comedy is preferred; two celebrities that perform this type of comedy are Jim Gaffigan and Brian Regan.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Society/2016/0709/Why-clean-comedy-is-becoming-big-business\n |title=Why clean comedy is becoming big business\n |last1=Goodale\n |first1=Gloria\n |last2=Wood\n |first2=Daniel B.\n |date=9 July 2016\n |website=The Christian Science Monitor \n |publisher=The Christian Science Monitor\n |access-date=11 February 2019}}</ref> In a lecture given at the University of Oxford, Stewart Lee stated that his character is unable to do corporate gigs, because he takes on the role of being superior to his audience.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Stewart Lee\n | date =3 July 2013\n | title =On Not Writing\n | medium =YouTube\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IrXVaytvJtQ\n | access-date =13 February 2019\n | format =Lecture\n | time =46:40-47:40\n |location=St Edmund Hall\n | publisher =University of Oxford\n | quote =I can\u2019t ever do the lucrative, corporate gigs that\u2026because in that\u2026people can get paid a lot of money for doing half an hour at a bankers' convention, but you have to be the sort of person that appears to please people\u2026[and not treat them as] deficient}}</ref>\n\n====Christian comedy circuit (CCA)====\nThe [[Christian comedy|Christian Comedy]] Association started in the 90s, in an attempt to use comedy as a \"spiritual vehicle.\"<ref name=CCA>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/zng4je/gods-comics-inside-the-world-of-christian-standup-comedy-456 |title=God's Comics: Inside the World of Christian Stand-Up\n |last=Leon\n |first=Harmon\n |date=1 July 2015\n |website=VICE\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref> Comedian [[Doug Stanhope]] has criticized Christian comedy.<ref name=CCA/> Heckling is almost nonexistent in the church circuit.<ref name=CCA/> Christian comedy is clean comedy that claims to help one's soul.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.readingeagle.com/life/article/christian-ventriloquist-ryan-bomgardner-believes-god-wants-us-to-laugh\n |url-access=limited\n |title=Christian ventriloquist Ryan Bomgardner believes God wants us to laugh\n |last=Posten\n |first=Bruce\n |date=15 August 2014\n |website=Reading Eagle\n |access-date=18 February 2019\n |quote=I define Christian comedy as clean comedy that can be good for the soul. I believe God wants us to laugh}}</ref>\n\n==Salary==\nMany comedians have day jobs.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.laughspin.com/2013/06/24/12-jobs-comedians-had-before-they-were-famous-kevin-hart-jon-stewart-louis-c-k-and-more\n |title=12 jobs comedians had before they were famous: Kevin Hart, Jon Stewart, Louis C.K. and more!\n |last= Guglielmi \n |first=Jodi\n |date=24 June 2013\n |website=LaughSpin\n |publisher=LaughSpin\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906172555/http://www.laughspin.com/2013/06/24/12-jobs-comedians-had-before-they-were-famous-kevin-hart-jon-stewart-louis-c-k-and-more\n |archive-date=6 September 2013\n |access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> In a comedian's first five years, they will lose money from travelling and performing.<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url= http://www.spentpodcast.com/episodes-1/2016/4/18/episode-002\n| title=Mark Normand: Funny for Money 002\n| website=SPENT\n| publisher=\n| host=Lindsay Goldwert\n| date=18 April 2016\n| time=4:14-4:40\n| access-date=\n| quote =I didn\u2019t start getting anywhere until\u2026five years in, financially\u2026even then, it was month to month [in New York City].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Buck\n| first        = Jerry\n| date         = 9 December 1987\n| title        = Comedian has last laugh\n| others       = Yakov Smirnoff\n| url          = https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19871209&id=kXJeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yWENAAAAIBAJ&pg=3044,1787128\n| work         = Observer Reporter (AP TV Writer)\n| access-date  = 8 April 2019\n| quote\t       = It took four or five years before I [Yakov Smirnoff] could make a living as a comedian.}}</ref><ref name=Leno>{{cite book\n |last=Ajaye\n |first=Franklyn\n |others=Jay Leno\n |year=2002\n |title=Comic Insights: The Art of Stand-up Comedy\n |publisher=Silman-James Press\n |pages=124\u2013125\n |isbn=1-879505-54-1\n |quote=I've [Jay Leno] always told comedians that if you can do this for seven years, I mean physically make it to the stage for seven years, you\u2019ll always make a living...You start to get paid at the end of the fourth or fifth year\u2014I mean paid in terms of here\u2019s $500 dollars for one night, not $15 or $20 for a set.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|year=2006\n|chapter=My Ride is Here: Ant\n|editor1-last=Shydner\n|editor1-first=Ritch\n|editor2-last=Schiff\n|editor2-first=Mark\n|title=I Killed: True Stories of the Road From America\u2019s Top Comics\n|url=http://www.standupstories.com\n|url-status=dead\n|others=[[Ant (comedian)]]\n|edition=First Paperback\n|location=New York\n|publisher=Three Rivers Press\n|page=10\n|isbn=978-0-307-38229-0\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501193623/http://www.standupstories.com:80/\n|archive-date=1 May 2012\n|access-date=31 March 2020\n|quote=Early in a comic\u2019s career, you get calls from\u2026bookers\u2026I would never again take a gig where it cost me more to get there than the pay, but back then I just needed stage time.}}</ref> Comedians will sometimes be paid for their performances with alcoholic beverages.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/exmax4/how-to-be-a-touring-stand-up-comic\n |title=How to Be a Touring Stand-Up Comic\n |last= Koester\n |first=Megan\n |date=26 June 2014\n |website=VICE\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref> A stand-up's first comedy job will often be emceeing.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=12\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=The first paying position a comic can land is to emcee or host a show.}}</ref> While it can take around a decade to make a living at comedy,<ref name=Leno/> unknown comedians may achieve great financial success.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Chris Dipetta\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/67 67]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=People like [[Jay Leno|Leno]] and [[Steven Wright|Wright]] can make ten thousand dollars a show now\u2014that\u2019s not shocking. What\u2019s shocking is that I\u2019m a virtually unknown comic and I make about one hundred twenty-five thousand dollars a year.}}</ref>\n\nHosts and MCs are paid $0-$200, depending on location and the time of week (emcees average $25<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=79\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=An emcee will make usually from $10-$35 a show. It's usually $25.}}</ref>); showcase spots get $10-$75; features get approximately $300-$600; a headliner with no following gets $150-$1500, depending on many factors; headliners with a following or TV credits can make $1,500-$10,000 per show.<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Ron White\n | year =2018\n | title = Ron White: If you Quit Listening, I\u2019ll Shut Up\n | language =English\n | url =https://www.netflix.com/title/80244900\n | access-date =29 March 2020\n | format =Motion Picture\n | time =39:21-39:41\n | quote =I was the feature act at ''The Punchline Comedy Club'' in Sacramento, California. And\u2026traditionally in American comedy clubs, there\u2019s three acts: there\u2019s an opening act that makes between a hundred and two hundred [dollars] a week for nine shows, there's a feature act\u2026makes between four and five hundred bucks a week for nine shows, and a headliner, who can make absolutely anything depending on who they are.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last         = Strauss\n| first        = Duncan\n| date         = 3 November 1988\n| title        = Comedy: The Clubbing of America: The rise of comedy club chains\n| url          = https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/comedy-the-clubbing-of-america-70535/\n| work         = Rolling Stone\n| access-date  = 10 September 2019\n| quote        = At the better chains, middle acts earn a weekly salary of $600 and up; headliners, anywhere from $2000 to $10,000, plus air fare and lodging \u2013 usually at the club's 'comedy condo' in town...The chief variable is drawing power, based on accumulated TV and movie credits.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://comedyhints.com/what-to-expect-when-youre-expecting-to-be-paid-at-a-club/\n |title=What to Expect when You're Expecting...to be Paid at a Club\n |last=Hofstetter\n |first=Steve\n |date=2 July 2015\n |website=Comedy Hints: Helping Comedians Help Themselves\n |access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-34571446\n |title=No laughing matter: The secrets behind comedy success\n |last= O\u2019Brien\n |first=Jane\n |date=21 October 2015\n |website=BBC News\n |publisher=BBC\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=If it's somebody starting off in the business it could be $1,500 a show. For somebody who's had some TV credits you could go from $4,500 to $7,500.}}</ref> The headliner makes \"10 times\" more money than the feature act.<ref name=\"MSU\"/> Famous headliners get paid from \"door deals,\" or a percentage of the revenue, based on the number of seats sold; these comics rely on their notoriety to fill seats, which makes them more money than headliners with no following.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=87\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=the famous comics have what\u2019s called a \u201cdoor deal\u201d and get paid based on the amount of people in the crowd.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Rick Messina\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/68 68]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=It depends on the TV exposure of the comic, whether the comic draws and if he can command a higher ticket price.}}</ref> Comics will sell merchandise after their shows; this will make up for other expenses, like traveling.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.rd.com/culture/things-stand-up-comedian-wont-tell-you/\n |title=13 Things a Stand-Up Comedian Won't Tell You\n |last= Breidbart\n |first=Shaun Eli |date=2018-07-09\n |website=Reader\u2019s Digest\n |publisher=Trusted Media Brands, Inc.\n |access-date=22 March 2019\n |quote=Those T-shirts and CDs we sell are what we make our real money on...And when we do book a paying gig? We spend most of the money on transportation to get there.}}</ref>\n\nMark Normand states that a set on [[Conan (talk show)|Conan]] will pay \"a couple grand\" for five minutes.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://qz.com/810609/comedians-explain-the-improbable-economics-of-stand-up/\n |title=Comedians explain the improbable economics of stand-up\n |last=Goldwert\n |first=Lindsay\n |date=16 October 2016\n |website=QUARTZ\n |publisher=Quartz Media, Inc.\n |access-date=26 January 2019}}</ref> In 2012, [[Comedy Central]] routinely offered $15,000 for a half-hour special.<ref name=NYTC/> As of 2015, Comedy Central will pay comedians about $20,000 for a thirty-minute set; an hour, Comedy Central special can be up to $150,000;<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2015/09/what-comedy-pays.html\n |title=What Comedy Pays\n |last=mattoo\n |first=Priyanka\n |date=22 September 2015\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=7 February 2019}}</ref> as of 2018, [[Netflix]] will pay comedians $26,000+ for a fifteen-minute set; Netflix pays celebrity-comedians different amounts from one another.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/01/how-much-does-netflix-pay-for-15-minutes-of-stand-.html\n |title=How Much Does Netflix Pay for 15 Minutes of Stand-Up?\n |last=Simons\n |first=Seth\n |date=24 January 2018\n |website=PASTE\n |access-date=3 February 2019}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/netflix-is-driving-la-comedy-gold-rush-1119236\n |title='I Sold the Same Special Twice!' How Netflix Is Driving an L.A. Comedy Gold Rush\n |last= Abramovitch\n |first=Seth\n |date=15 June 2018\n |website=The Hollywood Reporter\n |publisher=Prometheus Global Media, LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote= Netflix is wooing superstar comics with eight-figure deals, including Dave Chappelle (a reported $60 million), Louis C.K. ($26 million), Amy Schumer ($20 million) and Jim Gaffigan ($10 million).}}</ref>\n\nThe cruise-circuit comedian can make up to $10,000 per week,<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> some $85,000 per year; and, a college-circuit comedian can make six figures per year or thousands of dollars per gig.<ref name=NYTC>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/04/arts/stand-ups-and-their-salaries.html\n |url-access=limited\n |title=Clever, How They Earn That Laugh\n |last=Zinoman\n |first=Jason\n |last2=Megan\n |first2=Angelo\n |date=2012-11-02\n |website=The New York Times\n |access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.dailyeasternnews.com/2009/03/27/quick-witted-burress-set-for-laughs/\n |title='Quick-witted' Burress set for laughs\n |last=Holm \n |first=Heather\n |date=26 March 2009\n |website=Daily Eastern News: Tell the truth and don\u2019t be afraid\n |publisher=The Daily Eastern News\n |access-date=8 February 2019\n |quote=[[Hannibal Burress]] was the most popular comedian in Caponera\u2019s (2009) price range of $2,000.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/09/thats-not-funny/399335/\n |title=That's Not Funny! Today's college students can't seem to take a joke.\n |last=Flanagan\n |first=Caitlin\n |date=September 2015\n |website=The Atlantic\n |access-date=26 January 2019\n |quote=Keith is one of the kings of the college circuit. A few years ago, he was the most-booked college comic, playing 120 campuses. He charges $2,300 for a single performance.}}</ref> Christian circuit comedy headliners make $1,500-$2,500 per show.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/zng4je/gods-comics-inside-the-world-of-christian-standup-comedy-456 |title=God's Comics: Inside the World of Christian Stand-Up\n |last=Leon\n |first=Harmon\n |date=1 July 2015\n |website=VICE\n |publisher=VICE MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=18 February 2019\n |quote=Headliners can reap $1,500 to $2,500 per church comedy show}}</ref> Although one source states that newer comics on the national (L.A.) circuit make $1,250-$2,500 per week, another source claims that this is very innacurate, and the amount of money one makes is closer to $20 for a spot.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/netflix-is-driving-la-comedy-gold-rush-1119236\n |title='I Sold the Same Special Twice!' How Netflix Is Driving an L.A. Comedy Gold Rush\n |last= Abramovitch\n |first=Seth\n |date=15 June 2018\n |website=The Hollywood Reporter\n |publisher=Prometheus Global Media, LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote=A newer comic on the national circuit can earn anywhere from $1,250 to $2,500 per week, according to one prominent touring agent; more established names can pull in anywhere from $10,000 to $100,000 in the same period.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/06/comedians-reveal-what-the-l-a-stand-up-scene-actually-pays.html\n |title=Comedians Reveal What the L.A. Stand-up Scene Actually Pays\n |last=Caffir\n |first=Justin\n |date=20 June 2018\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC.\n |access-date=25 March 2019\n |quote= it\u2019s very hard to make that amount even on the road\u2026To mislead someone with a figure that is beyond an exaggeration and just ridiculous.}}</ref>\n\nFamous comedians may pay lesser comedians thousands of dollars for jokes and hire them on as writers,<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Durham\n |first=Rob\n |year=2011\n |title=Don't Wear Shorts on Stage: the stand-up guide to comedy\n |location=Middletown, DE\n |page=36\n |isbn=9781468004847\n |quote=Bigger name comics have been known to pay thousands for jokes and hire writers...After a famous comic has an HBO Special, they almost always hire writers to help them pump out more material.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=Barry Sand\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/239\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |pages=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/239 239\u2013240]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=Comics need material badly, especially once they get to be in demand\u2014they\u2019ve got to keep coming up with the stuff...Often, once a comic becomes successful, his requirements for material begin to exceed his ability to create it\u2014particularly in the case of TV spots, which \u2018eat\u2019 it instantly.\n }}</ref> but many famous comedians do not reveal this, as it is considered a taboo to admit purchasing material for stand-up comedy sets.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/09/should-all-standup-comics-write-their-own-jokes.html\n |title=Should All Standup Comics Write Their Own Jokes?\n |last= Hesse\n |first=Josiah \n |date=25 September 2014\n |website=Vulture: Devouring Culture\n |publisher=NEW YORK MEDIA LLC\n |access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref> Comedians may knowingly sell plagiarized jokes.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Borns\n |first=Betsy\n |others=[[Rita Rudner]]\n |year=1987\n |title=Comic Lives: Inside the World of American Stand-up comedy\n |url=https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/241\n |url-access=registration\n |publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/comiclivesinside00born/page/241 241]\n |isbn=0-671-62620-5\n |quote=[T]hat\u2019s another thing people do\u2014write down jokes they see on TV, then sell them to other comics who don\u2019t realize what they\u2019re doing.\n }}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nMany of the earliest vaudeville-era stand-ups gained their greater recognition on radio. They often opened their programs with topical monologues, characterized by [[ad-lib]]s and discussions about anything from the latest films to a missed birthday. Each program tended to be divided into the opening monologue, musical number, followed by a [[sketch comedy|skit]] or story routine. A \"feud\" between [[Fred Allen]] and [[Jack Benny]] was used as comic material for nearly a decade.\n\n[[Home Box Office|HBO]] presented comedians uncensored for the first time, beginning with [[Robert Klein]] in 1975, and was instrumental in reaching larger audiences. George Carlin was a perennial favorite, who appeared in 14 HBO comedy specials.\n\nContinuing that tradition, most modern stand-up comedians use television or motion pictures to reach a level of success and recognition unattainable in the comedy-club circuit alone.\n\nLate-night talk shows and award show ceremonies are commonly hosted by comedians, delivering monologues similar to stand-up.\n\nSince the mid-2000s, online video-sharing sites such as [[YouTube]] have also provided a venue for stand-up comedians, and many comedians' performances can be viewed online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailybits.com/watch-stand-up-comedians-on-youtube/|title=Watch Stand Up Comedians on YouTube|accessdate=2008-09-27 |work= Daniel Scocco |publisher=Dailybits.com |date=2008-09-23}}</ref>\n\nAn Amazon TV show, ''[[The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel]]'', depicts the fictional life of a woman comedian, set in the late 1950s. She often interacts with [[Lenny Bruce]].\n\n== List of comedians ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[List of comedians]]\n* [[List of humorists]]\n* [[List of stand-up comedians]]\n* [[List of musical comedians]]\n* [[List of Australian comedians]]\n* [[List of British comedians]]\n* [[List of Canadian comedians]]\n* [[List of Finnish comedians]]\n* [[List of German language comedians]]\n* [[List of Indian comedians]]\n* [[List of Italian comedians]]\n* [[List of Mexican comedians]]\n* [[List of Puerto Rican comedians]]\n* [[List of Filipino Comedian]]\n}}\n\n== Other types of stand-up ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Macchietta]] \u2014 Italian 19th century comedy act\n* [[Manzai]] \u2014 style of [[Double act]] comedy in Japan\n* [[Mandan (comedy)|Mandan]] \u2014 style of stand-up comedy in Japan\n* [[Rakugo]] \u2014 Japanese verbal solo entertainment similar to stand-up comedy, but kneeling instead of standing.<ref>{{cite book\n |last=Barry\n |first=Dave\n |author-link=Dave Barry\n |year=1992\n |title=Dave Barry Does Japan\n |publisher=Ballantine Books\n |location=New York\n |page=[https://archive.org/details/davebarrydoesjap00dave/page/129 129]\n |isbn=0-449-90810-0\n |url=https://archive.org/details/davebarrydoesjap00dave/page/129\n }}</ref>\n* [[Xiangsheng]] \u2014 Chinese traditional stand-up comedy \n}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* {{Portal-inline|Comedy |size=tiny}}\n* [[2019 in stand-up comedy]]\n* [[Aesthetic distance]]\n* [[Comedy troupe]]\n* [[Improvisational theatre]]\n* [[List of humor research publications]]\n* [[Non sequitur (literary device)|Non-sequitur]]\n* [[Radio comedy]]\n* [[Roast (comedy)|Roast]]\n* [[Situation comedy]]\n* [[Stage name]]\n* ''[[The Comedian's Comedian 