{"title_page": "Massachusetts Route 88", "text_new": "{{short description|American road}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=MA\n|route=88\n|alternate_name=\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 88}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 88 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=11.30\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">[[Massachusetts Department of Transportation|Executive Office of Transportation]], [http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/plan02&sid=about Office of Transportation Planning - 2005 Road Inventory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927193052/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Fplan02&sid=about |date=2006-09-27 }}</ref>\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a=John Reed Road in [[Westport, Massachusetts|Westport]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|177}} in Westport\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|6}} in Westport\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|I|195}} in Westport\n|established=\n|counties=[[Bristol County, Massachusetts|Bristol]]\n|previous_type=MA\n|previous_route=86\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=90\n}}\n'''Route 88''' is a {{convert|11.30|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} north&ndash;south [[state highway]] in the town of [[Westport, Massachusetts|Westport]] in southeastern [[Massachusetts]].  At just over 11 miles, it is the longest Massachusetts state route to be situated in only one town.\n\n==Route description==\n[[Image:MA Route 88 bridge over the Westport River, Westport Point MA.jpg|thumb|left|The Fontaine Bridge from Westport Point.]]\n[[Image:MA Route 88 At MM2.jpg|thumb|left|Near Mile Marker 2 looking northbound.]]\n[[Image:Southern End of Route 88.jpg|thumb|right|The southern terminus of Route 88.]]\n[[Image:Normand Edward Fontaine Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|The Fontaine Bridge from Horseneck Beach State Reservation.]]\nRoute 88 begins at the northern end of the [[Horseneck Beach State Reservation]] lands, on a peninsula dividing the East Branch of the [[Westport River]] from [[Buzzards Bay]].  After just {{convert|0.3|mi|km}}, it crosses the [[Normand Edward Fontaine Bridge]] over that river into the [[Westport Point Historic District|Westport Point]] section of town. The road has five [[at-grade intersection]]s with [[Traffic light|stoplights]] and two ramped overpass intersections.\n\nRoute 88 ends just north of Route 6 and the abandoned Old Colony Rail line at an interchange with [[Interstate 195 (Rhode Island-Massachusetts)|I-195]], where westbound entrance and exit fly on separate overpasses over the interstate, and eastbound entrance and exit are direct ramps with no flyovers.\n\nRoute 88 is a [[two-lane expressway]] or \"Super-2.\"  Route 88 (like other such roads) is peculiar in its design in that, while it has at-grade intersections with town roads and is not divided by barriers or grass median between the Fontaine Bridge and Old County Road (except at intersections), there is no development of any kind that abuts the route directly; the only property that comes close is an ice cream stand on the southeast corner of Route 88 and Hixbridge Road, but even this only has a driveway from Hixbridge Road.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=MA|county=Bristol|location=Westport|length_ref=}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=0.0\n|road=John Reed Road\n|notes=Southern terminus; to [[Horseneck Beach State Reservation]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|bridge=[[Normand Edward Fontaine Bridge]] over the [[Westport River]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=1.2\n|road=Drift Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=4.2\n|road=Hixbridge Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=6.3\n|road=Charlotte White Road Extension\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=7.8\n|road=Old County Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=8.6\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|177|location1=[[Tiverton, Rhode Island|Tiverton, RI]]|city2=New Bedford}}\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=10.3\n|road=Briggs Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|6|city1=North Westport|city2=Dartmouth}}\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.3\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|195|location1=[[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence, RI]]|city2=Cape Cod}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; exit 10 on I-195\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 88}}\n* [http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/MA-88/ Steve Anderson's BostonRoads.com: Horseneck Beach Connector (MA 88)]\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|088]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Bristol County, Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American road}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=MA\n|route=88\n|alternate_name=\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 88}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 88 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=11.30\n|length_round=2\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">[[Massachusetts Department of Transportation|Executive Office of Transportation]], [http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/plan02&sid=about Office of Transportation Planning - 2005 Road Inventory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927193052/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Fplan02&sid=about |date=2006-09-27 }}</ref>\n|direction_a=South\n|terminus_a=John Reed Road in [[Westport, Massachusetts|Westport]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=MA|MA|177}} in Westport\n*{{jct|state=MA|US|6}} in Westport\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=MA|I|195}} in Westport\n|established=\n|counties=[[Bristol County, Massachusetts|Bristol]]\n|previous_type=MA\n|previous_route=86\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=90\n}}\n'''Route 88''' is a {{convert|11.30|mi|km|-long|adj=mid}} north&ndash;south [[state highway]] in the town of [[Westport, Massachusetts|Westport]] in southeastern [[Massachusetts]].  At just over 11 miles, it is the longest Massachusetts state route to be situated in only one town.\n\n==Route description==\n[[Image:MA Route 88 bridge over the Westport River, Westport Point MA.jpg|thumb|left|The Fontaine Bridge from Westport Point.]]\n[[Image:MA Route 88 At MM2.jpg|thumb|left|Near Mile Marker 2 looking northbound.]]\n[[Image:Southern End of Route 88.jpg|thumb|right|The southern terminus of Route 88.]]\n[[Image:Normand Edward Fontaine Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|The Fontaine Bridge from Horseneck Beach State Reservation.]]\nRoute 88 begins at the northern end of the [[Horseneck Beach State Reservation]] lands, on a peninsula dividing the East Branch of the [[Westport River]] from [[Buzzards Bay]].  After just {{convert|0.3|mi|km}}, it crosses the [[Normand Edward Fontaine Bridge]] over that river into the [[Westport Point Historic District|Westport Point]] section of town. The road has five [[at-grade intersection]]s with [[Traffic light|stoplights]] and two ramped overpass intersections.\n\nRoute 88 ends just north of Route 6 and the abandoned Old Colony Rail line at an interchange with [[Interstate 195 (Rhode Island-Massachusetts)|I-195]], where westbound entrance and exit fly on separate overpasses over the interstate, and eastbound entrance and exit are direct ramps with no flyovers.\n\nRoute 88 is a [[two-lane expressway]] or \"Super-2.\"  Route 88 (like other such roads) is peculiar in its design in that, while it has at-grade intersections with town roads and is not divided by barriers or grass median between the Fontaine Bridge and Old County Road (except at intersections), there is no development of any kind that abuts the route directly; the only property that comes close is an ice cream stand on the southeast corner of Route 88 and Hixbridge Road, but even this only has a driveway from Hixbridge Road.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{jcttop|state=MA|county=Bristol|location=Westport|length_ref=}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=0.0\n|road=John Reed Road\n|notes=Southern terminus; to [[Horseneck Beach State Reservation]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|bridge=[[Normand Edward Fontaine Bridge]] over the [[Westport River]]\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=1.2\n|road=Drift Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=4.2\n|road=Hixbridge Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=6.3\n|road=Charlotte White Road Extension\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=7.8\n|road=Old County Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=8.6\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|177|location1=[[Newport, RI]]|city2=New Bedford}}\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=10.3\n|road=Briggs Road\n|notes=At-grade intersection\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.0\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|6|city1=North Westport|city2=Dartmouth}}\n|notes=Interchange\n}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.3\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|195|location1=[[Providence, RI]]|city2=New Bedford}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; exit 10 on I-195\n}}\n{{jctbtm}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 88}}\n* [http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/MA-88/ Steve Anderson's BostonRoads.com: Horseneck Beach Connector (MA 88)]\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|088]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Bristol County, Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Oliver Wendell 2009", "label": "safe", "comment": "Like I said earlier, Route 177's western end is in the Tiverton-Little Compton area not Newport. For Route 177 to reach Newport, it must cross the Sakonnet River Bridge and jump onto either Route 114 south or 138 west/south to do so.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Route_88"}
{"title_page": "Tadeusz Szeligowski", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name = Tadeusz Szeligowski\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image = Tadeusz Szeligowski.jpg\n| caption = Szeligowski, circa 1953\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1896|09|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lemberg]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1963|01|10|1896|09|13|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Pozna\u0144]], [[Poland]]\n| death_cause =\n| resting_place = Pozna\u0144 Skalka crypt of Merit\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments =\n| residence =\n| nationality = Polish\n| other_names =\n| education =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = Composer, music professor, pianist and music writer\n| years_active =\n| employer = {{Lang|pl|Pa\u0144stwowa Wyzsza Szko\u0142a Muzyczna}}\n| organization =\n| agent =\n| known_for =\n| notable_works = {{Unbulleted list| The peacock and the girl | Sonata for flute and piano }}\n| style =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| home_town =\n| television =\n| religion =\n| spouse =\n| partner =\n| children =\n| parents =\n| relatives =\n| awards =\n| website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Tadeusz Szeligowski''' (13 September 1896 - 10 January 1963) was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[composer]], [[educator]], [[lawyer]] and music organizer. His works include the operas ''The Rise of the Scholars'', ''Krakatuk'' and ''Theodor Gentlemen'', the ballets ''The Peacock and the Girl'' and ''Mazepa ballets'', two violin concertos, [[Chamber music|chamber]] and [[choral]] works.<ref name=Sokol>{{cite book|last=Sokol|first=Stanley S.|title=The Polish Biographical Dictionary|year=1992|publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci Publishers|isbn=0-86516-245-X|pages=[https://archive.org/details/polishbiographic00soko/page/397 397]|url=https://archive.org/details/polishbiographic00soko|url-access=registration|quote=Tadeusz Szeligowski.}}</ref>\n\nAs a music teacher, Szeligowski was very well established in [[Vilnius]], [[Lublin]], [[Pozna\u0144]] and [[Warsaw]]. He was also a respected [[music critic|music writer]] who frequently wrote for journals and magazines specialized in music such as the ''[[Kurier Wile\u0144ski]]'', ''[[Tygodnik Wile\u0144ski]]'', ''[[Muzyka]]'' and the ''[[Kurier Pozna\u0144ski]]''. His achievements include the creation of the [[Pozna\u0144 Philharmonic|Poznan\u00b4 Philharmonic]], where he served as its first director between the years 1947-1949, and the founding of the Pozna\u0144 Musical Spring, one of the most important festivals of contemporary music at the time.\n\n==Life and work==\n\n===Musical education===\nTadeusz Szeligowski was born on 13 September 1896 in [[Lemberg]], then in [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]] [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]] and now in western [[Ukraine]]. Szeligowski\u2019s first music and piano teacher was his mother. Later he began studying music at the Conservatory of Music of the Polish Society in L'vov in the years 1910-1914, where he studied piano under the direction of [[Vilem Kurz]],<ref name=Naxos>{{cite web|last=Naxos|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski (1896-1963)|url=http://www.naxos.com/person/Tadeusz_Szeligowski/49322.htm|publisher=Naxos.com|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> and then from 1918-1923 in [[Krak\u00f3w]], where he studied piano with H. Peters, and composition with [[Boles\u0142aw Wallek-Walewski]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Szeligowski Tadeusz|last=''Encyklopedia Muzyczna PWN|url=https://pl.wikisource.org/wiki/Encyklopedia_Muzyczna_PWM/Szeligowski_Tadeusz|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> Szeligowski's further education included [[musicology]] with [[Zdzis\u0142aw Jachimecki]] and law at the [[Jagiellonian University]] in Krak\u00f3w, where he received his [[doctorate]] in 1922. There he found work as [[repetiteur]] at the Krak\u00f3w Opera House, allowing him to become well acquainted with the opera repertoire.<ref name=Naxos/>\n\nHe complemented his studies in music in the years 1929-1931 in [[Paris]], where he met many composers of his time such as [[Sergei Prokofiev]], [[George Enesco]] and [[Arthur Honegger]]. There he studied composition with [[Nadia Boulanger]] and orchestration with [[Paul Dukas]].<ref name=\"Le Nart\">{{cite web|last=Le Nart|first=Agnieszka|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski|url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-music-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/tadeusz-szeligowski|publisher=Adam Mickiewicz Institute (AMI)|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> There he attended many concerts and intensely experienced the latest compositions by [[Darius Milhaud]], [[Francis Poulenc]], [[ballet]] productions of many famous companies, as well as highly acclaimed performances by [[Jascha Heifetz]], [[Vladimir Horowitz]], [[Arthur Rubinstein]] and [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]].<ref name=Naxos/>\n\n===Musical career===\nIn 1923 Szeligowski worked in Vilnius, [[Lithuania]] (then part of the [[Second Polish Republic]]), as lawyer and [[lecturer]] at the Conservatory of Music. There he met [[Karol Szymanowski]] and became a great admirer of his music. He also worked with a dramatic theatre called Reduta, composing music for many of its productions.<ref name=Naxos/> Shortly after his return to Poland in 1931,<ref name=Naxos/><ref>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Adrian|title=Polish music since Szymanowski|year=2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-58284-9|pages=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XT-ReqNMSx0C&pg=PA10&dq=Tadeusz+Szeligowski&hl=en&ei=MGpJTsP7FIe18QPzsez8Ag&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-preview-link&resnum=3&ved=0CDcQuwUwAjgK#v=onepage&q=Tadeusz%20Szeligowski&f=false}}</ref> he began teaching music in Pozna\u0144 until 1939, and then moved to Lublin for a little while after the [[World War II]].<ref name=Naxos/> From 1947-1962 he worked for The State Higher School Of Music ({{Lang|pl|Pa\u0144stwowa Wyzsza Szko\u0142a Muzyczna}}) in Pozna\u0144,<ref name=Sokol/> and from 1947-1950 he became director of the National Opera Academy, when on his own initiative the Pozna\u0144 [[Philharmonic]] was created.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rubin & Partners|title=Poznan Philharmonic Orchestra|url=http://www.pricerubin.com/classical/detail.php?SummaryNumber=6&detail=1|publisher=Price Rubin & Partners|accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref> In addition, he was the initiator of the festival of contemporary music, the \"Pozna\u0144 Musical Spring\", where modern music was then presented in all its glory,<ref name=\"Le Nart\"/> and one of the organizers of the H. Wieniawski International Violin Competition.<ref name=Naxos/> From 1951-1962 Szeligowski worked in [[Warsaw]], first for the faculty of the [[Fryderyk Chopin University of Music in Warsaw|Fryderyk Chopin University of Music]] in Warsaw, and later as director of the Polish Society of Composers.<ref name=Naxos/>\n[[File:Poznan 10-2013 img07 Philharmony.jpg|thumb|[[Pozna\u0144 Philharmonic]]]]\nA large group of his graduates on composition include: [[Zbigniew Bargielski]], [[Augustyn Bloch]], [[Joanna Bruzdowicz]], [[Wojciech Lukaszewski]], [[Tadeusz Wojciech Maklakiewicz]], [[Boleslaw Ocias]], [[Witold Rudzinski]], [[Marek Sart]], [[Aleksander Szeligowski]] and [[Antoni Szuniewicz]]. {{See LMST|Tadeusz|Szeligowski}}\n\n===As a music writer===\nLvov\u2019s musical scene at that time included a city opera, a symphonic orchestra, a music society and also a conservatory of music, and there Szeligowski was very active as a social organizer. Musicians such as [[Felix Weingartner]] and [[Oscar Nedbal]] usually visited the city and frequently performed works by [[Giuseppe Verdi]] and [[Richard Wagner]]. From 1951-1954 he served as chairman of the Polish Composers Union, and from 1953 he worked for the Board of Polish Music Publishers and the Central Pedagogical Office for Arts Education (COPSA).<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\">{{cite web|last=Mrygo\u0144|first=Adam|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski (1896-1963)|url=http://www.pwm.com.pl/szczegoly.php?&Szeligowski_Tadeusz&aukcja=0&grupa_p=6&grp=&pwd%5B6%5D=224404&sortuj=sattr_83&grupuj=&przedm=283381&strona=2&change_lang=1&change_skin=103374|work=Encyklopedia Muzyczna PWM, vol. 10|publisher=Polish Widawnictwo Muzycne SA|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> Tadeusz Szeligowski died in Pozna\u0144 on 10 January 1963 and since 1965 he has been buried in the Pozna\u0144 Skalka crypt of Merit.<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\"/>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Szeligowski.JPG|thumb|right|160px|J\u00f3zef Kopczy\u0144ski's 1966 commemorative plaque for Polish composer Tadeusz Szeligowski.]]\nSzeligowski received numerous awards, among them:\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1949}}|event= Third prize at the Second [[Chopin]] Composition Competition for his Piano Sonata in D minor<ref name=\"Polish Culture\">{{cite web|last=Polish Culture|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski|url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-music-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/tadeusz-szeligowski|publisher=Culture.pl|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1949}}|event= Second prize at the [[Polskie Radio|Polish Radio]] Competition for the song ''The Prince and the girl''<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1950}}|event= State prize of the second degree for ''The peacock and the girl'', ''Arion'', and the ''Lublin Wedding''<ref name=\"Le Nart\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1951}}|event= State prize of the first degree for the opera stage ''Rise of the scholars''<ref name=\"Le Nart\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1963}}|event= Prize Prime Minister of Poland for his music for children and youth<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1963}}|event= Music Award of the PCU, awarded every 17 January by the Polish Composers Union (ZKP \u2014 ''Zwiazek Kompozytorow Polskich'') for lifetime achievement (posthumous)<ref name=\"Mrygo\u01442\">{{cite web|last=ZKP|title=PCU Award|url=http://www.zkp.org.pl/nagroda.php?lang=en|work=Laureaci Nagrody ZKP|publisher=Polish Composers\u2019 Union|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> }}\n\nAlso, he received numerous prizes and awards, including:\n* The City of [[Pozna\u0144]] Music Prize{{when|date=October 2011}}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1952}}|event= Gold [[Cross of Merit (Poland)|Cross of Merit]] (''Z\u0141OTYM KRZYZEM ZAS\u0141UGI'')<ref>{{cite web|last=Monitor Polski|title=Order of the Prezident of the Republic - 1078|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:hVXWgzTheK0J:monitorpolski.gov.pl/M1952070107801.pdf+monitorpolski.gov.pl/M1952070107801.pdf&hl=cs&gl=cz&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESih0ko2ugXfFIv2aDLCQZNMiTFnUx59ScIbWw08-c9c1cajINyJ77TVbBlhgHlsBmGhKWkMrICygOvs4sgIe8GF3Ook7VdTBDCDQqBTx9muunKczW25E0awP5CMRgrWZ6O0KY2Z&sig=AHIEtbQGPhF-h-_b8MCqBLLtag__LHtw3Q|work=Granting State Awards on 22 July 1952|publisher=Monitor Polski.gov.pl|accessdate=18 August 2011|language=pl}}</ref> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1952}}|event= Medal [[Order of Polonia Restituta]]<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1966}}|event= A commemorative plaque designed by J\u00f3zef Kopczy\u0144ski and placed at House 22, Che\u0142mo\u0144ski street, in Pozna\u0144, where he lived from 1947.}}\n\n==Compositions==\n\n{{Cleanup lang|date=October 2011}}\n\n===Instrumental===\n\n====Orchestral works====\n*''The Peasant King'' - [[Overture]] to the comedy of [[Piotr Baryka]] for orchestra (1926)\n*''Kaziuki - St. Casimir's Day,'' [[suite (music)|suite]] for orchestra (1928\u201329)\n*''Concerto'' for Orchestra (1930)\n*''Archaic Suite'' for orchestra (1930)\n*''Little Suite'' for orchestra (1931)\n*''Clarinet Concerto'' (1933)\n*''Andante'' for clarinet and orchestra (1933)\n*''Blue Bird'' - suite for orchestra (1936)\n*''[[Epitaph]] on the death of [[Karol Szymanowski]]'' for string orchestra (1937)\n*''Carol Suite'' for string orchestra (1939)\n*''Piano Concerto'' (1941)\n*''Suite'' for small orchestra of Lublin (1945)\n*''Kupa\u0142owa night'' - suite for orchestra (1945)\n*''Nocturno'' for orchestra (1947)\n*''Comedy Overture'' for small symphony orchestra (1952)\n*''The peacock and girl'' ballet suite for orchestra (1953)\n*''Four Polish Dances'' for symphony orchestra (1954)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====Chamber music====\n[[File:Sonata Tadeusz Szeligowski.jpg|thumb|right|220px|A musical score of Tadeusz Szeligowski's ''Sonata for flute and piano''.]]\n*''Lithuanian Song'' for violin and piano (1928)\n*''String Quartet'' No. 1 (1928\u201329)\n*''[[Ricercar]]'' for 4 voices, instrumental or vocal (1931)\n*''String Quartet'' No. 2 (1934-1935)\n*''Trio'' for oboe, viola and cello (1935)\n*''Fish ball'', song for children's team (1937)\n*''Air grave et gai air'' for English horn and piano (1940)\n*''Nocturno'' for cello and piano (1943)\n*''Dance'' for cello and piano (1943\u201345)\n*''Poem'' for cello and piano (1943\u201345)\n*''Pastorale'' for cello and organ (1943\u201345)\n*''[[Sarabande]]'' for cello and organ (1943\u201345)\n*''Orientale'' for Cello and Piano (1945)\n*''Quintet'' for wind instruments (1953)\n*''Sonata'' for flute and piano (1953)\n*''On the meadow'', suite for 2 pianos (1955)\n*''Trio'' for violin, cello and piano (1955-1956)\n*''Polish love songs'' for recorders (1959)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====Solos (Pianoforte)====\n*''Variations on a folk song'' for piano (1927)\n*''Guitars of Zalamea'', for piano (1938\u201339)\n*''Sonatina'' for piano (1940\u201341)\n*''Russian Dance'', for piano (1942)\n*''Sonata'' in d minor for piano (1949)\n*''Two etudes on double sounds'' for piano (1952)\n*''Small pieces'' for piano (1952)\n*''Odds and ends for four hands'', for piano (1952)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n===Vocal Score===\n\n====For solo voices====\n*''Nos qui sumus'' - ''motet'' for two male voices (1929)\n*''O vos omnes'' - motet for three female voices (1929)\n*''Timor et tremor'' - motet for [[contralto]] and [[tenor]] (1929)\n*''Missa de Angelis'' for 3 female voices (1942)\n*''[[Ave Maria]]'' for three female voices (1943 )\n*''[[Regina Coeli|Regina Coeli Laetare]]'' for 3 female voices (1943)\n*''Populations meus'' for 3 female voices (1943)\n*''Veni Creator'' for 3 female voices (1943)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====For choir a cappella====\n*''Two [[Belarus]]ian songs'' for mixed choir (1930)\n*''Under the canopy of snow'' - Christmas carol for mixed choir (1933\u201334)\n*''Angela sang sweetly'' - motet for mixed choir (1934)\n*''Quail'' - Belarusian folk song for male choir (1934)\n*''Regina Coeli Laetare'' for mixed choir (1934)\n*''Already we have time'' for male choir (1935)\n*''Song of the sailors'', for mixed choir (1938)\n*''[[Psalm]] Joyful in memoriam of [[Guillaume Dufay]]'' for mixed choir (1938)\n*''[[Mass (music)|Mass]]'' for choir (1942)\n*''[[Stabat Mater]]'' for mixed choir (1943)\n*''[[Pange Lingua Gloriosi Corporis Mysterium|Pange lingua]]'' in mixed choir (1943)\n*''Five folk songs from Lublin region'' for choir female or child (1945)\n*''Five folk songs from the Lublin region'' for 3 mixed choir (1945)\n*''Four wedding songs from the Lublin region'' for mixed choir (1945)\n*''Koszalka - Opa\u0142ka'', [[scherzo]] for male choir (1946)\n*''A wyjrzyjcie\u017c'', youths, song for mixed choir (1948)\n*''Song of the 10th anniversary'' [version II] for mixed choir a cappella (1955)\n*''Psalm CXVI \"Laudate Dominum\"'' for mixed choir and boys' (1960)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n===Vocal and instrumental===\n\n====For voice and piano====\n*''Wanda'', song for voice and piano (1927)\n*''Lithuanian folk songs'' for voice and piano (1927)\n*''Song of the green'' for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Lilies'' - [[ballad]] for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Oaks'' - [[elegy]] for voice and piano (1929)\n*''In alder'' - [[idyll]] for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Hops'' - wedding song for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Floral allegories'' for voice and piano (1934)\n*''Songs to the words of [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]]'' for voice and piano (1945)\n*''Green brz\u00f3zko'', song for voice and piano (1947)\n*''My Girl'', song for voice and piano (1947)\n*''The Rose Highway'', song for voice and piano (1947)\n*''[[Arion]]'' for tenor and piano (1949)\n*''[[Demon]]'' for tenor and piano (1949)\n*''[[Doves]]'' for soprano and piano (1949)\n*''The Ballad of [[Aleksander Kostka Napierski|Kostka Napierski]]'' for voice and piano (1951)\n*''With three Mauretankach'', [[song]] for voice and piano (1953)\n*''Soledad'' for voice and piano (1960)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====For various vocal and instrumental ensembles====\n*''Psalm XVI'' - [[oratorio]] (1931)\n*''Latin Mass'' for mixed choir and [[organ (music)|organ]] (1932)\n*''Cherry Blues'' for [[voice]], [[cello]] and piano (1934)\n*''Ave Maria'' for [[soprano]], female choir and organ (1943)\n*''[[Aria]]'' for soprano and organ (1943)\n*''Sit down everybody around us'', suite 12 popular songs from the years 1810 to 1875 for mixed choir (or soprano and alto) and piano (1945)\n*''[[Triptych]]'' for soprano and orchestra (1946)\n*''[[Cantata]] for sport \"100 m\"'' for solo voice, choir and orchestra (1948)\n*''Wedding [[Suite (music)|Suite]]'' for [[soprano]], [[tenor]], female chorus, mixed chorus and piano (1948)\n*''Wedding in Lublin'' for soprano, mixed choir and small orchestra (1948)\n*''The young master and a girl'', musical dialogue for soprano, [[baritone]], mixed choir and orchestra or piano (1948-1949)\n*''[[Rhapsody (music)|Rhapsody]]'' for soprano and orchestra (1949)\n*''Of hearts card'', cantata for soprano, mixed choir and symphony orchestra (1952)\n*''Sophie'', suite for choir and orchestra (1952)\n*''Renegade'', ballad for bass and orchestra or piano (1953)\n*''Song of the 10th anniversary'' [version] for choir<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n===Stage works===\n*''The peacock and the girl'', [[ballet]] in 3 acts (1948)\n*''Bunt \u017cak\u00f3w'' (Student Rebellion), [[opera]] in 4 acts (1951)\n*''Krakatuk'', opera in 3 acts with a prologue (1954)\n*''[[Ivan Mazepa|Mazepa]]'', ballet in 3 acts (1958)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Magocsi|first=Paul Robert|title=A history of Ukraine|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=0-8020-7820-6|pages=240|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t124cP06gg0C&pg=PA240&dq=Tadeusz+Szeligowski&hl=en&ei=Y3ZJTpyxDMip8APN-dSZBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-preview-link&resnum=5&ved=0CDsQuwUwBDge#v=onepage&q=Tadeusz%20Szeligowski&f=false}}</ref>\n*''Theodore Gentleman'', opera in 2 acts ( 1960)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Classical music]]\n*[[Contemporary classical music|Modern music]]\n*[[Romantic composers]]\n*[[Neoclassicism#In music|Neoclassicism]]\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n#Zofia, Lissa; ''Rise of scholars'', Tadeusz Szeligowski, PWM, Krak\u00f3w 1957\n#Rozmowy ''\"Movement Music\". Says Tadeusz Szeligowski'', Movement Music 1959\n#Podhajski, Marek; ''Tadeusz Szeligowski: counterpoint studies with Nadia Boulanger'', Res Fact No. 8, PWM, Krak\u00f3w 1977\n#Szantruczek, Tadeusz; ''Compose... and die. The thing about Tadeusz Szeligowski'', Ars Nova, Poznan 1997\n#Szeligowski, Tadeusz; (biography), in: ''Encyclopedia of Music'', ed. by A. Chodkowski, OWN, Warsaw 2001, p.&nbsp;866\n#Szeligowski, Tadeusz; (biography), in: M. Hanuszewska B. Schaeffer, ''Polish Almanac of contemporary composers'', PWM, Krak\u00f3w 1982, p.&nbsp;263-265\n#Szeligowski, Tadeusz; Stud''ies and Memories'', edited by F. Wozniak, [[Pomerania]], [[Bydgoszcz]] 1987\n#Szeligowski, Tadeusz; ''Around the author and his works'', ed. by T. Brodniewicz, J. Kempinski, J. Tatar, Ars Nova, Poznan 1998\n#Szeligowski, Tadeusz; ''The 10th anniversary of the composer's death, the materials of the scientific session'', Academy of Music, [[Gda\u0144sk]] 1973\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*''This article is based on the translation of the corresponding article on the Polish Wikipedia. A list of all contributors can be found there at the'' [http://pl.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Tadeusz_Szeligowski&action=history History] ''section''.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons-inline|File:Pozna\u0144 Che\u0142mo\u0144skiego 22.JPG|Tadeusz Szeligowski}}\n*[http://posm2.poznan.pl The Poznan School of Music] {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szeligowski, Tadeusz}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Composers for piano]]\n[[Category:Fryderyk Chopin University of Music faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Lviv]]\n[[Category:Polish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Polish male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Polish classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Polish classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Polish Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Male pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name = Tadeusz Szeligowski\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image = Tadeusz Szeligowski.jpg\n| caption = Szeligowski, circa 1953\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1896|09|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lemberg]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1963|01|10|1896|09|13|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Pozna\u0144]], [[Poland]]\n| death_cause =\n| resting_place = Pozna\u0144 Skalka crypt of Merit\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments =\n| residence =\n| nationality = Polish\n| other_names =\n| education =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = Composer, music professor, pianist and music writer\n| years_active =\n| employer = {{Lang|pl|Pa\u0144stwowa Wyzsza Szko\u0142a Muzyczna}}\n| organization =\n| agent =\n| known_for =\n| notable_works = {{Unbulleted list| The peacock and the girl | Sonata for flute and piano }}\n| style =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| home_town =\n| television =\n| religion =\n| spouse =\n| partner =\n| children =\n| parents =\n| relatives =\n| awards =\n| website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Tadeusz Szeligowski''' (13 September 1896 - 10 January 1963) was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[composer]], [[educator]], [[lawyer]] and music organizer. His works include the operas ''The Rise of the Scholars'', ''Krakatuk'' and ''Theodor Gentlemen'', the ballets ''The Peacock and the Girl'' and ''Mazepa ballets'', two violin concertos, [[Chamber music|chamber]] and [[choral]] works.<ref name=Sokol>{{cite book|last=Sokol|first=Stanley S.|title=The Polish Biographical Dictionary|year=1992|publisher=Bolchazy-Carducci Publishers|isbn=0-86516-245-X|pages=[https://archive.org/details/polishbiographic00soko/page/397 397]|url=https://archive.org/details/polishbiographic00soko|url-access=registration|quote=Tadeusz Szeligowski.}}</ref>\n\nAs a music teacher, Szeligowski was very well established in [[Vilnius]], [[Lublin]], [[Pozna\u0144]] and [[Warsaw]]. He was also a respected [[music critic|music writer]] who frequently wrote for journals and magazines specialized in music such as the ''[[Kurier Wile\u0144ski]]'', ''[[Tygodnik Wile\u0144ski]]'', ''[[Muzyka]]'' and the ''[[Kurier Pozna\u0144ski]]''. His achievements include the creation of the [[Pozna\u0144 Philharmonic|Poznan\u00b4 Philharmonic]], where he served as its first director between the years 1947-1949, and the founding of the Pozna\u0144 Musical Spring, one of the most important festivals of contemporary music at the time.\n\n==Life and work==\n\n===Musical education===\nTadeusz Szeligowski was born on 13 September 1896 in [[Lemberg]], then in [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian]] [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]] and now in western [[Ukraine]]. Szeligowski\u2019s first music and piano teacher was his mother. Later he began studying music at the Conservatory of Music of the Polish Society in L'vov in the years 1910-1914, where he studied piano under the direction of [[Vilem Kurz]],<ref name=Naxos>{{cite web|last=Naxos|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski (1896-1963)|url=http://www.naxos.com/person/Tadeusz_Szeligowski/49322.htm|publisher=Naxos.com|accessdate=15 August 2011}}</ref> and then from 1918-1923 in [[Krak\u00f3w]], where he studied piano with H. Peters, and composition with [[Boles\u0142aw Wallek-Walewski]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Szeligowski Tadeusz|last=''Encyklopedia Muzyczna PWN|url=https://pl.wikisource.org/wiki/Encyklopedia_Muzyczna_PWM/Szeligowski_Tadeusz|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> Szeligowski's further education included [[musicology]] with [[Zdzis\u0142aw Jachimecki]] and law at the [[Jagiellonian University]] in Krak\u00f3w, where he received his [[doctorate]] in 1922. There he found work as [[repetiteur]] at the Krak\u00f3w Opera House, allowing him to become well acquainted with the opera repertoire.<ref name=Naxos/>\n\nHe complemented his studies in music in the years 1929-1931 in [[Paris]], where he met many composers of his time such as [[Sergei Prokofiev]], [[George Enesco]] and [[Arthur Honegger]]. There he studied composition with [[Nadia Boulanger]] and orchestration with [[Paul Dukas]].<ref name=\"Le Nart\">{{cite web|last=Le Nart|first=Agnieszka|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski|url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-music-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/tadeusz-szeligowski|publisher=Adam Mickiewicz Institute (AMI)|accessdate=17 August 2011}}</ref> There he attended many concerts and intensely experienced the latest compositions by [[Darius Milhaud]], [[Francis Poulenc]], [[ballet]] productions of many famous companies, as well as highly acclaimed performances by [[Jascha Heifetz]], [[Vladimir Horowitz]], [[Arthur Rubinstein]] and [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]].<ref name=Naxos/>\n\n===Musical career===\nIn 1923 Szeligowski worked in Vilnius, [[Lithuania]] (then part of the [[Second Polish Republic]]), as lawyer and [[lecturer]] at the Conservatory of Music. There he met [[Karol Szymanowski]] and became a great admirer of his music. He also worked with a dramatic theatre called Reduta, composing music for many of its productions.<ref name=Naxos/> Shortly after his return to Poland in 1931,<ref name=Naxos/><ref>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Adrian|title=Polish music since Szymanowski|year=2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-58284-9|pages=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XT-ReqNMSx0C&pg=PA10&dq=Tadeusz+Szeligowski&hl=en&ei=MGpJTsP7FIe18QPzsez8Ag&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-preview-link&resnum=3&ved=0CDcQuwUwAjgK#v=onepage&q=Tadeusz%20Szeligowski&f=false}}</ref> he began teaching music in Pozna\u0144 until 1939, and then moved to Lublin for a little while after the [[World War II]].<ref name=Naxos/> From 1947-1962 he worked for The State Higher School Of Music ({{Lang|pl|Pa\u0144stwowa Wyzsza Szko\u0142a Muzyczna}}) in Pozna\u0144,<ref name=Sokol/> and from 1947-1950 he became director of the National Opera Academy, when on his own initiative the Pozna\u0144 [[Philharmonic]] was created.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rubin & Partners|title=Poznan Philharmonic Orchestra|url=http://www.pricerubin.com/classical/detail.php?SummaryNumber=6&detail=1|publisher=Price Rubin & Partners|accessdate=19 August 2011}}</ref> In addition, he was the initiator of the festival of contemporary music, the \"Pozna\u0144 Musical Spring\", where modern music was then presented in all its glory,<ref name=\"Le Nart\"/> and one of the organizers of the H. Wieniawski International Violin Competition.<ref name=Naxos/> From 1951-1962 Szeligowski worked in [[Warsaw]], first for the faculty of the [[Fryderyk Chopin University of Music in Warsaw|Fryderyk Chopin University of Music]] in Warsaw, and later as director of the Polish Society of Composers.<ref name=Naxos/>\n[[File:Poznan 10-2013 img07 Philharmony.jpg|thumb|[[Pozna\u0144 Philharmonic]]]]\nA large group of his graduates on composition include: [[Zbigniew Bargielski]], [[Augustyn Bloch]], [[Joanna Bruzdowicz]], [[Wojciech Lukaszewski]], [[Tadeusz Wojciech Maklakiewicz]], [[Boleslaw Ocias]], [[Witold Rudzinski]], [[Marek Sart]], [[Aleksander Szeligowski]] and [[Antoni Szuniewicz]]. {{See LMST|Tadeusz|Szeligowski}}\n\n===As a music writer===\nLvov\u2019s musical scene at that time included a city opera, a symphonic orchestra, a music society and also a conservatory of music, and there Szeligowski was very active as a social organizer. Musicians such as [[Felix Weingartner]] and [[Oscar Nedbal]] usually visited the city and frequently performed works by [[Giuseppe Verdi]] and [[Richard Wagner]]. From 1951-1954 he served as chairman of the Polish Composers Union, and from 1953 he worked for the Board of Polish Music Publishers and the Central Pedagogical Office for Arts Education (COPSA).<ref  name=\"Mrygo\u0144\">{{cite web|last=Mrygo\u0144|first=Adam|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski (1896-1963)|url=http://www.pwm.com.pl/szczegoly.php?&Szeligowski_Tadeusz&aukcja=0&grupa_p=6&grp=&pwd%5B6%5D=224404&sortuj=sattr_83&grupuj=&przedm=283381&strona=2&change_lang=1&change_skin=103374|work=Encyklopedia Muzyczna PWM, vol. 10|publisher=Polish Widawnictwo Muzycne SA|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> Tadeusz Szeligowski died in Pozna\u0144 on 10 January 1963 and since 1965 he has been buried in the Pozna\u0144 Skalka crypt of Merit.<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\"/>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Szeligowski.JPG|thumb|right|160px|J\u00f3zef Kopczy\u0144ski's 1966 commemorative plaque for Polish composer Tadeusz Szeligowski.]]\nSzeligowski received numerous awards, among them:\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1949}}|event= Third prize at the Second [[Chopin]] Composition Competition for his Piano Sonata in D minor<ref name=\"Polish Culture\">{{cite web|last=Polish Culture|title=Tadeusz Szeligowski|url=http://www.culture.pl/web/english/resources-music-full-page/-/eo_event_asset_publisher/eAN5/content/tadeusz-szeligowski|publisher=Culture.pl|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1949}}|event= Second prize at the [[Polskie Radio|Polish Radio]] Competition for the song ''The Prince and the girl''<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1950}}|event= State prize of the second degree for ''The peacock and the girl'', ''Arion'', and the ''Lublin Wedding''<ref name=\"Le Nart\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1951}}|event= State prize of the first degree for the opera stage ''Rise of the scholars''<ref name=\"Le Nart\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1963}}|event= Prize Prime Minister of Poland for his music for children and youth<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1963}}|event= Music Award of the PCU, awarded every 17 January by the Polish Composers Union (ZKP \u2014 ''Zwiazek Kompozytorow Polskich'') for lifetime achievement (posthumous)<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\">{{cite web|last=ZKP|title=PCU Award|url=http://www.zkp.org.pl/nagroda.php?lang=en|work=Laureaci Nagrody ZKP|publisher=Polish Composers\u2019 Union|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> }}\n\nAlso, he received numerous prizes and awards, including:\n* The City of [[Pozna\u0144]] Music Prize{{when|date=October 2011}}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1952}}|event= Gold [[Cross of Merit (Poland)|Cross of Merit]] (''Z\u0141OTYM KRZYZEM ZAS\u0141UGI'')<ref>{{cite web|last=Monitor Polski|title=Order of the Prezident of the Republic - 1078|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:hVXWgzTheK0J:monitorpolski.gov.pl/M1952070107801.pdf+monitorpolski.gov.pl/M1952070107801.pdf&hl=cs&gl=cz&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESih0ko2ugXfFIv2aDLCQZNMiTFnUx59ScIbWw08-c9c1cajINyJ77TVbBlhgHlsBmGhKWkMrICygOvs4sgIe8GF3Ook7VdTBDCDQqBTx9muunKczW25E0awP5CMRgrWZ6O0KY2Z&sig=AHIEtbQGPhF-h-_b8MCqBLLtag__LHtw3Q|work=Granting State Awards on 22 July 1952|publisher=Monitor Polski.gov.pl|accessdate=18 August 2011|language=pl}}</ref> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1952}}|event= Medal [[Order of Polonia Restituta]]<ref name=\"Mrygo\u0144\"/> }}\n* {{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1966}}|event= A commemorative plaque designed by J\u00f3zef Kopczy\u0144ski and placed at House 22, Che\u0142mo\u0144ski street, in Pozna\u0144, where he lived from 1947.}}\n\n==Compositions==\n\n{{Cleanup lang|date=October 2011}}\n\n===Instrumental===\n\n====Orchestral works====\n*''The Peasant King'' - [[Overture]] to the comedy of [[Piotr Baryka]] for orchestra (1926)\n*''Kaziuki - St. Casimir's Day,'' [[suite (music)|suite]] for orchestra (1928\u201329)\n*''Concerto'' for Orchestra (1930)\n*''Archaic Suite'' for orchestra (1930)\n*''Little Suite'' for orchestra (1931)\n*''Clarinet Concerto'' (1933)\n*''Andante'' for clarinet and orchestra (1933)\n*''Blue Bird'' - suite for orchestra (1936)\n*''[[Epitaph]] on the death of [[Karol Szymanowski]]'' for string orchestra (1937)\n*''Carol Suite'' for string orchestra (1939)\n*''Piano Concerto'' (1941)\n*''Suite'' for small orchestra of Lublin (1945)\n*''Kupa\u0142owa night'' - suite for orchestra (1945)\n*''Nocturno'' for orchestra (1947)\n*''Comedy Overture'' for small symphony orchestra (1952)\n*''The peacock and girl'' ballet suite for orchestra (1953)\n*''Four Polish Dances'' for symphony orchestra (1954)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====Chamber music====\n[[File:Sonata Tadeusz Szeligowski.jpg|thumb|right|220px|A musical score of Tadeusz Szeligowski's ''Sonata for flute and piano''.]]\n*''Lithuanian Song'' for violin and piano (1928)\n*''String Quartet'' No. 1 (1928\u201329)\n*''[[Ricercar]]'' for 4 voices, instrumental or vocal (1931)\n*''String Quartet'' No. 2 (1934-1935)\n*''Trio'' for oboe, viola and cello (1935)\n*''Fish ball'', song for children's team (1937)\n*''Air grave et gai air'' for English horn and piano (1940)\n*''Nocturno'' for cello and piano (1943)\n*''Dance'' for cello and piano (1943\u201345)\n*''Poem'' for cello and piano (1943\u201345)\n*''Pastorale'' for cello and organ (1943\u201345)\n*''[[Sarabande]]'' for cello and organ (1943\u201345)\n*''Orientale'' for Cello and Piano (1945)\n*''Quintet'' for wind instruments (1953)\n*''Sonata'' for flute and piano (1953)\n*''On the meadow'', suite for 2 pianos (1955)\n*''Trio'' for violin, cello and piano (1955-1956)\n*''Polish love songs'' for recorders (1959)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====Solos (Pianoforte)====\n*''Variations on a folk song'' for piano (1927)\n*''Guitars of Zalamea'', for piano (1938\u201339)\n*''Sonatina'' for piano (1940\u201341)\n*''Russian Dance'', for piano (1942)\n*''Sonata'' in d minor for piano (1949)\n*''Two etudes on double sounds'' for piano (1952)\n*''Small pieces'' for piano (1952)\n*''Odds and ends for four hands'', for piano (1952)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n===Vocal Score===\n\n====For solo voices====\n*''Nos qui sumus'' - ''motet'' for two male voices (1929)\n*''O vos omnes'' - motet for three female voices (1929)\n*''Timor et tremor'' - motet for [[contralto]] and [[tenor]] (1929)\n*''Missa de Angelis'' for 3 female voices (1942)\n*''[[Ave Maria]]'' for three female voices (1943 )\n*''[[Regina Coeli|Regina Coeli Laetare]]'' for 3 female voices (1943)\n*''Populations meus'' for 3 female voices (1943)\n*''Veni Creator'' for 3 female voices (1943)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====For choir a cappella====\n*''Two [[Belarus]]ian songs'' for mixed choir (1930)\n*''Under the canopy of snow'' - Christmas carol for mixed choir (1933\u201334)\n*''Angela sang sweetly'' - motet for mixed choir (1934)\n*''Quail'' - Belarusian folk song for male choir (1934)\n*''Regina Coeli Laetare'' for mixed choir (1934)\n*''Already we have time'' for male choir (1935)\n*''Song of the sailors'', for mixed choir (1938)\n*''[[Psalm]] Joyful in memoriam of [[Guillaume Dufay]]'' for mixed choir (1938)\n*''[[Mass (music)|Mass]]'' for choir (1942)\n*''[[Stabat Mater]]'' for mixed choir (1943)\n*''[[Pange Lingua Gloriosi Corporis Mysterium|Pange lingua]]'' in mixed choir (1943)\n*''Five folk songs from Lublin region'' for choir female or child (1945)\n*''Five folk songs from the Lublin region'' for 3 mixed choir (1945)\n*''Four wedding songs from the Lublin region'' for mixed choir (1945)\n*''Koszalka - Opa\u0142ka'', [[scherzo]] for male choir (1946)\n*''A wyjrzyjcie\u017c'', youths, song for mixed choir (1948)\n*''Song of the 10th anniversary'' [version II] for mixed choir a cappella (1955)\n*''Psalm CXVI \"Laudate Dominum\"'' for mixed choir and boys' (1960)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n===Vocal and instrumental===\n\n====For voice and piano====\n*''Wanda'', song for voice and piano (1927)\n*''Lithuanian folk songs'' for voice and piano (1927)\n*''Song of the green'' for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Lilies'' - [[ballad]] for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Oaks'' - [[elegy]] for voice and piano (1929)\n*''In alder'' - [[idyll]] for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Hops'' - wedding song for voice and piano (1929)\n*''Floral allegories'' for voice and piano (1934)\n*''Songs to the words of [[Jaros\u0142aw Iwaszkiewicz]]'' for voice and piano (1945)\n*''Green brz\u00f3zko'', song for voice and piano (1947)\n*''My Girl'', song for voice and piano (1947)\n*''The Rose Highway'', song for voice and piano (1947)\n*''[[Arion]]'' for tenor and piano (1949)\n*''[[Demon]]'' for tenor and piano (1949)\n*''[[Doves]]'' for soprano and piano (1949)\n*''The Ballad of [[Aleksander Kostka Napierski|Kostka Napierski]]'' for voice and piano (1951)\n*''With three Mauretankach'', [[song]] for voice and piano (1953)\n*''Soledad'' for voice and piano (1960)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n====For various vocal and instrumental ensembles====\n*''Psalm XVI'' - [[oratorio]] (1931)\n*''Latin Mass'' for mixed choir and [[organ (music)|organ]] (1932)\n*''Cherry Blues'' for [[voice]], [[cello]] and piano (1934)\n*''Ave Maria'' for [[soprano]], female choir and organ (1943)\n*''[[Aria]]'' for soprano and organ (1943)\n*''Sit down everybody around us'', suite 12 popular songs from the years 1810 to 1875 for mixed choir (or soprano and alto) and piano (1945)\n*''[[Triptych]]'' for soprano and orchestra (1946)\n*''[[Cantata]] for sport \"100 m\"'' for solo voice, choir and orchestra (1948)\n*''Wedding [[Suite (music)|Suite]]'' for [[soprano]], [[tenor]], female chorus, mixed chorus and piano (1948)\n*''Wedding in Lublin'' for soprano, mixed choir and small orchestra (1948)\n*''The young master and a girl'', musical dialogue for soprano, [[baritone]], mixed choir and orchestra or piano (1948-1949)\n*''[[Rhapsody (music)|Rhapsody]]'' for soprano and orchestra (1949)\n*''Of hearts card'', cantata for soprano, mixed choir and symphony orchestra (1952)\n*''Sophie'', suite for choir and orchestra (1952)\n*''Renegade'', ballad for bass and orchestra or piano (1953)\n*''Song of the 10th anniversary'' [version] for choir<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/>\n\n===Stage works===\n*''The peacock and the girl'', [[ballet]] in 3 acts (1948)\n*''Bunt \u017cak\u00f3w'' (Student Rebellion), [[opera]] in 4 acts (1951)\n*''Krakatuk'', opera in 3 acts with a prologue (1954)\n*''[[Ivan Mazepa|Mazepa]]'', ballet in 3 acts (1958)<ref name=\"Polish Culture\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Magocsi|first=Paul Robert|title=A history of Ukraine|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=0-8020-7820-6|pages=240|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t124cP06gg0C&pg=PA240&dq=Tadeusz+Szeligowski&hl=en&ei=Y3ZJTpyxDMip8APN-dSZBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-preview-link&resnum=5&ved=0CDsQuwUwBDge#v=onepage&q=Tadeusz%20Szeligowski&f=false}}</ref>\n*''Theodore Gentleman'', opera in 2 acts ( 1960)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Classical music]]\n*[[Contemporary classical music|Modern music]]\n*[[Romantic composers]]\n*[[Neoclassicism#In music|Neoclassicism]]\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n#Zofia, Lissa; ''Rise of scholars'', Tadeusz Szeligowski, PWM, Krak\u00f3w 1957\n#Rozmowy ''\"Movement Music\". Says Tadeusz Szeligowski'', Movement Music 1959\n#Podhajski, Marek; ''Tadeusz Szeligowski: counterpoint studies with Nadia Boulanger'', Res Fact No. 8, PWM, Krak\u00f3w 1977\n#Szantruczek, Tadeusz; ''Compose... and die. 